<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, March 11 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi Annan begins his
two-day visit to Washington Wednesday and is expected to defend
his deal with Iraq on weapons inspection and ask the U.S. to pay
its dues to the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Annan will meet U.S. President Bill Clinton at noon Wednesday
at the White House, where he is to have a working lunch with the
president's national security adviser, Sandy Berger.
</P>
<P>
The secretary-general is also expected to meet with Secretary
of State Madeleine Albright in the afternoon and Defense Secretary
William Cohen on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The focus during the meetings will be the deal on Iraqi weapons
inspection Annan signed on February 23 in Baghdad with the Iraqi
authorities. U.N. spokesman Fred Eckhard said on Tuesday Annan
would be "seeking political support" for the agreement.
(US-Annan-Visit)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- Two companies of Iraq and Iran have signed a
contract for organizing the visits of Iranians to the holy places
in Iraq, the Iraqi News Agency (INA) reported Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The contract, the first of its kind in 18 years, was signed
here late Tuesday night between the Al-Hodda Company for Religious
Tourism of Iraq and the Morning Breeze Company of Iran. It
includes items dealing with how Iranians are to be accommodated
and carried to the holy places in Iraq. (Iraq-Iran-Pilgrims)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- A senior official of the Bank of Japan (BOJ), Japan's
central bank, was arrested Wednesday on suspicion of taking 4.3
million yen (33,858 U.S. dollars) in bribes from two major banks.
</P>
<P>
Yasuyuki Yoshizawa, head of the Capital Markets Division of
BOJ's Credit and Market Management Department, is suspected of
receiving the bribes in the form of entertainment, mainly through
wining, dining and golf outings, over four years since May 1993.
</P>
<P>
Several former or incumbent finance ministry officials have
already been arrested on suspicion of being wined and dined, but
it is the first time that a BOJ official has been arrested since
the central bank was established in 1882.
</P>
<P>
Officials at the Tokyo District Public Prosecutors Office said
Yoshizawa, in exchange, leaked information relating to the central
bank's market operations and its lending policy to the Industrial
Bank of Japan (IBJ) and Sanwa Bank. (Japan-BOJ-Bribery)
</P>
<P>
- - -
</P>
<P>
JERUSALEM -- Clashes between Palestinian protesters and
Israeli soldiers in Hebron area continued Wednesday following the
killing of three Palestinians Tuesday evening.
</P>
<P>
The clashes centered in Dura, west of Hebron, and Hebron's
center, where Palestinian youths threw stones and petrol bombs
and burned tires. Israeli soldiers fired rubber bullets and tear
gas in response. Palestinian sources said at least 14 Palestinian
protesters were wounded, 11 from Dura and three in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
A large presence of Israeli troops were deployed in Dura to
prevent more rioting and Palestinian policemen were also sent to
calm the tension.
</P>
<P>
The head of Israeli Army's Central Command Uzi Dayan held an
emergency meeting Wednesday morning with Palestinian police
officials to discuss ways to calm the situation.
(Israel-Palestine-Clashes) 
</P>
</TEXT>
