<HEADLINE> Japan Provides Extra Donation for Mongolia </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ULAN BATOR, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Japan, Mongolia's leading
benefactor, provided its seventh unplanned free assistance package
to Mongolia Wednesday, which is worth 2.5 billion Yen (19.7
million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
The exchange of notes on the donation was signed here by
Mongolian Minister of External Relations Shukher Altangerel and
Japanese Ambassador to Mongolia Kubota, the Mongolian News Agency
(MNA) reported.
</P>
<P>
The donation, which is to be used largely for the purchase of
Japanese-manufactured diesel generators for 79 Japanese-aided
counties, amounts to a sum equal to eight percent of Mongolia's
state budget for 1998.
</P>
<P>
Japan has given free aid to Mongolia seven times since 1991.
The previous gifts exceeded 80 million dollars.
</P>
<P>
Since the early 1990s, Japan has offered nearly 600 million
dollars in aid and loans to the inland Asian nation, accounting
for about a third of the aid promised by foreign countries and
international organizations. 
</P>
</TEXT>
