<BODY>
<HEADLINE> British Official Visits Albania on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA, March 11 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Office Minister of
State Tony Lloyd made a flash visit to Albania Wednesday on Kosovo
business.
</P>
<P>
Lloyd briefed Albanian Foreign Minister Paskal Milo on Monday's
emergency meeting in London of the Contact Group on former
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement after the London meeting, the Contact
Group, comprising the United States, Russia, Britain, France,
Germany and Italy, asked the United Nations Security Council for
an arms embargo against Yugoslavia, and called for a peaceful
solution to the troubles through dialogue.
</P>
<P>
Milo elaborated on Albania's position on the Kosovo issue.
</P>
<P>
The situations at the Albanian-Yugoslav border, Albania's
defense preparations and the political situation in Albania were
also discussed in the meeting between Lloyd and Milo.
</P>
<P>
Lloyd, at a news conference after the meeting, hailed the
Albanian government's identical position on the Kosovo issue with
the Contact Group.
</P>
<P>
The Contact Group and the international community were waiting
for a reply to the London statement from Yugoslav authorities,
said Lloyd.
</P>
<P>
Should its demands be refused by Belgrade, the Contact Group
would take new measures against Yugoslavia, said Lloyd.
</P>
<P>
Lloyd flew on to Macedonia and Yugoslavia on the same mission
after the news conference. 
</P>
</TEXT>
