<HEADLINE> UAE President Calls for Lifting Sanctions </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ABU DHABI, March 11 (Xinhua) -- United Arab Emirates (UAE)
President Sheikh Zayed bin Sultan al Nahyan Wednesday urged the
international community to lift economic sanctions against Iraq to
end the sufferings of the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
The UAE president said he hoped to "remove the darkness
covering the Iraqi people who should not be responsible for the
sanctions," the UAE's official Wam news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
He made the remarks during his talks with al Akhder al
Ibrahimi, visiting adviser of U.N. Secretary General Kofi Annan,
the agency said.
</P>
<P>
The UAE has repeatedly called for the lifting of the economic
sanctions against Baghdad imposed by the United Nations since
1990 after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
Abu Dhabi said late last month that the issue was the "next
step" on which the international community should focus its
efforts after the U.N. peacefully defused a crisis with Iraq on
arms inspections.
</P>
<P>
Iraq has said that in the past seven years, hundreds of
thousands of Iraqi women and children have died for lack of food
and medicines caused by the U.N. sanctions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
