<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Exempts Vietnam from Trade Restriction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton has
exempted Vietnam from a Cold War law that restricts trade
because of limit emigration, the White House said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The president based his decision on Vietnam's track record
of progress on emigration over the past 15 years and its
accelerated efforts in recent months," the White House said in a
statement.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said on Tuesday that Clinton signed a waiver
to the so-called Jackson-Vanik amendment, which prevents the
U.S. government from giving trade and investment funding to
nations that do not allow their citizens to emigrate or travel
abroad freely.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's decision will make Vietnam eligible for financial
backing from the U.S. Export-Import Bank and the Overseas Private
Investment Corp, but does not grant it the Most Favored Nation
trade status. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0010 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ICRISAT to Expand Its Sorghum/Millet Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 11 (Xinhua) -- The India-based International
Crop Research Institute for the Semi-Arid Tropics (ICRISAT) will,
beginning in September next year, transform the sorghum and
millet improvement program (SMIP) centered in Zimbabwe into a
network (SMINET).
</P>
<P>
ICRISAT director-general Shawki Barghouti Wednesday told the
Zimbabwe News Agency in Bulawayo, the country's second largest
city, that the change would necessitate the expansion of the
program to add other drought-resistant crops considered suitable
for southern Africa's arid and dry weather conditions.
</P>
<P>
Since its inception in 1984, the SMIP southern Africa region
center in Matopos, west Zimbabwe, researched and developed hybrid
varieties of sorghum and millet, but SMINET would also look at
groundnuts, pigeonpeas, chickpeas, pearl millet and other crop
varieties which are expected to improve food availability in the
region.
</P>
<P>
"SMINET will also carry out research in natural resource
management, soil and water conservation as well as modern and
sustainable methods of farming that preserve natural assets,"
Barghouti said.
</P>
<P>
"More scientists will be brought in to carry out research and
promote new crops and farming concepts at national level in all
the 14 Southern African Development Community (SADC) countries,"
he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
