<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zambian Villagers Call for Control of Elephants </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUSAKA, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Villagers in southern Zambia
urged Wednesday the country's department of wildlife to control
elephants which are destroying their maize fields.
</P>
<P>
Mukuni ward councillor Eddie Singongi said in Livingstone on
half of the villagers in Mukuni area that the villagers are
concerned at the destruction of their crops and demand
compensation from the wildlife department.
</P>
<P>
"For the past few years elephants have been destroying our
crops. This time the elephants are back destroying our maize
fields, now we are demanding compensation because we shall
starve," Singongi said.
</P>
<P>
He said in the past the department of wildlife has always told
them that the elephants were international animals and Zambia
alone had no power to crop them.
</P>
<P>
But the villagers have put up another option in their request
that Mukuni village be made part of the Musi-Oa-Tunya park in
order to benefit from the proceeds realized from the sale of
government trophies and tourism in general for they live in the
same neighborhood with wildlife.
</P>
<P>
"We are faced with a predicament as our sweat and toil has
been wasted because we are not getting any spin-offs from the
elephants.
</P>
<P>
Another option of electrical fencing to deter the animals from
crossing to destroy crops was proposed though unpracticable.
</P>
<P>
The villagers have also requested for relief food saying that
they have no alternative but to turn to the government for
handouts to survive. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
