<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0013 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ILO Governing Body to Decide on Possible Declaration </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 11 (Xinhua) -- The governing body of the
International Labor Organization (ILO) will make decisions on a
possible declaration on fundamental rights and elect a new ILO
director-general when it holds its 271st plenary session here on
March 23-27.
</P>
<P>
The declaration will be submitted to the next session of the
International Labor Conference in June 1998, the ILO said in a
press release Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Current ILO Director-General Michel Hansenne described the
declaration under discussion and an appropriate follow-up
mechanism as "the most significant endeavor for ensuring respect
for fundamental ILO standards since the adoption in 1945 of the
Declaration of Philadelphia".
</P>
<P>
He believed that the draft declaration would be central to
fulfilling the increasing hopes and expectations placed on the ILO
by the international community, notably in the aftermath of the
United Nations' World Summit for Social Development in Copenhagen
in 1995.
</P>
<P>
Beginning on March 12, the various committees of the ILO
governing body will examine such issues as freedom of association,
discrimination in employment and occupation and the future of ILO
technical cooperation programs to eliminate child labor, enhance
employment opportunities for women and combat poverty and social
exclusion, said the ILO.
</P>
<P>
Hansenne was elected ILO Director-General in 1989 and
re-elected to a second five-year term of office in 1994. His
current term expires in March 1999.
</P>
<P>
Two candidates for the election of the new director-general are
Ms Maria Nieves Roldan-Confesor of the Philippines and Mr Juan
Somavia of Chile, both submitted by their respective governments.
</P>
<P>
The voting will take place on March 23 by secret ballot. A
candidate receiving more than one-half of the 56 votes will win.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
