<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UNITA Admitted As Political Party in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 11 (Xinhua) -- The Angolan government issued a
declaration here on Wednesday, acknowledging the National Union
for the Total Independence of Angola (UNITA) as a legitimate
political party in the country.
</P>
<P>
The declaration also lifts the restriction on UNITA's
political and party activities within the national territory.
</P>
<P>
According to the declaration issued at the end of the standing
committee meeting of Angolan ministers, UNITA announced its
accomplishment of total demilitarization last Friday, based on
which the government made the decision.
</P>
<P>
The Lusaka Peace Accord signed by Angola's warring parties in
November 1994, requires for UNITA's complete demilitarization to
become a political party and operate in line with the
constitution, especially the Political Party Act.
</P>
<P>
The declaration further announced that the government will
allow UNITA to be engaged in political activities under the new
agenda set by the joint committee for the peace process on March
6.
</P>
<P>
UNITA was the second large party and the biggest opposition
party in Angola. After the country's first multi-party elections
at the end of 1992, UNITA refused to take the election results,
accusing the government of fraud, therefore once again took up
arms and started the civil war. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
