<HEADLINE> Indonesian Vice President-elect Pledges to Push </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JAKARTA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Indonesia's newly elected vice
president B.J. Habibie here Wednesday evening pledged to carry out
industrialization in the country by relying national power on
renewable human resources.
</P>
<P>
The vice president made the statement at his swearing in
ceremony held before the members of the People's Consultative
Assembly (MPR) who were attending the five-yearly general session.
</P>
<P>
Habibie, who has been State Minister of Research and Technology
since 1978, was elected as vice president for 1998-2003 period
earlier Wednesday by the MPR, the highest legislative body.
</P>
<P>
"I am ready to assist and associate with the president in
carrying out state duties and development endeavors of our nation
in the run up to the 21st century, the era of globalization and
technology, to meet the expectation of the whole of the Indonesian
people," he noted.
</P>
<P>
He said the industrialization is aimed at realizing a modern
and self-reliant national industry, that relies on a strong
agricultural sector and utilizes, develops and masters both
science and technology in order to stimulate an increasing
self-supporting and highly competitive national life.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the MPR Chairman Harmoko, who chaired the conclusion
meeting of general session, said the 11-day session has succeeded
in producing several decisions and decrees including endorsing the
State Policy Guideline for the next five year, electing a
president and a vice president.
</P>
<P>
The 1998 State Policy Guidelines will be carried out earnestly
by the president who shall lead the nation in the run-up to the
21st century in the third millennium, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Harmoko, who is also speaker of the House of Representatives
(parliament), quoted president Soeharto as saying that in the new
century the Indonesian people will face with more difficult and
complex new challenges.
</P>
<P>
On the current economic and monetary crisis which has hit the
country since July last year, he expressed the hope that the
president and vice president will immediately take the steps to
overcome it.
</P>
<P>
"The Assembly strongly believes that the president shall not
hesitate for a moment to take the necessary steps to safe the
people and weather the storms," he stressed.
</P>
<P>
Harmoko held that international cooperation and assistance is
important, but it is more important to rely on the nation's
strength and confidence.
</P>
<P>
The MPR, which was attended by 1,000 members from five factions
-- the ruling Golkar party, the Armed Forces, the regional
representatives, the United Development Party (PPP) and the
Indonesian Democratic Party (PDI), -- had reelected the incumbent
president Soeharto to his seventh term of office on Tuesday.
</P>
