<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0019 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South Africa to Spend More on Social Services, </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 11 (Xinhua) -- South African Finance
Minister Trevor Manuel on Wednesday announced in Cape Town a
budget for 1998/99 in parliament, stressing to increase spending
on social services, police, justice and correctional services.
</P>
<P>
Unveiling the 201-billion Rand (40.2 billion U.S. Dollars)
budget, Manuel said the budgets for police, justice and
correctional services have received a 12 percent increase and
will tatal 20.7 billion Rand (4.1 billion Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Health services will receive 14 percent of the budget (4.6
billion Dollars), education 28 percent (9 billion Dollars), while
spending on housing would remain above 3.5 billion Rand (700
million dollars).
</P>
<P>
Capital spending on water schemes and related infrastructure
would be 1.6 billion Rand (320 million Dollars) in 1998/99, and
rise to 1.8 billion Rand (360 million Dollars) in 2001.
</P>
<P>
The allocation to poverty relief projects will rise from 500
million Rand (100 million Dollars) in 1997/98 to 800 million Rand
(160 million Dollars) in 2001.
</P>
<P>
Education spending would grow from 45 billion Rand (nine
billion Dollars) in 1997/98 to more than 50 billion Rand (10
billion Dollars) over the next three years.
</P>
<P>
Manuel said the government expected investment growth to
strengthen in the rest of 1998 and further into 1999 and remained
confident that a Gross Domestic Product (GDP) of three percent
would be achieved.
</P>
<P>
Last year, South Africa's GDP was registered at 1.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
The South African government's projection was that inflation
would fall to around five percent by the year 2000. The current
inflation rate in South Africa is 5.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
The new budget showed that tax cuts worth 3.7 billion Rand
(740 million Dollars) for middle income taxpayers, but smokers,
drinkers and motorists will cough up more to help balance the
books.
</P>
<P>
The fuel levy on petrol and diesel would increase by 10 cents
a liter from next month. Excise duties on cigarettes has been
raised by 29 percent and a packet of 20 cigarettes would now cost
46 cents extra. Pipe tobacco will cost an extra 2.11 Rand (40
cents) per kilogram.
</P>
<P>
The South African government would place 3.7 billion Rand back
into the taxpayer's pocket by eliminating some of the effects of
tax bracket creep.
</P>
<P>
This means that a person under the age of 65 and earns 25,000
Rand (5,000 Dollars) per year will pay 300 Rand (60 Dollars) less
tax per year, a 20 percent reduction in liability.
</P>
<P>
Value-Added Tax will remain unchanged at 14 percent.
</P>
<P>
In releasing his first budget under the Medium Term
Expenditure Framework, which allows the government to present
spending plans for the next three years, Manuel also announced
the establishment of a special fund to create jobs. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
