<HEADLINE> Cholera Spreads to Half of Mozambican Provinces </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MAPUTO, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Avertino Barreto, assistant
director of the National Health Bureau, announced here Wednesday
that a total of 51 cholera cases were reported in Zambezia
province in central Mozambique within the past 24 hours,
fortunately with no death.
</P>
<P>
This is the first discovery of cholera in the province since
its outbreak last August. So far, six of the country's 10
provinces in the central and southern part have been hit by the
epidemic.
</P>
<P>
Disclosing the news at a press conference, Barreto said the
government had taken up measures to contain the disease. Special
clinics have been set up in Sofala province to receive cholera
patients, with trained professionals.
</P>
<P>
Zambezia province has reportedly blood serum stock of 45,000
liters, and will soon receive 80,000 liters more from the capital
Maputo.
</P>
<P>
To date, 570 people have died of the epidemic in Mozambique,
with 22,429 people affected.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Barreto revealed that about 450,000 to 50,000 people
in Mozambique are cholera-virus carriers, who might suffer the
disease within months or a year.
</P>
<P>
But he added that the health authorities have been ready for
it. 
</P>
</TEXT>
