<HEADLINE> Russian Envoy to Visit Cyprus </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NICOSIA, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Russian envoy Vladimir Tchizhov
will visit Cyprus early April to review the latest development of
the Cyprus issue, a senior Russian diplomat announced here
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters after a meeting with Interior Minister
Dinos Michaelides, Russian Ambassador to Cyprus Georgi Mouradov
said Tchizhov will visit Cyprus within the framework of Russia's
interest to back efforts to solve the Cyprus problem.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on threats by Turkish Cypriot leader Rauf Denktash
that he will not participate in peace talks, Mouradov said his
country favors the continuation of the dialog between the two
communities of Cyprus. "This is the only way to find a fair
solution," he added.
</P>
<P>
Two rounds of U.N.-led peace talks between the two Cypriot
communities' leaders were held last summer, which failed because
of Denktash's refusal to negotiate after the European Union
decided to open accession talks with Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Mouradov pointed out that "U.N. Security Council and General
Assembly resolutions should be implemented, as well as the two
high level agreements between the two communities."
</P>
<P>
He described the agreements of 1977 and 1979 reached between
the leaders of the two Cypriot communities, providing for a
bizonal, bicommunal federation, as the basis of a solution in
Cyprus.
</P>
<P>
Referring to press reports that the U.S. is exerting pressure
on the Cypriot government to postpone the deployment of the
surface-to-air missile system S-300 it ordered from Russia,
Mouradov said the deal is legal in all aspects.
</P>
<P>
He said Cyprus needs this defense system and this is why no
pressure should be exerted and there should be no third party's
involvement in the matter.
</P>
<P>
The Russian-made S-300 missiles were ordered by the Cypriot
government in January 1997 and they are expected to be deployed on
the island later this year.
</P>
<P>
Turkey has threatened to strike the missiles if they are
deployed on the island.
</P>
<P>
This East Mediterranean island has been divided since 1974
when Turkey landed its troops and took over the northern third
of the island following a failed pro-Athens coup in Nicosia.
</P>
</TEXT>
