<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EU Proposes Random Road Checks to Enhance Safety </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BRUSSELS, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Heavy truck drivers in European
Union countries may soon expect to be stopped and have their
vehicles checked by roadside as a move to enhance road safety and
air quality.
</P>
<P>
The move, proposed on Wednesday by the European Commission,
requires EU member states to supplement their annual
roadworthiness test on commercial vehicles, heavy goods vehicles
in particular, with random roadside inspections.
</P>
<P>
Commission officials said that recent surveys indicated that
the annual routine inspection on commercial vehicles does not
guarantee an acceptance standard of maintenance throughout the
year.
</P>
<P>
Immediate action is needed, therefore, to improve road safety
as the road haulage market is to become fully liberalized on July
1, this year.
</P>
<P>
Heavy goods vehicles already cause around 20 percent of the
annual deaths of 45,000 people on the roads of the European Union,
according to official figures.
</P>
<P>
Air quality is also needed to improve so as to create the
conditions of fair competition by ensuring that all vehicles are
maintained to similar standards.
</P>
<P>
"This will discourage irresponsible operators from trying to
cut costs by operating vehicles so poorly-maintained that they
threaten the life of other road users and damage the environment,"
said Neil Kinnock, European commissioner in charge of transport
policy.
</P>
<P>
Commission officials argued that for many of the heaviest
vehicles travelling some 150,000 kilometers a year, an annual
inspection is unlikely to provide sufficient guarantee that
commercial vehicles operating on EU territory do so with an
acceptance standard of maintenance throughout the year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics showed that two-thirds of the serious defects that
contribute to causes of accidents or fatalities on EU highways
concerned defective brakes resulting from lack of proper
maintenance.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that a correctly maintained fleet of heavy
goods vehicles saves 2 percent of fuel consumption and an
equivalent proportion of carbon dioxide emissions. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0033 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Israeli Inner Cabinet Discusses S. Lebanese </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Israeli inner security Cabinet
convened Wednesday to discuss the idea of unilateral withdrawal
from South Lebanon, where Israel is bogged down in a tough
guerrilla war.
</P>
<P>
The meeting was chaired by Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu
and attended by Defense Minister Yithzak Mordechai and National
Infrastructure Minister Ariel Sharon.
</P>
<P>
The main topic was the Israeli offer to unilaterally withdraw
from South Lebanon in conformity with the U.N. Security Council's
resolution 425 calling for Israeli pullback.
</P>
<P>
The ministers heard the reports presented by senior Army
officials, including Army intelligence chief Moshe Yaalon,
Northern Command head Amiram Levine and Coordinator in South
Lebanon Uri Lubrani.
</P>
<P>
Israel Radio reported that the uniform view formed in the
inner Cabinet was that the Israeli pullback would only be
implemented with Syrian agreement following peace negotiations
with Damascus. Israel's whole Cabinet is to discuss the issue at
next week's session.
</P>
<P>
The idea for a unilateral withdrawal was proposed by Netanyahu
following the killing of three Israeli soldiers last Thursday. So
far four Israeli soldiers have been killed by Hezbollah (Party of
God) guerrilla forces in South Lebanon this year.
</P>
<P>
Since Israel's establishment of the so-called South Lebanon
Security Zone in 1985, an average 35 Israeli soldiers were killed
annually, leading to increasing domestic pressure for a
unilateral withdrawal.
</P>
<P>
While Netanyahu pledged to honor the U.N. resolution 425 by
unilaterally withdrawing troops from Lebanon, he demanded for
Lebanese government's promise to take over security control in
the area to ensure the safety of Israeli northern
territory.
</P>
<P>
Lebanon and Syria have rejected the idea, saying Israel must
withdraw its troops without setting any conditions.
</P>
<P>
During his visit to Europe last week, Netanyahu explored with
European leaders the possibility of deploying international
forces to maintain security in South Lebanon following an Israeli
pullout.
</P>
<P>
But the common sense was that any Israeli withdrawal would not
be feasible without reaching an agreement with Syria, which
Israel charges for using the fighting in Lebanon as a leverage in
talks with Israel.
</P>
<P>
The Israeli-Syrian talks have been halted since early 1996 and
the hope for its resumption has been slim since the access to
power by the hardline Likud government led by Netanyahu.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
