<HEADLINE> Mass Funeral for 40 Children Held in Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 11 (Xinhua) -- A mass funeral was held here
Wednesday for 40 children who have died for lack of medicine and
foodstuffs due to the U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq for its
invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
Saltan al-Shawy, chairman of the Iraqi child support society,
was quoted by the Iraqi news agency as saying that the embargo has
led to the death of 1.3 million Iraqi children.
</P>
<P>
He held the U.S. administration responsible for the death of
the children on account of its determination to maintain the
unjustified sanctions on the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shawy described the continuing embargo as a collective
annihilation crime against the children and people of Iraq.
</P>
<P>
He delivered a letter from parents of the deceased to the U.N.
resident representative office in Baghdad. In their letter, the
parents expressed their deep sorrow and strong denunciation of the
collective killing of children throughout the years of embargo.
</P>
<P>
According to official figures compiled by the Iraqi Ministry of
Health, the mortality rate among children in all Iraqi provinces
stands at 7,500 deaths per month, due to the serious shortages of
foodstuffs and medicine. 
</P>
