<HEADLINE> France Calls on U.N. to Give Iraq Hopes </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 11 (Xinhua) -- France on Wednesday called on the
U.N. to give hopes to Iraqi people who are suffering from the
seven-year-old U.N. sanctions if Baghdad really has destroyed its
weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
The remarks were made by French Ambassador in Lebanon Daniel
Jouanneau, who delivered a letter from French Foreign Minister
Hubert Vedrine to his Lebanese counterpart Fares Boueiz.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a news conference, Jouanneau said "We believe that
the U.N. should give Iraq some hopes and say to its President
Saddam Hussein and its people what will happen if it applies with
the U.N. resolutions and destroy all weapons of mass destruction."
</P>
<P>
The ambassador said the letter also expressed his country's
wishes that the U.N. lift its seven-year-old sanctions imposed on
Iraq due to its 1990 invasion of Kuwait if U.N. arms experts prove
that Iraq doesn't hold any weapons of mass destruction.
</P>
<P>
In the letter, France expressed satisfaction with the
U.N. resolution regarding the Iraq weapons inspection and the
agreement reached between the U.N. general secretary Kofi Annan
and Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The agreement was signed last month to defuse a crisis in which
the U.S. and Britain unleased war threat against Iraq to force
Baghdad to open some presidential sites for U.N. weapons
inspectors. It allows U.N. experts free entry to those places.
</P>
<P>
France, together with China and Russia, has opposed the use of
force as well-prepared by the other two permanent members in the
U.N. Security Council.
</P>
<P>
However, France asks Iraq to fully comply with the agreement
with the United Nations, Jouanneau added. 
</P>
