after the incident, in which three Palestinian workers were killed
by Israeli soldiers at a check point.
</P>
<P>
Following the shooting, clashes erupted between Israeli troops
and local residents around the check point. Confrontations and
demonstrations also broke out in the territories, with young
Palestinians throwing stones at Israeli soldiers, who responded
with tear gas and rubber bullets.
</P>
<P>
Asked about the possibility of a wave of violence against
Israel, Netanyahu said that violence would damage the interests
of both Israel and the Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He also stressed that the Israeli-Palestinian peace talks are
beneficial to both sides, and Israel will move on the peace
process.
</P>
<P>
In an effort to calm the situation, Israeli security forces
remained in close contact with the Palestinian National Authority
(PNA) in the wake of the incident. Palestinian police have been
deployed in Hebron to try to keep order.
</P>
<P>
The shooting incident came at a time of deadlock in
Israeli-Palestinian peace process. PNA President Yasser Arafat had
threatened that there would be a new Palestinian intifada
(uprising) in the territories if no breakthrough in the peace
talks is achieved.
</P>
<P>
Israeli-Palestinian peace process has been stalled for nearly a
year over the construction of a Jewish settlement in Arab East
Jerusalem in March last year. 
