<HEADLINE> Egyptian Killer Nurse Sentenced to Death </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 11 (Xinhua) -- An Egyptian court Wednesday
sentenced to death a nurse after finding her guilty of murdering a
patient and attempting to kill 29 others by injecting lethal
doses, Egypt's Middle East News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The Alexandria Criminal Court ordered that the sentence be
referred to the Mufti, Egypt's chief Muslim official, for
ratification before reaffirming it on March 26.
</P>
<P>
Aida Nourreddine, a 25-year-old nurse at Al Meeri Hospital of
northern port city Alexandria, was arrested last August after the
recurring deaths of 33 intensive care patients from respiratory
failure shortly after they had undergone successful surgeries.
</P>
<P>
Investigations show that she injected them with a respiratory
muscle relaxant which caused them choke to death in the state-run
hospital in the country's second largest city.
</P>
<P>
Nourreddine was suspected of having been involved in all the 33
deaths but was charged with murdering only one patient as an
autopsy could be conducted only on him. She was also accused of
attempted murder of 29 other persons who survived.
</P>
<P>
But the former "model nurse" of her hospital, who works at the
neurology department's intensive care unit (ICU), pleaded
innocent. She also accused doctors at the department of negligence
and prescribing the wrong medication to their patients.
</P>
<P>
She reportedly sought revenge on her ex-lover, a doctor in the
same hospital who jilted her, by killing patients under his care.
</P>
<P>
The police have found a surprise twist in their investigation
as they can have no access to the ICU patients' dossiers, with
hospital officials claiming that they had been disposed of. The
standard practice is to delete such files five years after being
closed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0050 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Agrees to Consult U.N. Before Strike on Iraq </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 11 (Xinhua) -- President Bill Clinton said
Wednesday that Washington would consult U.N. Security Council
members before resorting to force against Iraq if it fails to
comply with its agreement on weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
But he insisted there was no need for the United Nations to
approve for any kind of such attacks on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the resolution gives us the authority to take
whatever actions are necessary but of course we would consult,"
Clinton told reporters before a meeting with U.N.
Secretary-General Kofi Annan. "It would be unthinkable that we
wouldn't."
</P>
<P>
He said he had spent a lot of time on the telephone with large
numbers of world leaders in the latest standoff with Iraq over
weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
He was careful to speak only of consulting with the Security
Council rather than seeking its approval.
</P>
<P>
Clinton praised Annan for his diplomacy, which reduced for the
moment the threat of a U.S.-British military strike against Iraq.
On Feb. 23, Annan succeeded in reaching an accord with Baghdad to
revive weapons inspections under the U.N. resolutions.
</P>
<P>
"Let me (say) how pleased I am with the agreement worked out
with Iraq to continue the inspections as well as the access which
has been provided to the inspectors," Clinton said. "The
secretary-general deserves a lot of appreciation from the United
States and all Americans for the work that is being done."
</P>
<P>
Annan's two-day visit, his first to Washington since returning
from Iraq, is designed to build political support for his
agreement with Iraq on weapons inspections and to appeal once more
for the United States to pay the 1.3 billion dollars in arrears to
the United Nations.
</P>
<P>
Annan told reporters on his plane to Washington that he
expected the U.S. Congress to make good on an agreement struck
last year under which the arrears would be made in return for
reforms Annan carried out to slim down the world body's
bureaucracy.
</P>
<P>
He said a lot had changed at the United Nations in the last 15
months. "We have delivered and I want to know when they will
deliver," he said.
</P>
<P>
As he was flying from New York, House of Representatives
Republicans announced they would link anti-abortion provisions to
any legislation covering the U.N. funding.
</P>
<P>
Annan said he regretted the addition of abortion provisions,
saying it was made "for purely domestic reasons." But he said it
was something that had to be worked out between Clinton and
Congress. 
</P>
</TEXT>
