<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0052 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Chief Executive Confides in Basic Law </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, the Chief Executive
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region (HKSAR) of China,
said here on Wednesday that the Basic Law of Hong Kong is "the
ultimate source of our confidence."
</P>
<P>
"The Basic Law provides a constitutional framework for the Hong
Kong Special Administrative Region. It institutionalizes the
concept of `one country, two systems.' It clearly prescribes that
the social, economic and political system in Hong Kong will be
different from those in mainland China. It protects the rights,
freedoms and lifestyle of Hong Kong people," said Tung in a speech
to the French National Employers' Association CNPF.
</P>
<P>
He also said that the Basic Law guarantees the independence of
Hong Kong's judiciary, allows complete financial autonomy,
establishes Hong Kong as a separate customs territory and gives
Hong Kong full responsibility to manage its own affairs -- except
foreign affairs and defense.
</P>
<P>
Tung said that it is in the fundamental national interests of
China that the "one country, two systems" be implemented,
because by demonstrating that different social, economic and
political systems can operate within one country will be a
significant step towards the greater and final objective of the
unification of the entire nation.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out that the Basic Law has set out a 10-year
timetable for elections both for the Chief Executive and for the
Legislature, which will increase the number of members of
Legislature to be directly elected to 50 percent in three phases
from 1998 to 2004.
</P>
<P>
"In fact, the process of democratic evolution in the next
decade will be far more comprehensive and far-reaching than what
we had under 156 years of colonialism," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
