<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Four Japanese Opposition Parties Agree to Merge </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Four Japanese opposition parties
comprising the largest parliamentary opposition group, Minyuren,
on Thursday agreed to form a new party ahead of the House of
Councillors (upper house) election in July, Kyodo News reported.
</P>
<P>
The four parties -- the Democratic Party of Japan (DPJ), The
Good Governance Party (GGP), the Amity Party and the Democratic
Reform Party (DRP) -- agreed to merge under the DPJ banner during
the group's high-level strategy session.
</P>
<P>
The parties plan to launch a task force next week to prepare
for their merger and discuss principles and policies to be adopted
by the new party, which is expected to be formed before the
"Golden Week" holidays which will run between April 29 and May 5.
</P>
<P>
The new party aims to prevent the ruling Liberal Democratic
Party (LDP) from winning a majority in the upper house in the July
election and to take over power from the LDP at the next House of
Representatives (lower house) election, which is due to take place
by October 2000.
</P>
<P>
The merger will give the new DPJ a total of around 140 seats in
both houses of the Diet (parliament), compared with 380 Diet
members of the LDP.
</P>
<P>
The merger accord was reached in response to a proposal made
last week by former Prime Minister Morihiro Hosokawa, a top GGP
member.
</P>
<P>
The parties are now expected to play tug-of-war over who will
represent the new party as its prime ministerial candidate.
</P>
<P>
The DPJ is led by former Health and Welfare Minister Naoto Kan,
while the GGP is headed by former Prime Minister Tsutomu Hata, the
Amity Party, by Kansei Nakano, and the DRP, by Teiko Sasano.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
