<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0056 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> German Lobby Claims Cheating on Euro Targets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BONN, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Germany failed to meet the single
currency criteria with its 1997 budget deficit at five percent of
the gross domestic product (GDP), a taxpayer lobby alleged
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Finance Minister Theo Waigel had claimed the deficit was 2.7
percent.
</P>
<P>
"It is fatal and highly alarming that even Germany used various
tricks concerning the convergence criteria," said Karl Heinz
Daeke, leader of the Association of Taxpayers.
</P>
<P>
Under European Monetary Union criteria, countries must limit
their budget deficit to under three percent of the GDP to be
qualified as a euro country, the single European currency to be
launched on January 1, 1999.
</P>
<P>
Daeke told reporters Bonn used a series of unorthodox measures
to get the 2.7 percent figure -- delaying payments, collecting
future revenues in advance and shifting loss-making economic
activities to the private sector in order to conceal deficits.
</P>
<P>
He also criticized Italy and France for using tricks to bring
down budget deficit figures.
</P>
<P>
His organization called for a delayed startup of the euro, but
admitted this was unlikely to happen.
</P>
<P>
European leaders had a "blind determination" to go ahead with
the single currency, he said.
</P>
<P>
Only the German Constitutional Court was still able to prevent
Germany from joining the euro next year, Daeke added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
