<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 1600 GMT, March 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- A group of United Nations oil experts arrived in
Baghdad Thursday on a mission to evaluate Iraq's oil production
capability under an enhanced oil-for-food program, the Iraqi News
Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Head of the group, Jalace Graham, said upon arrival at the
Habbaniya military airport, 80 kilometers west of Baghdad, that
his group will stay in Iraq for two weeks to determine how much
oil Iraq can produce, how much it would be able to export.
</P>
<P>
Eric Falt, spokesman for the Office of U.N. Humanitarian
Coordinator in Iraq, told a press conference earlier Thursday that
the group of 14 oil experts will hold talks with U.N. officials
upon arrival, and then in the evening, with Iraqi officials from
ministries of foreign affairs and oil. (Iraq-U.N.-Oil Expert)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TEHRAN -- An Iranian Foreign Ministry official has denied a
report by a newspaper here that a U.S. State Department official
recently visited Iran.
</P>
<P>
According to Iran's official news agency IRNA Thursday, the
official said the report was "incorrect." Only a group of
scholars of different nationalities arrived here last week to
attend a conference on security in the Persian Gulf held by the
Foreign Ministry, he said.
</P>
<P>
The participants, including a number of Americans, held no
official post but were present for scientific purposes, said the
official, who asked not to be named. (Iran-US)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TOKYO -- Bank of Japan (BOJ) Governor Yasuo Matsushita said
Thursday he had offered to resign to take the blame for the arrest
of a senior BOJ official suspected of accepting bribes.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Matsushita said he telephoned Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto Wednesday and expressed his intention to step
down.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto is expected to release Matsushita from his duties
before the central bank makes institutional changes in line with a
revised central bank law, which from April will give it greater
independence, government sources said. (Japan-BOJ
Chief-Resignation) 
</P>
</TEXT>
