<HEADLINE> Russia Dislikes Latvian Foreign Minister's Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Moscow is not ready to receive
Latvian Foreign Minister Valdis Birkavs, who is hoping to visit
Russia, Russian Foreign Ministry stated on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minsitry's spokesman Gennady Tarasov told a briefing
here that "A visit by the Latvian foreign minister to Moscow as it
was planned by the Latvian side is hardly likely to introduce
something new to our relations."
</P>
<P>
According to the spokesman, Latvia recently notified Moscow
that Birkavs would like to visit Russia in order to discuss
important issues pertaining to relations between the two
countries.
</P>
<P>
Tarasov noted the purpose of the visit by the Latvian Foreign
Minister was to provide explanations over the recent rally of
Russian-speakers in Riga which resulted in police beating elderly
people and women, and to consider the outlook for economic
cooperation between Russian and Latvia.
</P>
<P>
Describing the agenda of the visit as sidestepping the main
cause of the current state of affairs in the bilateral relations,
the spokesman pointed out that the main cause is "disrespect for
the rights of our compatriots living in this country".
</P>
<P>
Russia is looking forward "not to just talking and promises
which was often the case in the past but to practical deeds to
ensure the basic rights and freedoms in Latvia."
</P>
<P>
He continued that if the Latvian side is ready to hold such
talks, Russia is ready for it.
</P>
<P>
On Tuesday, Birkavs said that he is ready and willing to visit
Moscow in the nearest future to meet Russian counterpart Yevgeny
Primakov and other Russian officials to discuss the two countries'
relations.  
</P>
</TEXT>
