<HEADLINE> CPPCC Session Holds Third Speech Meeting (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Member Y.S.Wu, president of the Hopewell Holdings Ltd. in Hong
Kong, said that it would have been impossible for Hong Kong to
maintain its prosperity and stability without the current fine
situation for the entire Chinese economy.
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong will have a better tomorrow with continued
implementation of the 'one country, two systems' policy," he said.
</P>
<P>
His view was shared by Member Woo Chia-wei, president of the
Hong Kong University of Science and Technology, who said that he
is very optimistic about Hong Kong's future development.
</P>
<P>
Member Ho Teng Iat, a noted entrepreneur in Macao, said that
the return of Macao to China at the end of next year would draw
worldwide attention. She stressed the necessity to step up
preparatory work for Macao's return.
</P>
<P>
Member Wu Mingxi, who represents the Central Committee of the
China Zhi Gong Party, a non-Communist party whose members are
mostly returned overseas Chinese and relatives of overseas
Chinese, expressed the hope that overseas Chinese would play a
more active role in promoting China's complete reunification.
</P>
<P>
Member Ginzom Gyincainpuncog, vice-chairman of the Tibet
Autonomous Regional Committee of the CPPCC, urged the Tibetan
people to unswervingly safeguard the unity of the motherland, take
a clear-cut stand in opposing separatism, and completely clear
away the influence of the Dalai Lama.
</P>
<P>
The establishment of the rule of law in China has become
another popular topic in today's speeches. Member Zhang Baowen and
Member Huang Jingjun, both senior leaders of the Central Committee
of the China Democratic League, another non-Communist party in
China, said in a joint speech that administering the country
according to law is the key to China's lasting prosperity and
stability.
</P>
<P>
Member Zhang Shiming, vice-chairman of the Central Committee of
the Chinese Peasants and Workers Democratic Party, spoke about the
CPPCC's functions, while Member Cheng Lianchang, executive
vice-chairman of the China Quality Control Association, praised
the State Council plan of institutional restructuring, which was
approved by the ongoing session of the Ninth National People's
Congress, China's top legislature, on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Executive chairmen of today's meeting are Zhang Siqing, Lu
Jiaxi, Ma Man-kei, Wan Guoquan and Zhu Xun. 
</P>
