<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0071 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen on International Situation and Diplomatic Work (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Taking questions on Taiwan, he said conditions are ripe to hold
cross-Straits political negotiations under the principle of "one
China".
</P>
<P>
He underlined that negotiations should be held in accordance
with the principle of "one China". In this way can Taiwan
compatriots' desire to seek peace and security be satisfied, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Qian said a step-by-step approach can be adopted before further
talks are held, and the first step is to end hostilities across
the Taiwan Straits.
</P>
<P>
It is reasonable to hold procedural talks to discuss the name,
form and ways of negotiations, and all kinds of matters can be
discussed.
</P>
<P>
According to the previous experience, there were political
obstacles when business talks were held, he said.
</P>
<P>
Qian said he welcomes the expansion of cross-Straits exchanges,
including exchanges between the Association for Relations Across
the Taiwan Straits (ARATS) and Straits Exchange Foundation (SEF).
</P>
<P>
"Recently, the Taiwan side made ambiguous the one-China
principle issue, a question used to be very distinct," he said,
" and I do not understand why Taiwan is afraid of taling about
'one-China' principle."
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan authorities used to adhere to "one China" but now
they have backed down from that position, he added.
</P>
<P>
It is totally unnecessary to be afraid of talking about "one
China," he said. Both sides should recognize that there is one
China in the world before the reunification, that Taiwan is part
of China, and that China's territory and sovereignty cannot be
separated, he said.
</P>
<P>
On Taiwan's role in the Asian financial crisis, he said,
Taiwan's activities during the Southeast Asian financial crisis
will produce no good results.
</P>
<P>
He further noted that the financial crisis started from
Southeast Asia last July and later spread to many countries.
</P>
<P>
Last October, he recalled, Taiwan announced all of sudden the
devaluation of the New Taiwan Dollar by 10 percent, thus leading
to another round of devaluation. Actually, Taiwan added fuel to
the flame of the southeast Asian financial crisis, Qian said.
</P>
</TEXT>
