<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen on International Situation and Diplomatic Work (5) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Speaking on Sino-Russian relations, he expected that President
Jiang Zemin's planned visit to Russia this year will further
promote the relations between the two neighboring nations.
</P>
<P>
President Jiang Zemin will meet with President Yeltsin again in
Russia this year according to a plan agreed upon by the two sides,
although it may not be an official visit, he said.
</P>
<P>
The planned summit between the leaders of the two countries
will help further advance the growth of bilateral relations, Qian
noted.
</P>
<P>
With the settlement of some outstanding issues exiting between
them, he said, the two countries are in a better position to
further bilateral ties.
</P>
<P>
Concerning Sino-Japanese relations, he said the exchange of
visits by Chinese Premier and Japanese Prime Minister last year
has further promoted the development of Sino-Japanese relations.
</P>
<P>
During the visit, the two sides conferred on issues of shared
interest and increased mutual understanding, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
Chinese President Jiang Zemin is to visit Japan this year as a
return visit for the Japanese Emperor's China trip. It will be the
first visit to Japan by a Chinese president in history, he said.
</P>
<P>
"China and Japan are two major neighboring countries. In
history, the two countries had built long-standing friendship in
addition to close cultural links. However, the two nations also
experienced some unfortunate period in modern history," the
foreign minister said.
</P>
<P>
"Therefore, the two countries should work together and take
history as a guidance for the future development of Sino-Japanese
relations," he said.
</P>
<P>
On Sino-British relations, he said, with the settlement of the
Hong Kong issue and scheduled exchange of visits by senior
government leaders, Sino-British relations will witness greater
development in 1998.
</P>
