<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen on International Situation and Diplomatic Work (6) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
"Hong Kong used to be a problem between China and Britain left
over by history. The two countries once fought war over Hong Kong,
and also had conflicts and disputes over the Hong Kong issue,"
noted Qian.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, this 150-year-plus history has already become
by-gones with Hong Kong's return to its motherland, which was
recognized by the British government.
</P>
<P>
"With the settlement of this issue left over from the past, the
relations between China and Britain, two major powers, will surely
enjoy greater growth in all areas," he said.
</P>
<P>
He further noted that British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook has
already paid a visit to China, and British Prime Minister Tony
Blair is also going to visit China later this year. Sino-British
relations will witness a great development in 1998, he said.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he added, the Chinese premier will attend the second
Asia-Europe Meeting scheduled to be held in London in April, and
also visit Britain.
</P>
<P>
"So I believe this year will witness greater development in
Sino-British relations," Qian said.
</P>
<P>
In response to a question concerning the Republic of Korea
(ROK), he said China appreciates President Kim Dae-jung's position
on resuming the implementation of the agreement reached between
the North and South of Korea, and his pursuit of a peace policy.
</P>
<P>
Qian also congratulated Kim Dae-jung on his election and
welcomed him to visit China at his convenience.
</P>
<P>
Commenting on the Kosovo issue, he said China is very concerned
about the recent bloodshed in Kosovo and that arms embargo may be
an option for resolving the issue.
</P>
<P>
"There are really too many weapons in that region," he said,
adding that when the turmoil erupted not long ago in Albania,
there was a very widespread dissemination of weapons in this
region, and almost everybody had a weapon, which was very
dangerous.
</P>
</TEXT>
