<HEADLINE> Arrested S. African Official's Trip Unauthorized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Senior South African
foreign affairs official Robert Mcbride, who was arrested Monday
in Mozambique for alleged illegal gun running, was at that time
using his diplomatic passport on an unauthorized private visit.
</P>
<P>
This was revealed by the Foreign Affairs Department of South
Africa in a statement in Pretoria on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
It said that Mcbride, who was arrested Monday in the small
town of Ressano Garcia near the border between South Africa and
Mozambique, was on leave at the time. He is staying in police
custody in Maputo, capital of Mozambique and the Mozambican
police are investigating the matter.
</P>
<P>
Foreign Minister Alfred Nzo was shocked at the news of the
arrest, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
Deputy Director-General Abdul Minty visited Maputo on
Wednesday to investigate the matter and reported to Nzo Wednesday
night, the statement said.
</P>
<P>
The legal process in Mozambique will take its normal course,
during which the South African government will maintain regular
contact with the Mozambican government, it said.
</P>
<P>
The news of the arrest has drawn sharp reaction from
opposition parties. They said the incident suggested that the ANC
was using the Foreign Affairs Department as a cover for arms
smuggling.
</P>
<P>
They also accused the government of trying to cover up the
reasons for the arrest and called for Mcbride's suspension
pending the outcome of investigations.
</P>
<P>
No charges has been laid against Mcbride, who is the director
in charge of the Asian desk in the South African Foreign Affairs
Department.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
