<HEADLINE> Northeast China Reports New Progress in Enterprise Reform </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Provincial governors from three
northeast China provinces, a major industrial base, reported today
remarkable progress in reform of their large state-owned economic
sector.
</P>
<P>
The governors from the provinces of Liaoning, Jilin,
Heilongjiang, present at the current session of the National
People's Congress (NPC), in session since last week, said the past
couple of years have seen the establishment of a number of
industrial conglomerates consisting of firms from different areas,
different industrial sectors and of different ownerships.
</P>
<P>
The large enterprise groups linked by capital have been playing
a key role in boosting economic growth in their respective areas,
said the governors, Zhang Guoguang from Liaoning, Wang Yunkun from
Jilin and Tian Fengshan from Heilongjiang.
</P>
<P>
In Jilin, ten such groups have been set up and they are led by
the First Automotive Works and Jilin Chemical Industry Complex,
Wang said.
</P>
<P>
In Liaoning last year, 49 large and medium-sized firms were
merged and 26 others went bankrupt, and dozens of state-owned
enterprises have been converted into joint-stock companies, the
province's governor said. Reform has been in full swing in more
than 80 percent of all small firms in the province, he said.
</P>
<P>
In Heilongjiang, where state-owned enterprises dominate the
local economy, reforms have centered on the establishment of a
modern enterprise system, according the provincial governor.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
