<HEADLINE> Kazakhstan, Mongolia Sign Agreement on Trade, Cooperation </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ALMA ATA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Kazakhstan and Mongolia signed a
joint statement on Thursday for promoting bilateral trade and
strengthening cooperation in mining, agriculture, animal
husbandry, education, tourism, culture and sports.
</P>
<P>
The statement was signed by Kazakh President Nursultan
Nazarbayev and by visiting Mongolian President Nachagyn Bagabandy.
</P>
<P>
The statement came after bilateral trade in 1997 declined by
41.8 percent from that of 1996, to 21 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
The two presidents also signed agreements on preventing dual
taxation and on cooperation in customs affairs, veterinary
training, environmental protection and plant quarantining.
</P>
<P>
The two countries have signed more than 30 cooperation
agreements since they established diplomatic relations in January,
1992.
</P>
<P>
Bagabandy, who arrived here earlier Wednesday for a visit, is
also expected to visit Kuwait and Turkey. This is his first
foreign trip since he took office on June 20, 1997. 
</P>
