<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Autonomous Region Sees Rapid Economic Development </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- "Fundamental changes" have taken
place in northwest China's Ningxia Hui Autonomous Region since it
was founded in 1958, acting chairman of the regional government Ma
Qizhi said today.
</P>
<P>
Four decades ago, 70 percent of people in Ningxia, an area with
the largest concentration of Hui people in China, did not have
adequate food and clothing. The annual per capita net income of
local residents was less than 100 yuan then, said Ma, who is
attending the annual session of the Ninth National People's
Congress here as a deputy.
</P>
<P>
In recent years, the region's economy has been growing at an
average rate of 8.9 percent a year. Per capita grain production
there stands at 500 kg a year, fifth in China. Also, Ningxia ranks
second in the country in per capita amount of electricity
generated, he said.
</P>
<P>
Its gross domestic product soared to 21 billion yuan in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The proportion of industry in its economy has risen from 7.8
percent in the late 1950s to 34 percent at present.
</P>
<P>
Ningxia has built economic and trade ties with more than 60
countries and regions. Its import and export value came to 300
million U.S. dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
The annual net income of farmers averaged 1,545 yuan while that
of urban residents 3,431 yuan last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
