<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0086 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Half of Athenians Exposed to Excessive Noise </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ATHENS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Despite measures to curb noise,
more than half of all Athenians were exposed to excessive noise
pollution, a newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The newspaper, "Athens News", quoted a Greek Environment
Ministry report as saying that 36 percent of the residents in the
Greek capital were subjected to noise whose levels in excess of 75
decibels.
</P>
<P>
During peak hours, the noise in many places in Athens reached
levels of 90 to 100 decibels.
</P>
<P>
The Greek environment ministry sets 66 to 68 as an acceptable
range while the European Union has set a limit of 75 decibels for
vehicle noise emissions.
</P>
<P>
The report attributed much of the noise pollution to Athens'
chronic traffic problem and construction works for the metro.
</P>
<P>
Athens, with a population of four million people, has about 1.3
million cars and 600,000 motorcycles.
</P>
<P>
To cut down on noise, the Greek government has taken measures
including the introduction of a compulsory decibel limit test for
industries and nightclubs, and hefty fines for noisy motorcycle
owners.
</P>
<P>
Greece also began constructing noise barriers two years ago in
spots beside roads and railway lines around Athens. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
