<HEADLINE> France Warns Schroder Not to Deviate from Coupling </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- French Minister-delegate for
European Affairs Pierre Moscovici Thursday warned the German
Socialist candidate for chancellery, Gerhard Schroder, that a
Franco-German axis in the European structure must be maintained.
</P>
<P>
In an interview with the "L'Expresse" weekly, published
Thursday, Moscovici said the "European anchorage" by Germany and
its privileged relations with France were an obligation for all
German leaders in the future.
</P>
<P>
Schroder, who was re-elected the president-minister in
Germany's economically powerful Lower Saxony last month, and whose
support rate is much higher than Chancellor Helmut Kohl's, has
said he will organize a round-table debate on the euro and will
transform the Franco-German axis in Europe into a
German-British-French triangle.
</P>
<P>
"I believe that if tomorrow Mr. Schroder becomes chancellor, he
would be as European and as committed to the Franco-German couple
as Mr. Kohl is," said Moscovici.
</P>
<P>
"This reality, because it is necessary for Europe, is an
obligation for all governments, in France as well as in Germany,"
he added.
</P>
<P>
He expressed doubt over whether Schroder understands European
problems and France as well as Kohl.
</P>
<P>
"It is true that Gerhard Schroder has not expressed, until now,
with the same strength as Helmut Kohl on the European problems.
Without doubt, he knows less about France than other leaders,"
said Moscovici. 
</P>
</TEXT>
