<HEADLINE> Nepal, Bangladesh to Share Experience in Poverty </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Nepal hopes to share Bangladesh's
experience in poverty alleviation and infrastructure development,
visiting Nepalese Minister for Local Development Gajendra Marayan
Singh said here Friday.
</P>
<P>
"We look forward to learning from and sharing your (Bangladesh)
experiences," the Nepalese minister said at a three-day workshop
aimed at sharing experiences on food-assisted development in the
two South Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
The Nepalese minister, who arrived here Wednesday, is leading a
30-member delegation to familiarize with the food-assisted
development programs in Bangladesh.
</P>
<P>
Both Nepal and Bangladesh, as members of the South Asian
Association for Regional Cooperation, face similar challenges,
with getting the people out of poverty and destitution as one of
the major goals, he said.
</P>
<P>
The food-for-work program assisted by the World Food Program
(WFP) has contributed a lot to this direction in Nepal, according
to the Nepalese minister. "We are very happy to learn that WFP
programs have a grand success in Bangladesh," he added.
</P>
<P>
Mofazzal Hossain Chowdhury Maya, state minister for Local
Government, Rural Development and Cooperatives, said Bangladesh
attaches top priority to poverty alleviation.
</P>
<P>
Since 1974, the WFP has opened up a new dimension in rural
infrastructure development in Bangladesh through two projects --
Vulnerable Group Development and Rural Development, which are
aimed at poverty alleviation and have created job opportunities
for the poorest, particularly for destitute women, he said.
</P>
</TEXT>
