<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Russian Upper House Passes 1998 Budget </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MOSCOW, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Russia's Federation Council (the
upper house of parliament) approved the 1998 federal budget by a
vote of 115 to 22 against, with four abstentions, on Thursday, the
Interfax news agency reported.
</P>
<P>
The budget, which was passed by the State Duma (the lower house
of parliament) in its fourth reading on March 4, will be submitted
to President Boris Yeltsin for signing into law.
</P>
<P>
The approved budget provides a deficit of 133 billion rubles
(22 billion U.S. dollars) and an expenditure of about 500 billion
rubles (83 billion dollars).
</P>
<P>
Revenue is expected to be 367 billion rubles (61 billion
dollars).
</P>
<P>
The GDP is forecast to be 2,840 billion rubles (47 billion
dollars), 90 billion rubles (15 billion dollars) more than earlier
forecast by the government.
</P>
<P>
Annual inflation is estimated to be 5.7 percent, with the
average ruble exchange rate at 6.18 to the dollar.
</P>
<P>
Presenting the budget to the Federation Council, Finance
Minister Mikhail Zadornov said a two percent growth of GDP is the
government's key target for 1998.
</P>
<P>
He said national defense was one of the priorities in spending,
for which about 3.5 percent of GDP was earmarked in allocations.
</P>
</TEXT>
