<HEADLINE> NPC Deputies on Improving Social Security </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Deputies to the Ninth National
People's Congress (NPC), in session here since last week, call for
reforming China's social security system, which they say lags far
behind economic reform.
</P>
<P>
Effective measures should be taken to quicken the reform of
old-age, medical and unemployment insurance systems to eliminate
such malpractices as irrational charges and a low rate of
socialization, they say.
</P>
<P>
Dong Wande, chairman of the Liaoning Provincial Federation of
Trade Unions, says the government decision to set up a Ministry of
Labor and Social Security has a great bearing on building a social
security system with Chinese characteristics.
</P>
<P>
Wang Jiren, deputy director of the Shanxi Provincial Department
of Coal Industry, says that the country should expand unemployment
insurance and combine it with employment, create more job
opportunities for laid-off workers and establish a welfare system
guaranteeing a basic living standard for the needy in urban areas.
</P>
<P>
Shen Anbo, director of the Yunnan Provincial Policy Research
Center, says that the key to building a social security system is
to accumulate adequate funds. Funds should be raised from a
variety of channels, he says.
</P>
<P>
He advocates a fund-raising system involving contributions from
the state, enterprises and individuals.
</P>
<P>
"This method should be standardized by enacting relevant laws,"
he says.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0097 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 683 HK Election Committee Members to Be Elected Next Month </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 12 (Xinhua) -- A total of 683 members of the
Election Committee, which should produce a number of members of
the first Legislative Council of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR), will be returned from 35 subsectors'
elections scheduled for April 2.
</P>
<P>
According to an official press release circulated here late
Thursday, these 683 members, together with the ex-officio members
and the religious subsector, which will nominate its own
representatives, will form an 800-strong election committee.
</P>
<P>
The election committee will elect 10 members of the Legislative
Council on May 24, the day of the SAR's first Legislative Council
elections. The nomination period for the subsector elections will
start on Friday and last up to March 20.
</P>
<P>
In accordance with the Basic Law, the SAR's first Legislative
Council shall be composed of 60 members, with 20 returned by
geographical constituencies through direct elections, 10 returned
by an election committee and 30 returned by functional
constituencies.
</P>
<P>
Preparations for the legislative elections in the SAR, the
first of such kind since Hong Kong returned to China on July 1,
1997, are in full swing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
