<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0098 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Troops to Remain in Gulf: Top Officer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CAIRO, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States' top military
officer said here Thursday that U.S. troops will remain in the
Gulf region until Iraq complies with United Nations arms
inspections.
</P>
<P>
"We will have a continuous presence in the area. U.S. forces
are in the Gulf to work for implementing the Baghdad deal and to
secure the Iraqi side's abidance by the U.N. resolutions," said
Chairman of the U.S. Joint Chiefs of Staff Henry Shelton.
</P>
<P>
But if the U.S. is convinced that Iraq complies with the
U.N. resolutions, some 36,000 American troops in the Gulf will be
downsized, Shelton told reporters after talks with Egyptian
President Hosni Mubarak earlier Thursday.
</P>
<P>
He claimed that "the diplomatic solution to the Iraq crisis was
reached through military support."
</P>
<P>
Iraq's refusal last month to allow the U.N. Special Commission
(UNSCOM) to inspect presidential sites prompted the U.S. to
unleash a threat to take military actions against it. An agreement
reached between the U.N. and Iraq on February 23 defused the
crisis.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement, Iraq will grant free and unconditional
access to eight presidential sites suspected of hiding weapons of
mass destruction to a special team comprising UNSCOM inspectors
and senior diplomats appointed by U.N. chief Kofi Annan.
</P>
<P>
Shelton said that Washington and Cairo have formed "relations
of strategic partnership" that is based on "cooperation, respect
and solidarity."
</P>
<P>
"Friendship between Egypt and the U.S. is getting deeper," he
said, referring to their joint exercises, participation in
peace-keeping missions and humanitarian aid all over the world.
</P>
<P>
Shelton, who arrived here on Wednesday, held talks with
Egyptian Defense Minister Hussein Tantawi and Chief of Staff of
the Armed Forces Magdi Hetata during the day on forging closer
military links between the two countries .
</P>
<P>
The U.S. military officer is now on a regional tour which has
taken him to Saudi Arabia and Kuwait.
</P>
<P>
His tour is also aimed at paving the way for a trip by U.S.
Defense Secretary William Cohen later next month to Egypt, Israel,
Jordan, Turkey and Greece. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
