<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 13:55 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Iran Decides to Privatize State-owned Companies </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 12 (Xinhua) - The Iranian government announced
Wednesday night to transfer the state-owned companies to the
private and cooperative sector in order to save them from serious
economic crisis.
</P>
<P>
The Iranian official news agency IRNA Thursday quoted
government spokesman Ataollah Mohajerani as saying that the
cabinet session on Wednesday night announced readiness to ease
the government's control over state-own companies.
</P>
<P>
Mohajerani, also Minister of Culture and Islamic Guidance,
said that the Plan and Budget Organization briefed the cabinet
session on the status of the state-owned companies.
</P>
<P>
The government is trying to transfer the state-owned companies
to people in a way that the transfers would be in line with
social justice and would not damage their management, he said.
</P>
<P>
Mohajerani put the total number of state-run companies at
2,400, saying that 400 of them are "important" firms and only 30
out of the 400 "important" companies, engaged in different areas
of oil, petrochemicals, steel and energy, have key role among
other state-run companies.
</P>
<P>
However, the government has not decided how to transfer the
state-own companies to the people, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
According to earlier reports, the country's state-owned
companies were facing a serious crisis and some of them were in a
condition of bankruptcy due to liquidity shortages, lack of
investment security, instability in regulations.
</P>
<P>
In many fields, such as the textile industry, the operation
was only around 45 percent of their full capacity. Reports said
that some managing directors had urged President Khatami to save
the companies from being closed down. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
