<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Relations of China's Ethnic Groups Become Closer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Reform and opening-up over the
past 20 years have cemented the ties of China's 56 ethnic groups,
said participants in the ongoing sessions of the Ninth National
People's Congress (NPC) and the Ninth National Committee of the
Chinese People's Political Consultative Conference (CPPCC).
</P>
<P>
Li Mutang of the Hui ethnic group said that the development of
transportation, telecommunications and cultural undertakings has
facilitated exchanges between the country's ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
"Long-term migration and blending between various ethnic groups
in history have made them dependent on each other," he said. "They
are more so than ever."
</P>
<P>
Shanghai and the Tibet Autonomous Region, for example, have
established close ties, and so have Yunnan and Heilongjiang
provinces, he said. Under the conditions of a market economy, all
the ethnic groups of the country are mutually benefiting one
another, he said.
</P>
<P>
"With such relations, the Chinese people of various
nationalities can never be separated by external forces," Li said.
</P>
<P>
Ma Like from the Uzbek ethnic group said that China has bid
farewell to an economy of shortages. The growing overall national
strength serves as a powerful backing for economic development in
areas inhabited by minority ethnic groups.
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, poverty eradication and economic take-off in
such areas will contribute greatly to the growth of the national
economy, Ma Like said.
</P>
<P>
Cultural blending between different ethnic groups is also
common. People of the Han ethnic group and other minority ethnic
groups are learning each other's languages, and many of them are
interested in the other's cultures, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
