<HEADLINE> India's Regional Party Demands Firm Commitment from BJP </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The ALL-India Anna Dravida
Munnetra Kazhagam (AIADMK) and its allies are unlikely to give
their support for the Bharatiya Janata Party (BJP) to form the
next government unless the BJP makes a "firm commitment" on
various demands placed by the AIADMK, Press Trust of India (PTI)
reported Thursday evening.
</P>
<P>
Sources in the combine, which commands the loyalty of 27 MPs of
the Lower House of Parliament, said that of the demands put
forward by AIADMK supremo Jayalalitha, dismissal of the Dravida
Munnetra Kazhagam (DMK) government in Tamil Nadu figured the
topmost. Next in the list was the allocation of finance and law
portfolios to Jayalalitha's nominees.
</P>
<P>
BJP's prime ministerial candidate Atal Behari Vajpayee has
expressed his inability to give any commitment on the demands such
as dismissal of the Tamil Nadu government.
</P>
<P>
Tough negotiations were still going on between the two sides to
reach a common ground as time appeared to be running out for
Vajpayee to give a response to the president's directive to
furnish documents supporting his claim of 252 out of 543 MPs in
the House.
</P>
<P>
In his letter to Vajpayee on Tuesday, President K. R. Narayanan
asked him whether his party, which has emerged the largest party
in the just concluded general elections, was "able and willing" to
form a "stable government".
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee called on the president Tuesday evening and claimed to
be able to form a stable government. Then the president asked him
to furnish documents of support and Vajpayee promised to do so on
Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
It is yet to be known whether Vajpayee could call on the
president Thursday evening to present all the support documents to
him.
</P>
<P>
The president is unlikely to initiate any further action on the
formation of the next central government till he is fully
satisfied on the basis of documentary proof that the coalition
government to be formed by Vajpayee would be a stable one.
</P>
</TEXT>
