<HEADLINE> Over 30 Palestinians Injured in Hebron </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Over 30 Palestinian protesters
were injured in the West Bank city of Hebron on Thursday in
clashes with Israeli troops, according to the Palestinian press
service JMCC.
</P>
<P>
The clashes started Thursday morning when tens of hundreds of
local residents gathered in the center of the city to protest
against the bloody killing of three palestinian workers on
Tuesday by Israeli soldiers at the Tarkumiya roadblock near Hebron.
</P>
<P>
The Palestinians threw stones and Molotov cocktails at the
Israeli soldiers who returned fire with rubber bullets and
tear-gas, injuring more than 30 Palestinians. The clashes were
continuing in Hebron.
</P>
<P>
In Bethlehem, another city in the West Bank, a large number of
Palestinians clashed with Israeli troops at the Rachel's Tomb. But
there was no report of injuries so far.
</P>
<P>
Three Israeli soldiers opened fire Tuesday at a van carrying
Palestinian workers returning from their job in Israel, killing
the driver and two others. The soldiers said they suspect the
driver tried to run over them in a terror attack, but the driver
was actually trying to cut into the line only.
</P>
<P>
The shooting incident triggered off widespread protests from
the Palestinians. Clashes between Palestinian protesters and
Israeli troops erupted on Wednesday in Hebron and Ramallah, and
over 50 Palestinians were reportedly injured.
</P>
<P>
In a move to calm the situation in the West Bank and Gaza
Strip, Israeli Defense Minister Yitzhak Mordechai telephoned
Palestinian National Authority (PNA) deputy head Mahmoud Abbas
Wednesday night to express sorrow over the killing.
</P>
<P>
Mordechai updated Abbas his visit late Wednesday to the
Tarkumiya roadblock and promised that details of the investigation
into the shooting would be relayed to the PNA. He called on Abbas
to help calm the tensions.
</P>
<P>
PNA President Yasser Arafat termed the killing as "a big crime
against the Palestinian workers." The PNA has asked to have an
international investigation of the incident.
</P>
<P>
Shortly after the incident, Israeli President Ezer Weizman and
Prime Minister Benjamin Netanyahu phoned Arafat to express their
sorrow over the killing. 
</P>
</TEXT>
