<HEADLINE> IBM's New Strategy In China </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The U.S.'s IBM has announced a
change in focus in China this year to small and medium-sized
enterprises, as a new strategy for increasing its share of the
information technology market.
</P>
<P>
IBM has a new generation of Intel-based servers called
Netfinity that will provide a platform for Electronic-Business,
according to George Man, IBM Greater China's general manager for
Netfinity.
</P>
<P>
E-Business allows business to be done on-line,
bringing costs down and increasing efficiency, by applying the
network and World Wide Web technologies to the work of modern
enterprises, he says, and especially gives small and medium-sized
businesses a chance to compete in the world market.
</P>
<P>
Because Electronic-Business is becoming increasingly popular in
many parts of the world, insiders say that bringing the huge
number of small and medium-sized enterprises on line is crucial.
</P>
<P>
IBM now has a large part of China's information technology
market and its turnover surged by more than 60 percent last year
from the previous year. 
</P>
