<HEADLINE> Jordan's King Leaves for Talks in Washington </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
AMMAN, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Jordan's King Hussein left here for
the United States on Thursday for talks with President Bill
Clinton on the stalled Middle East peace process and Iraqi issue.
</P>
<P>
Hussein is expected to meet with Clinton on March 19. The talks
might focus on the peace negotiations between the Palestinians and
Israel and the prospects for a direct dialog between the U.S. and
Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The king would emphasize the need for Israel to carry out troop
withdrawal from the West Bank under agreements signed with the
Palestinians.
</P>
<P>
He might propose that Washington and Baghdad hold a direct
dialog to patch up differences that appeared since the 1990-91
Gulf crisis, triggered off by Iraqi invasion of Kuwait, Jordan's
Prime Minister Abdul-Salam Majali told reporters earlier.
</P>
<P>
Hussein will also exert efforts to procure more U.S. aid for
Jordan. The U.S. aid for the kingdom in the fiscal year of 1998 is
estimated at around 200 million U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Before meeting Clinton, the 62-year-old king will have
regular medical checkups at the Mayo clinic in Minnesota. He
underwent surgery to remove cancer in 1992.
</P>
<P>
His visit came following a series of Israeli officials' visits
to Jordan aimed at restoring Jordanian-Israeli relations that have
deteriorated since last September's botched assassination attempt
by Israeli agents on a leader of the anti-Israeli movement Hamas.
</P>
<P>
The king just concluded a six-day Arab tour that included talks
with leaders of Egypt, the United Arab Emirates (UAE) and Oman.
</P>
<P>
Crown Prince Hassan paid visits to Ramallah in the West Bank
and Tel Aviv on Monday and Tuesday for talks with Palestinian and
Israeli officials on the Israeli-Palestinian peace negotiations,
which have been deadlocked since March 1997. 
</P>
