<HEADLINE> Iran Denies Reported U.S. Official's Visit </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TEHRAN, March 12 (Xinhua) -- An Iranian Foreign Ministry
official has denied a report by a newspaper here that a U.S. State
Department official recently visited Iran.
</P>
<P>
According to Iran's official news agency IRNA today, the
official said the report was "incorrect." Only a group of scholars
of different nationalities arrived here last week to attend a
conference on security in the Persian Gulf held by the Foreign
Ministry, he said.
</P>
<P>
The participants, including a number of Americans, held no
official post but were present for scientific purposes, said the
official, who asked not to be named.
</P>
<P>
Contacts between Iranians and Americans are increasing after
Iranian President Mohammad Khatami called for cultural dialogue
between the two peoples.
</P>
<P>
Last month, several American foreign policy experts, including
Geoffrey Kemp, a security aide in the Reagon administration,
visited Iran and held talks with Iranian officials.
</P>
<P>
It is believed that Washington and Tehran intend to test the
possibility of government-to-government dialogue by first
promoting cultural exchanges. Officials from both sides are guard
against such a speculation. 
</P>
