<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0116 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup: S. Africa's New Budget Gets Mixed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JOHANNESBURG, March 12 (Xinhua) -- South Africa's 1998/99
budget, unveiled Wednesday, received much praise from business
circles and economists for laying the foundation for sustained
growth and job creation and meanwhile drew fire from opposition
parties.
</P>
<P>
Business organizations and economists hailed the
201-billion-Rand (40.2-billion-U.S. Dollars) budget as one that
would boost economic growth while tackling social issues such as
crime, health and education.
</P>
<P>
They appreciated the attempts by Finance Minister Trevor
Manuel, who announced the budget Wednesday, to ease the tax
burden on low and middle-income class, and provide relief to the
poor.
</P>
<P>
The budget increased spending on the police, justice and
correctional services by 12 percent, to a total of 20.675 billion
Rand (4.135 billion Dollars).
</P>
<P>
Education services got a lion's share of 28 percent of the
budget, or 45 billion Rand (9.04 billion Dollars), and health
received 14 percent or 23 billion Rand (4.6 billion Dollars).
</P>
<P>
With an increase of 5 billion Rand (1 billion Dollars) to 19
billion Rand (3.82 billion Dollars) in welfarFE, Welfare Minister
Geraldine Fraser-Moleketi announced that social security grants
would rise by 4.3 percent from July.
</P>
<P>
The allocation to poverty relief projects will rise from 500
million Rand (100 million Dollars) in 1997/98 to 800 million Rand
(160.6 million Dollars) in 2001.
</P>
<P>
The budget raised levies on cigarettes, alcohol and fuel. The
levies, which are expected to generate an additional 2.51 billion
Rand (504 million Dollars) in revenue, would enable the
government to make tax concessions to the poor while containing
national deficit within acceptable limits.
</P>
<P>
The South African Chamber of Business said Manuel had laid a
solid foundation for economic growth and further interest-rate
cuts.
</P>
<P>
The South African Agricultural Union said the budget was in
line with the Growth, Employment and Redistribution (GEAR)
macro-economic strategy. GEAR, adopted in 1996, highlights a
competitive fast-growing economy and targets job creation and
poverty relief.
</P>
<P>
The steel and engineering industries said the budget
demonstrated the government's firm commitment to sound financial
management and planning, in line with sound macro-economic
principles.
</P>
<P>
Automobile manufacturers also welcomed the budget, saying it
indicated government recognition of the importance of investment
growth and the critical role of business in market expansion,
economic growth and job creation.
</P>
<P>
The National NGO (non-governmental organization) Coalition
hailed the budget for its plan to establish a job creation fund,
saying the move indicated Manuel's recognition of unemployment as
a major problem.
</P>
<P>
However, the budget came under criticism from opposition
parties as well as an ally of the ruling African National
Congress, the Congress of South African Trade Unions (COSATU).
</P>
<P>
The National Party (NP), the biggest opposition par$9, said
the budget contained no imaginative steps to enhance economic
growth and job creation despite predictions that the unemployment
rate now standing at 29 percent would soar to 40 percent within
10 years.
</P>
<P>
The Inkatha Freedom Party (IFP) said the greatest weakness of
the budget was its "failure to comply with a number of
fundamental requirements of the GEAR strategy", together with its
little effort to "compel productive economic activity and
industrial expansion".
</P>
<P>
The Democratic Party (DP), a white-based opposition party,
also slammed the budget for ignoring some of GEAR's elements,
such as greater labor market flexibility, public service reform
and privatization.
</P>
<P>
COSATU and the Pan Africanist Congress, both black-based
parties, attacked the budget for doing little to create jobs.
</P>
<P>
COSATU, which is in the tripartite government coalition, said
Manuel had put more rhetorics in his budget speech than providing
concrete steps to alleviate joblessness. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0117 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
