<HEADLINE> Arafat Reaffirms Commitment to Peace Process </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Palestinian National Authority
President Yasser Arafat on Thursday reaffirmed Palestinian
commitment to continuing the peace process with Israel despite
the current crisis.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters in Gaza city, Arafat said the recent
wave of violence should not be allowed to stop the
Israeli-Palestinian peace process.
</P>
<P>
He reaffirmed that the Palestinians are still committed to
advancing the peace process in spite of all what they are facing.
</P>
<P>
Arafat made the comments as Palestinian violence against
Israeli troops in the territories entered the third day to protest
the Tuesday killing of three Palestinians at a roadblock near West
Bank city of Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Three Israeli soldiers opened fire at a van carrying
Palestinian workers returning from their job in Israel, saying
they suspected the driver tried to run over them in a terror
attack.
</P>
<P>
Some 14 Palestinians were reportedly injured in clashes in
various places in the territories, including Hebron and
Bethlehem. On Wednesday, at least 30 Palestinians were wounded by
rubber bullets fired by Israeli soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Arafat had condemned the killing as "a big crime," but
Palestinian police acted to help control the situation following
Israeli leaders' expression of regrets and condolences over the
incident.
</P>
<P>
The latest crisis highlighted the simmering tension between
Israel and the Palestinian side at a time when the peace talks are
deadlocked. Disputes over Israel's delayed troop redeployments in
West Bank and continued expansion of Jewish settlements have
prevented any progress in forging a permanent peace in the region.
</P>
