<HEADLINE> U.N. Oil Experts Arrive in Baghdad </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 12 (Xinhua) -- A group of United Nations oil
experts arrived in Baghdad Thursday afternoon on a mission to
evaluate Iraq's oil production capability under an enhanced
oil-for-food program, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Head of the group, Jalace Graham, said upon arrival at the
Habbaniya military airport, 80 kilometers west of Baghdad, that
his group will stay in Iraq for two weeks to determine how much
oil Iraq can produce, how much it would be able to export.
</P>
<P>
Eric Falt, spokesman for the Office of U.N. Humanitarian
Coordinator in Iraq, told a press conference earlier Thursday that
the group of 14 oil experts will hold talks with U.N. officials
upon arrival, and then in the evening, with Iraqi officials from
ministries of foreign affairs and oil.
</P>
<P>
Falt said these oil experts will go to Iraq's northern city of
Kirkuk and southern oil field in Basra to examine oil facilities
and evaluate Iraq's need for new equipment, spare parts and
repairs to its oil facilities.
</P>
<P>
Under a U.N. Security Council resolution adopted last month,
the amount of oil Iraq can sell in six months has been increased
to 5.2 billion U.S. dollars for the third phase of oil-for-food
deal, from 2 billion dollars for the first and second phases, to
alleviate the humanitarian crisis in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
However, Iraq said it is unable to pump that much oil due to
price decline on world oil markets and the lack of equipment and
spare parts in its oil sector. It has asked the U.N. to allow it
to import equipment and spare parts.
</P>
<P>
Crushing economic sanctions have been imposed on Iraq by the
United Nations since its invasion in 1990 of Kuwait and inflicted
grave suffering to the Iraqi people. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
