<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> WB: Raising Interest Rates Wrong Medicine for Asian </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Raising interest rates is a "wrong
medicine" for the ailing East Asian economies, including the
Philippines, a World Bank (WB) chief economist said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In a forum organized by the WB and the Asian Development Bank
on ways of dealing with the financial crisis, Joseph Stiglitz,
also senior president of the WB, said the move has been working in
Latin America because of high inflation and fiscal imbalances
there.
</P>
<P>
"But in the case of East Asia, raising the interest rates would
exacerbate the situation (currency crisis) because of the
declining domestic demand," he said, adding that the inflation
rates and fiscal position of the region have been kept within
manageable levels.
</P>
<P>
In the Philippines, the extremely high interest rates, standing
at between 25 and 40 percent, not only failed to stabilize the
peso, but also dampened the economy and drew the massive protest
of the business community.
</P>
<P>
The Philippine Central Bank had shifted its focus of attention
to reducing the interest rates from intervening in the foreign
exchange market, analysts said.
</P>
<P>
Stiglitz, however, said that raising the interest rates during
the financial crisis also has its credit. It can demonstrate
commitment to monetary authorities, strengthen macroeconomic
stability and attract more funds into the region, he added.
</P>
<P>
To minimize the pain brought about by the financial turmoil, he
said the World Bank is working on a program that aims at
strengthening the financial sector in the region.
</P>
<P>
The week-long forum was attended by some 350 government
officials, economists and journalists who discussed the lessons of
the financial crisis and the region's future development
strategies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0128 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 12:18 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Aziz Meets Head of U.N. Special Inspection Group </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BAGHDAD, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Iraqi Deputy Prime Minister Tariq
Aziz on Thursday met with a U.N. official in charge of forming a
special group to proceed with the inspection of Iraqi presidential
sites.
</P>
<P>
Aziz and Jayanatha Dhanapala, a Sri Lankan diplomat specialized
in disarmament, discussed special procedures concerning the
inspections of the presidential palaces in line with the
Iraq-U.N. accord, the Iraqi News Agency reported.
</P>
<P>
Dhanapala's visit is an important step in implementing the
February 23 Iraq-U.N. memorandum of understanding that brought to
a peaceful end the Iraq crisis over U.N. weapons inspections that
erupted four months ago.
</P>
<P>
The Sri Lankan diplomat was asked by U.N. Secretary-General
Kofi Annan to head of a special group of diplomats to escort arms
inspectors to the presidential sites, previously off-limits. The
inspections are expected to start later this month.
</P>
<P>
Aziz said Iraq is keen to implement its accord with Annan and
to cooperate with the United Nations to ensure "transparent and
objective effectuation that would observe Iraq's sovereignty,
dignity and national security."
</P>
<P>
He hoped inspections of presidential palaces would "reveal the
truth and lay bare the falsities fabricated over these sites."
</P>
<P>
Dhanapala underlined United Nations commitment to applying the
accord as soon as possible and in good will, taking into
consideration of Iraq's legitimate concerns.
</P>
<P>
He welcomed Iraq's readiness for cooperation on the road to
sound, objective implementation of the agreement on weapons
inspection in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
Under the agreement signed Annan and Aziz, Iraq agrees to open
eight presidential palaces to special groups comprising senior
diplomats appointed by Annan and experts drawn from the
U.N. Special Commission on disarming Iraq and the International
Atomic Energy Agency.
</P>
<P>
Dhanapala arrived here Wednesday on his first visit to Iraq. "I
have come to prepare the ground for the inspection of the eight
presidential sites," he told the media upon arrival. 
</P>
</TEXT>
