<HEADLINE> China Urges Nuclear Powers to Stick to Nuclear Disarmament </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Disarmament Ambassador Li
Changhe has called on the countries possessing the largest and
most advanced nuclear arsenals to continue to fulfill their
special responsibilities and obligations for nuclear disarmament.
</P>
<P>
Li made the statement here Thursday in a plenary session of the
Conference on Disarmament (CD).
</P>
<P>
"They should carry out further drastic reductions of their
nuclear arsenals, abandon the strategy of nuclear deterrence, stop
the research in and development and proliferation of missile
defense systems, which undermine the global strategic security and
stability," he said.
</P>
<P>
Li said he believed that the nuclear powers' fulfillment of
their special responsibilities and obligations for nuclear
disarmament would help create necessary conditions for all the
nuclear-weapon states to participate in the nuclear disarmament
negotiation process in the future.
</P>
<P>
He noted that some members of the CD have already put forward a
series of proposals on the establishment of working mechanisms for
nuclear disarmament.
</P>
<P>
"The Chinese delegation hopes that on the basis of full
exchange of views, a commonly acceptable formula can be found to
address and discuss nuclear disarmament in the CD, and we will
support such endeavors," Li said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
