<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China Enjoys Booming Computer Market </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- China's computer market is
expected to grow to over 200 billion yuan (24 billion US dollars)
annually by the year 2000.
</P>
<P>
The 1997 Review of the China Computer Market and Forecasts for
1998-2000 released today by a government research institute showed
that the computer industry's total sales for 1997 hit 130 billion
yuan (15.6 billion US dollars), up 41.3 percent on 1996.
</P>
<P>
The three pillars of the computer industry -- hardware, software
and information technology services -- registered rapid growth
on previous years.
</P>
<P>
Hardware, which accounted for the lion's share of the
industry's total sales, witnessed a 45.5 percent rise on the
previous year to end 1997 at 104 billion yuan, or 80 percent of
total sales for the year.
</P>
<P>
Software sales grew by 21.7 percent to 11.2 billion yuan, with
revenues from information technology services growing by 31
percent to 14.8 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Personal computers (PCs), the most popular item, retained their
vigorous competitive edge in the computer market, with over 3.5
million PCs valued at 41.5 billion yuan sold during 1997. The
figures represented 66 percent growth in the PC market during the
year and PCs accounted for some 92 percent of the total number of
computers sold during the year.
</P>
<P>
Applications software held a 63.2 percent share of the total
software market, with systems software registering the most rapid
growth rate of 61.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The total volume for computer trading continued to grow rapidly
in 1997, with the total value of imports and exports reaching
13.16 billion US dollars, up 33.1 percent on the previous year.
</P>
<P>
The growth was mainly due to the increasing number of joint
ventures major international computer companies established in
China.
</P>
<P>
Computer exports grew by 34.9 percent on 1996 to 8.73 billion
US dollars, with imports rising by 29.5 percent to 4.43 billion US
dollars.
</P>
<P>
Sources from relevant government departments pointed out that
China's computer market has entered the maturation stage. They
also noted that local computer industries, especially the PC
industry, have kept pace with the worldwide industry in terms of
research and development, marketing and applications.
</P>
<P>
Forecasts indicate that China's computer market will record
total 1998 sales of 165 billion yuan, with the figure expected to
grow to over 200 billion yuan in 1999. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
