<HEADLINE> Sinn Fein Leader Agrees to Return to Peace Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Sinn Fein leader Gerry Adams said
Thursday that he wanted his party back at the Northern Ireland
talks table "as soon as possible."
</P>
<P>
But he said it was up to the leadership in the party to make a
decision on that matter.
</P>
<P>
"My own view is that we should seek to go back into the talks
at the earliest possible opportunity. But that is not a decision
for me alone. We are a collective leadership. We will consult,"
Adams told reporters outside 10 Downing Street after meeting with
British Prime Minister Tony Blair.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein, the political wing of the Irish Republican Army
(IRA), was expelled from the multi-party peace talks last month
for IRA's alleged involvement in two killings.
</P>
<P>
The party was allowed to rejoin the talks on March 9 on
condition that IRA take no more terrorist acts.
</P>
<P>
However, Sinn Fein insists that it would not return to the talk
table until a meeting between Adams and Blair.
</P>
<P>
Referring to his meeting with Blair, Adams said the talks were
a "good, positive engagement."
</P>
<P>
He also said he hoped the nationalists and unionists in
Northern Ireland could resolve their differences at the talk table.
</P>
<P>
Sinn Fein struggles for the separation of Northern Ireland from
Britain and then a unification with the Republic of Ireland. But Sinn
Fein's participation to the peace process is crucial if Britain
and Ireland are to win a settlement that could be endorsed by both
Catholics and Protestants, alienated by a quarter century of
sectarian strife. 
</P>
