<HEADLINE> US Conditions for Backing Abacha's </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The United States has pledged to
accept Nigeria's head of state General Sani Abacha as the next
civilian president provided the decision to draft him inro the
presidential race is a "collective one."
</P>
<P>
Although Washington canvasses a free and fair process in
choosing candidates for the August presidential election, it will
recognize Abacha if he emerges as president through an open
contest.
</P>
<P>
Disclosing this Wednesday in the Nigerian capital Abuja,
William Twaddell, U.S. ambassador to the country, cautioned the
Nigerian government to leave the contest open to all Nigerians to
participate in, the press reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. position is similar to th view of Salim Ahmed Salim,
secretary-general of the Organization of African Unity.
</P>
<P>
Salim said here Monday on his way to Sierra Leone to attend
President Ahmed Tejan Kabbah's reinstatement ceremony that only
Nigerians can decide whether General Abacha should succeed
himself.
</P>
<P>
Under the Nigerian military government's transition to civil
rule program, presidential election will start on August 1 and
the elected government will be inaugurated two months later.
</P>
<P>
However, no official presidential candidate has been produced
by the five political parties less than five months ahead of the
election, apparently waiting for the decision of the head of
state.
</P>
<P>
Abacha, who started to head the current administration in late
1993, has been tight-mouthed on whether or not he wants to
succeed himself, saying that the issue should be decided by the
constituency.
</P>
<P>
Recently, campaigns to support or oppose Abacha to run the
race have gained momentum.
</P>
<P>
Last week, a two-day two-million-man carnival-like rally was
held in the capital to ask Abacha to contest the forthcoming
election. The rally, supported by the government, went on in good
order under tight police protection.
</P>
<P>
However, another five-million-man rally in Lagos, the economic
center of the country, organized by pro-democracy and anti-Abacha
groups, was dispersed by armed police before it officially took
off last Tuesday afternoon.
</P>
<P>
While the anti-Abacha campaigners are voicing protest against
the police suppression, the Abuja rally organizers have announced
to hold similar activities in other parts of the country.
</P>
<P>
It is predicted that the head of state would break the silence
under mounting pressure. 
</P>
</TEXT>
