<BODY>
<HEADLINE> UN Calls for Aid to Transport Links in Tanzania </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 12 (Xinhua) - The United Nations has
appealed for immediate aid to repair the flood-hit transport
links to ease serious food shortages in Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
"Priority should be focused on transport constraints and
moving food as soon as possible to areas of need rather than on
injecting further quantities of relief food," the World Food
Program (WFP) and the Food and Agriculture Organization (FAO)
said in a joint report issued Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report, based on a joint assessment mission conducted
recently, said a poor transport network was acting as a severe
constraint on Tanzania's economic development.
</P>
<P>
"In the coming months, logistical limitations in food movement
and the pace at which transport difficulties are resolved will be
as important determinants of food security as the overall food
supply situation in the country," the report said.
</P>
<P>
The figures provided by the Food Security Department said
Tanzania's stock of cereals, mainly maize, stood at an estimated
350,000 tons at the beginning of February and per-capita cereal
consumption in Tanzania, whose population is about 30 million,
was at some 192 kg per year.
</P>
<P>
President Benjamin Mkapa of Tanzania, which suffered a severe
drought in late 1996 and early 1997 and destructive floods
resulted from the unprecedented rainfall attributed to the El
Nino weather phenomenon in late 1997 and early this year, has
appealed for emergent international food aid.
</P>
<P>
While donors responded generously and Tanzania waived import
duties on grain shipments, traders found it difficult to move the
food to the famine threatening areas due to the paralyzed
transport network. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
