<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Uganda's Ruling Party Wins Local Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KAMPALA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Uganda's ruling National
Resistant Movement (NRM) has won the sub-county level local
election, the New Vision reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Among the 672 declared Local Council Three (LC3) chairmanships
in sub-counties, 539 were won by NRM, 88 by oppositions and 45
are still to be established by their winner's political
affiliation, the report said.
</P>
<P>
There are 895 sub-counties in Uganda, each having a chairman
which is elected by secret ballot.
</P>
<P>
Under the election rule in Uganda, voters elect their
executive committee and its chairman in villages, before the
elected form Local Council One and elect the executive committee
and its chairman of the upper-level parish.
</P>
<P>
Members of the parish, sub-county, county, district executive
committees form the Local Council Two, Three, Four and Five and
elect the higher level executive committee and its chairman.
</P>
<P>
Uganda has some 45,000 villages, 5,000 parishes, 900
sub-counties, 70 counties and 45 districts.
</P>
<P>
NRM enjoyed overwhelming victories in the western part of the
country, while the opposition won in some central sub-counties.
</P>
<P>
But P. Kintu, the new chairman in Nakawa, an electorate in
Kampala, explained that the NRM lost the polls in some areas in
Kampala due to lack of discipline among the ranks of NRM, which
had resulted in split ballots.
</P>
<P>
Local people enjoyed the mode of government of NRM, and were
not sure what will happen if the opposition won the election, he
said.
</P>
<P>
Ugandan authorities insisted that NRM is not a political
party, with President Yoweri Museveni saying that the multi-party
system causes only chaos and tribalism in his country. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0145 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Stone Material Industry Setting Fast Growth Pace </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
FUZHOU, March 12 (Xinhua) -- China's stone material industry
has sustained an annual growth rate of more than 25 percent since
1981 to become the fastest growing sector in the building material
industry.
</P>
<P>
Zhang Wenbo, vice-chairman of the China Stone Materials
Industry Association, released this information at the opening
ceremony of the first national exhibition of stone materials and
its auxiliary machinery held yesterday in Quanzhou, a city of
Fujian Province in east China.
</P>
<P>
According to Zhang, China's output of granite, marble, terrazzo
and artificial stone materials is second only to Italy. The
industry, which produced 120 million square meters last year,
employs 2.6 million people and has an annual output value of more
than 30 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
Stone materials have replaced cement in first place in China's
building materials exports, he said. In 1997, the industry did 1.1
billion U.S. dollars in foreign trade with 760 million
U.S. dollars of exports, in notable contrast to the 40,000
U.S. dollars of exports in 1981.
</P>
<P>
He also noted that the growth of the industry has stimulated
its auxiliary industries, saying that before the 1990s China had
to import stone technology and equipment. Less than a decade
later, it has hundreds of machinery producers nationwide, whose
products have not only satisfied the domestic market but also been
exported to Southeast Asian, Mideast and East European countries.
</P>
<P>
There are still some problems, however, in further development,
Zhang said. The technology of China's stone industry is low
compared to developed countries and its production scale is
small, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
