<HEADLINE> HK Appropriation Bill 1998 Debated at PLC Meeting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Hong Kong Provisional
Legislative Council (PLC) members debated the Appropriation Bill
1998 during the two afternoon sessions starting Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The Bill, which was introduced to the PLC by Financial
Secretary Donald Tsang Yam-kuen of the Hong Kong Special
Administrative Region (SAR) on February 18 this year, sets out
the government's expenditure proposals for the following
financial year.
</P>
<P>
During the debate which lasted more than 10 hours, PLC members
delivered speeches one after another, expressing their universal
support to the Bill and at the same time presenting their opinions
and suggestions.
</P>
<P>
Lau Hon-chuen said the Bill has been concentrated the wisdom of
the Hong Kong people and formulated on the basis of soliciting
the residents' opinions.
</P>
<P>
Mrs. Tu Elsie quoted Tsang as saying that the conditions under
which he had framed the budget were the most complex faced by a
financial secretary for many years.
</P>
<P>
"I agree with him," she said, adding that Tsang is to be
congratulated on his achievement in those difficult circumstances.
</P>
<P>
"He has given us hope and inspiration that we can ride out the
storm and renew Hong Kong's strength," she said.
</P>
<P>
She stressed: "We need determination, and the dedication of
every department to put Sir Donald's hope into reality".
</P>
<P>
Dr. Leong Che-hung said the Bill has indeed reflected social
demands, proposing to reduce the burden on salaries taxpayers and
raise allowances for individuals or married persons.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he said the cutting of taxes and the increasing of
public expenditure are proposed under a prerequisite for ensuring
increased surpluses.
</P>
<P>
In a word, the present Bill is completely different from the
previous ones before Hong Kong returned to China last July, he
stressed.
</P>
<P>
The suggestions and opinions raised by PLC members during the
sessions mainly focused on such issues as the adjustment of light
diesel oil duty, investment in education and policy on medical and
health work.
</P>
<P>
In addition, members of the PLC also addressed questions for
written replies from the SAR government on various policy areas
during the meeting. 
</P>
</TEXT>
