<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Air Pollution, Illegal Dumping, HK Top Environmental Problems: SAR Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HONG KONG, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Worsening air pollution and
illegal dumping have become the most prominent problems that
officials of Hong Kong's Environmental Protection Department (EPD)
are to tackle, director of the department said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"We have had another busy year with some significant successes.
We can not pretend, however, that Hong Kong's environment is in
good shape," said Robert J.S. Law in an annual press briefing
here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Emissions from diesel engines are one of the main causes of
Hong Kong's air pollution problems and a pilot scheme is being
conducted to introduce liquefied petroleum gas (LPG) fueled taxis
in the hope of replacing the existing diesel fueled taxis.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the local taxi trade will soon agree that LPG
taxis are acceptable in both operational and economic terms," said
Law.
</P>
<P>
To reduce air pollution, the EPD has managed to further
lower the sulfur content in automotive diesel to 0.05 percent and
introduced much tougher emission standards (Euro II standards) for
large diesel vehicles.
</P>
<P>
And it has also completed a pilot scheme for using a tougher,
dynamometer-based method for checking smoke emissions from diesel
vehicles.
</P>
<P>
Illegal dumping is on the rise, according to the department
chief. At least 150 sites have been found for illegal disposal of
such wastes as those from construction sites, and dead animals and
rubber tires.
</P>
<P>
Law said that through various elements of a plan to be
released around the middle of this year, it is hoped to achieve
significant reduction in the amount of waste that must be disposed
 of at Hong Kong's landfills.
</P>
<P>
One of the most important elements of the plan will be the
introduction of large, waste-to-energy incinerators and an ongoing
study of providing latest technology is expected to be finished by
the end of this financial year, according to Law.
</P>
<P>
The EPD will also work in other key areas, such as phasing out
of noisy percussive piling hammers in built-up areas and making
proposals for retrofitting existing roads with noise abatement
measures, he added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
