<HEADLINE> China Stands for Complete Prohibition, Thorough Destruction </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GENEVA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Disarmament Ambassador Li
Changhe reaffirmed here Thursday that China has always stood for
the complete prohibition and thorough destruction of nuclear
weapons.
</P>
<P>
The cessation of nuclear arms race and nuclear disarmament is
the first agenda item of the Conference on Disarmament (CD) and
also an issue to which all countries attach great importance, Li
said when delivering his first formal statement in a plenary
session of the CD in his capacity of the new Chinese Ambassador
for Disarmament Affairs.
</P>
<P>
Stressing that China has been opposed to the nuclear arms race
and the policy of nuclear deterrence, Li said:
</P>
<P>
"Since the very first day when it came into possession of
nuclear weapons, China has undertaken not to be the first to use
such weapons at any time and under any circumstances.
</P>
<P>
"It has also made unilateral and unconditional commitment not
to use or threaten to use nuclear weapons against
non-nuclear-weapon states or nuclear-weapon-free zones.
</P>
<P>
"China has all along supported the efforts of
non-nuclear-weapon states to establish nuclear-weapon-free zones
on a voluntary basis."
</P>
<P>
Therefore, Li pointed out, China's nuclear weapons do not
constitute a threat to any country.
</P>
<P>
China actively participated in the negotiations on the
Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty (CTBT) and signed the
treaty, Li said. It supports the commencement of negotiations in
the CD on a convention banning the production of fissile material
for nuclear weapons. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
