<HEADLINE> ADB Approves Loan to Thailand </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Asian Development Bank (ADB)
approved Thursday a 500 million U.S. dollar loan to Thailand to
mitigate the impact of the economic crisis, especially on the poor
and disadvantaged.
</P>
<P>
This is the first major assistance for the social sector in the
current currency crisis and is the biggest social-sector loan ever
provided by the ADB, a news release from the Manila-based bank
said.
</P>
<P>
The loan is part of the ADB's 1.2 billion dollars contribution
to the 17.2 billion dollars IMF-led rescue package.
</P>
<P>
The loan will help the social sector program developed by the
Thai government with the assistance of the ADB in cooperation with
a number of donor agencies.
</P>
<P>
The program will support reforms in the labor, health and
social welfare and education sectors.
</P>
<P>
It is specifically designed to support poor people who have
been laid off as a result of the current economic crisis, students
who may have to drop out of school due to their parents' increased
hardship, and other vulnerable groups.
</P>
<P>
It will also initiate structural reforms to boost the
competitiveness of the Thai economy by developing human resources
and reducing inefficiencies in social services.
</P>
<P>
To help implement the program, the ADB has also approved three
technical assistance grants totaling 2.1 million dollars, to help
the government establish systems to monitor the social impact of
the crisis. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
