<HEADLINE> BOJ Chief Offers to Step Down </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TOKYO, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Bank of Japan (BOJ) Governor Yasuo
Matsushita said Thursday he had offered to resign to take the
blame for the arrest of a senior BOJ official suspected of
accepting bribes.
</P>
<P>
In a statement, Matsushita said he telephoned Prime Minister
Ryutaro Hashimoto Wednesday and expressed his intention to step
down.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto is expected to release Matsushita from his duties
before the central bank makes institutional changes in line with a
revised central bank law, which from April will give it greater
independence, government sources said.
</P>
<P>
Matsushita's five-year term of office was to expire in December
1999.
</P>
<P>
Senior Deputy Governor Toshihiko Fukui is widely believed to be
a strong candidate for the top BOJ position. But since he is
already a high-ranking officer at the bank, which is mired in
scandal, opposition could limit him to only an interim
appointment, the sources said.
</P>
<P>
On Wednesday, Tokyo prosecutors arrested Yasuyuki Yoshizawa,
chief of the Capital Markets Division at the BOJ Credit and Market
Management Department. He was suspected of taking bribes worth 4.3
million yen (about 33,858 U.S. dollars) in the form of
entertainment over four years from two major commercial banks, in
exchange for confidential information about central bank
operations in the financial market. 
</P>
</TEXT>
