<HEADLINE> Lebanon's Property Company Grows by 30 Percent </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIRUT, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Solidere, Lebanon's real
estate giant and symbol of the country's post-war reconstruction
drive, posted a growth of 30 percent in net profit in 1997, the
Daily Star newspaper said on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
According to a financial report issued by the company,
Solidere's net profit last year soared to 77.8 million U.S.
dollars, compared to 59.8 million dollars in 1996.
</P>
<P>
The 30-percent profit growth was attained due to an upturn of
sales and rental income of the company's properties, the Daily
Star quoted the report as saying.
</P>
<P>
The company succeeded in selling a total of 136,223 square
meters of floor space at an average price of 1,056 dollars per
square meter, the report said.
</P>
<P>
But most of the company's net profit lay in the sales of 144
million dollars in real estate in central Beirut. Solidere is
leading a multi-billion-dollar strive to rebuild the war-ravaged
capital.
</P>
<P>
"The Management is confident that the outlook for 1998 is
promising, based on the current activities of the company in land
and real estate development and the continued solid investor and
occupier interest in the Beirut central district," the report
added.
</P>
<P>
It showed that the company's cash position at the end of 1997
was 229.9 million dollars, and its accounts and notes receivable
amounted to 214 million dollars at the same time.
</P>
<P>
As the report was issued, the price of Solidere's A share at
the Beirut Stock Exchange rose by daily maximum rate of 5
percent. Shareholders decide to keep their stocks in anticipation
of further surge. 
</P>
</TEXT>
