<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> U.S. Automakers Cut Costs </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 11 (Xinhua) -- American automakers are
using cost-cutting to drive profits in a period of flattening
sales and limited price increase.
</P>
<P>
General Motors Corp. announced Wednesday it will cut 4 billion
dollars in costs this year, compared with 3.5 billion dollars last
year.
</P>
<P>
Ford Motor Co. has already stated that it wants to slash 1
billion dollars in costs this year, following a trim of 3 billion
dollars last year.
</P>
<P>
Chrysler Corp. also wants to cut 1.5 billion dollars in the
one-year period ending this summer.
</P>
<P>
The savings will come from lower materials costs, manufacturing
efficiencies and smaller engineering expenses, said Jim Finn,
spokesman for General Motors.
</P>
<P>
Jack Smith, General Motors' chairman, told a group of analysts
at the company's annual meeting opened in Detroit that
cost-cutting opportunities are "practically limitless."
</P>
<P>
The analysts, however, expect U.S. automakers to cut tens of
thousands of jobs in the coming year by not replacing workers who
retire. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0165 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Economist Stresses Government Role in Financial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The government plays an important
role in overseeing and regulating the financial system, which is
essential for steady economic growth and stability, a leading
economist said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In his keynote speech before the end of the week-long Asian
Development Forum, Joseph Stiglitz, senior vice president and
chief economist of the World Bank, said that deep, efficient and
robust financial systems are essential for sustainable
development.
</P>
<P>
"But left themselves, financial markets will not become deep,
efficient, or robust," he said.
</P>
<P>
Stiglitz said that the government plays an essential role,
"both in directly overseeing and regulating the financial system
and also in establishing the correct incentives to encourage
prudential and productive behavior."
</P>
<P>
On the role of the financial system in the current East Asian
financial crisis, Stiglitz said that when financial systems are
working well, the result can be strong economic growth.
</P>
<P>
But when financial systems are working badly, the result can be
crises and prolonged periods of slower growth, he said.
</P>
<P>
"The roots of the crisis are not in government profligacy, but
in private sector decisions that made the economies vulnerable to
a sudden withdrawal of confidence," Stiglitz said.
</P>
<P>
He said that the biggest problems were the mis-allocation of
investment, most notably to speculative real estate, and the risky
form of financing, especially short-term debt on international
markets.
</P>
<P>
The buildup of short-term, unhedged debt left East Asia's
economies vulnerable to a sudden collapse of confidence, he said.
</P>
<P>
"As a result, capital outflows, and with them depreciating
currencies and falling asset prices, exacerbated the strains on
private sector balance sheets and thus proved self-fulfilling,"
the economist said.
</P>
<P>
Stiglitz said that improving the financial system can lead to
higher growth and reduce the likelihood and severity of crises.
</P>
<P>
"In thinking about financial reform, we need to treat
liberalization as a means rather than an end. Instead of pushing
for immediate de-regulation, we should be trying to understand the
important role the government plays in financial markets," he
said.
</P>
<P>
During the meeting, which was sponsored by the World Bank and
the Asian Development Bank, 350 economists, government officials
and journalists have discussed lessons of the Asian crisis and
Asia's future development strategies. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
