<BODY>
<HEADLINE> EximBank Set to Increase Lending Volume </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Import and Export Bank of
China (EximBank) plans to increase loans to exporters by as much
as 60 percent in order to boost 1998 exports.
</P>
<P>
The bank plans to grant total loans of 24.3 billion yuan, said
a bank official, adding that the funds will be mainly used to
finance exports of vessels, complete sets of equipment, and
telecommunications and electronics products.
</P>
<P>
He said EximBank will continue to grant loans to state-owned
enterprises, but will also expand services to cover joint-stock
companies controlled by the state, and collective and
foreign-funded enterprises in which Chinese partners hold
controlling stake.
</P>
<P>
EximBank, founded in 1994 to finance China's exports of high
value-added capital goods, has granted export seller's credits of
well over 40 billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
China's export growth has slowed significantly in the first two
months of this year as a result of the ongoing financial crisis in
Southeast Asia and massive currency devaluations in Thailand, the
Philippines, the Republic of Korea and various other Asian nations.
</P>
<P>
China's exports grew by 20.9 percent during 1997, with the
trade surplus hitting a record 40.3 billion US dollars. 
</P>
</TEXT>
