<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Consumer Rights Better Protected </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Different levels of
administrations for industry and commerce in China dealt with
18,800 cases involving infringement upon consumer rights in 1997,
retrieving losses of about 300 million yuan for consumers.
</P>
<P>
The number of handled cases increased by 25.8 percent over the
previous year, according to Gan Guoping, deputy director of the
State Administration for Industry and Commerce.
</P>
<P>
A national network has been formed to handle consumer
complaints through various channels, Gan said, adding that Beijing
Wednesday opened a special telephone line to receive complaints,
with 150 calls received in the first three hours.
</P>
<P>
In March of last year, the State Administration for Industry
and Commerce issued a series of concrete measures for local
administrations to hear and handle disputes concerning consumers'
rights.
</P>
<P>
Gan said that the awareness of consumer rights has
increased. An investigation targeting city dwellers shows that
more than 70 percent of the consumers basically know about the Law
on Protection of Consumers' Rights.
</P>
<P>
The country's administrations for industry and commerce handled
72,500 cases concerning the manufacturing and marketing of shoddy
and fake products with a total value of 1.71 billion yuan. Also
handled were 2,500 illegal pyramid sale cases.
</P>
<P>
Gan said protecting consumers' rights covers the interests of
more than one billion Chinese, and it is of great significance to
regulating market order and promoting social stability and unity.
</P>
<P>
He vowed to broaden official channels to accept consumer
complaints and give priority to solving hot problems.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
