<HEADLINE> U.S. Delivers First Two AWACS to Japan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 11 (Xinhua) -- The United States Wednesday
delivered the first two of four airborne warning and control
system (AWACS) aircraft to Japanese military, according to reports
from Boeing company.
</P>
<P>
The aircraft were manufactured by Boeing company under a
contract of 2 billion U.S. dollars and they were the first AWACS
jets to be built on Boeing 767 airframe.
</P>
<P>
AWACS electronic gear had been loaded on Boeing 707 platform
until 1991 and there are currently 66 E-3 707 AWACS planes
operating around the world.
</P>
<P>
The AWACS aircraft act as a high-flying "eye in the sky." They
can help direct troops on the ground and monitor airborne activity
in the sky.
</P>
<P>
The first two AWACS aircraft will be flown to Japan later this
month, Boeing officials said, adding that the second two will be
delivered early next year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
