<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0175 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> "One Country, Two Systems" Best Option to Keep Taiwan's Existing System, Life Style: Member </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- A member of the Ninth National
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC) said here today that the "one country, two
systems" concept is the best way to maintain Taiwan's existing
social and economy systems.
</P>
<P>
This is the best option to guarantee that Taiwan compatriots'
practical and long-term interests will be freed from any harms.
</P>
<P>
Zeng Chonglang, advisor of the Central Committee of the Taiwan
Democratic Self-Government League and vice-president of the
All-China Federation of Taiwan Compatriots, said that "we know
very well what most of the Taiwan compatriots are thinking about
and understand their desire to maintain the trend for increasing
economic and trade ties as well as people-to-people contracts
across the straits.
</P>
<P>
The principle is suitable for the country's realities and is
able to best protect the interests of Taiwan compatriots, he
added.
</P>
<P>
According to the concept of "one country, two systems," the
compatriots of Taiwan can retain their existing social and
economic systems and their style of life after its return to the
motherland, and Taiwan can keep its troops and have
administrative, legislative and judicial powers.
</P>
<P>
The central government will neither send any people to station
there, nor levy any tax from Taiwan, Zeng said.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the situation in Hong Kong has been very good and
become still more prosperous after its return to the motherland,
and the flow of international capital into Hong Kong is
increasing. Recently, he added, Chief Executive Tung Chee Hwa of
the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region said that Hong Kong's
economic prospects remains bright.
</P>
<P>
"Sustained economic growth and ongoing reform and opening-up in
the interior areas of the country will enable Hong Kong to have
a still more optimistic future," he said.
</P>
<P>
"We welcome that the Taiwan compatriots to go on following Hong
Kong's development and promote the settlement of the Taiwan
question at an early date by drawing on Hong Kong's successful
experience in implementing "one country, two systems" concept,"
Zeng Chonglang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0176 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Poverty-Relief Loans Paying Dividends in Yunnan Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUNMING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Woman farmer Fu Fengdi's dream to
have her own cattle has come true because of the small
poverty-relief loans adopted in the mountainous areas of Yunnan
Province.
</P>
<P>
Last year, Fu started by raising 40 chicks on a 1,000-yuan loan
from local government, and later bought cattle. Her family is only
one of the 10,000 impoverished rural households that have
benefited from the practice of small loans.
</P>
<P>
The ethnic-filled province still has 4.4 million poor, and the
provincial government has been making efforts to wipe out
poverty. Small poverty-relief loans is the latest tactic to help
the province's impoverished people.
</P>
<P>
The one-year loan for a maximum of 1,000 yuan is paid directly
to farmers. Last year, Yunnan introduced the loan program in 25
townships. As a result, 100 percent of the farmers receiving loans
improved their lives and paid back the loans.
</P>
<P>
In 1998, the province will spend 250 million yuan to expand the
loan program in 73 counties and, in the next three years, another
900 million yuan will be allocated for credit in all 506 poor
townships, Gov. Li Jiating said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
