<BODY>
<HEADLINE> E. African Summit to Upgrade Coop </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DAR ES SALAAM, March 12 (Xinhua) - Three East African
Cooperation (EAC) states are expected to hold a summit in August
in Arusha to sign an agreement to upgrade their cooperation into
a treaty, sources from the EAC Secretariat said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The treaty will help define in clearer terms the mode and
inclination of cooperation among the three member states,
Tanzania, Kenya and Uganda, in specific areas, they said.
</P>
<P>
The long-expected East African Passports, which grant the
holders free traveling among the three states, will also be
officially launched during the summit, the sources added.
</P>
<P>
Members states of the EAC, which will greet its second
birthday on Saturday, are busy studying the draft of the treaty
to be tabled at the Permanent Tripartite Commission, the highest
EAC decision-making body.
</P>
<P>
Jakaya Kikwete, current chairman of the Tripartite Commission,
who is also Tanzanian Foreign Minister, will host a cocktail
party to celebrate the anniversary in Tanzania's northern city of
Arusha which seats the EAC Secretariat.
</P>
<P>
The EAC was founded on the basis of the defunct East African
Community which collapsed in 1977 due to reasons including the
divergence of economic policies then pursued by the member
states, the continued perception of disproportionate sharing of
benefits and lack of adequate compensation mechanisms.
</P>
<P>
Since its foundation, the EAC has tried to address the
shortcomings inherent in the past cooperation initiatives.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
