<HEADLINE> Jilin Earns Nearly $60 Million in Tourism </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHANGCHUN, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Northeast China's Jilin Province
cashed in on tourism last year with an increase of 11.7 percent
over 1996, according to local authorities.
</P>
<P>
More than 200,000 overseas tourists spent 59.35 million
U.S. dollars during their stays in the province, which is known
for its winter resorts near the Changbai Mountains.
</P>
<P>
The province's tourism agencies promoted special tour packages
from the beginning of last year. The local government invested 250
million yuan (30 million U.S. dollars) into the thriving business.
</P>
<P>
In addition, a tourism center jointly funded by China and the
Republic of Korea was established near the Changbai Mountains.
</P>
<P>
Tourism programs featuring snow sports were also popular.
Jilin, together with three enterprises, is developing a 35
million-yuan snow-and-ice sports center, which is scheduled to
open in August, local officials said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the province standardized the profitable business by
adopting a few regulations to improve services which could attract
more outside travelers, officials said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
