<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Australia Pioneers New Lifesaving Computer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CANBERRA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Australian researchers are using
computer imaging technology to produce three-dimensional images of
the inside of the human body and software systems capable of
making a diagnosis to help doctors save more lives, avoid pain and
discomfort for patients.
</P>
<P>
Major advances in the diagnosis of breast and cervical cancer,
skin cancer, lung disease and other potentially deadly conditions
are on the way thanks to a revolution in the use of computers to
analyze medical images such as X-rays, ultrasound and
computer-aided-test scans, Australia's largest research body the
Commonwealth Scientific and Industrial Research Organization
(CSIRO) announced here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
CSIRO scientists have already developed a way to make three
dimensional models of a patient's own internal organs, surgeons
can plan the least-invasive form of treatment without first
opening them up.
</P>
<P>
In a national science briefing to some Australian MPs and
journalists Thursday at the Parliament House in Canberra, experts
said they had developed several computer-aided diagnosis systems
capable of telling what is abnormal from the normal in some part
of human body.
</P>
<P>
Dr. Laurie Wilson with CSIRO Telecommunications and Industrial
Physics department, said the research body, in collaboration with
others, had developed some innovative applications which mad use
of computer representations of anatomical knowledge.
</P>
<P>
The first application is a computer-aided diagnosis system
called "an expert assistant" to assist clinicians in their
assessment of chest X-rays.
</P>
<P>
Radiologist Bruce Doust described the system as capable of
identifying the major features of a chest X-ray, performing a
number of measurements, detecting a range of abnormalities and
producing a diagnosis "report" couched in familiar radiological
terminology.
</P>
<P>
He said the system, which is still in an early clinical test,
would improve the speed, accuracy and reliability of screening for
breast cancer.
</P>
<P>
The system would be available 24 hours a day and would never
get tired, Doust said.
</P>
<P>
Victor Skladnev, managing director of Sydney medical technology
firm Polartechnics PL, said his company is developing Skin Polar
Probe, a detecting device for melanoma, the skin cancer for which
Australia has the highest incidence in the world, using image
analysis techniques developed by CSIRO.
</P>
<P>
"The average general practitioner sees only a few melanomas a
year, and identifying them from other skin blemishes is not so
simple. It can mean that up to half of all melanomas are missed,"
said Skladnev.
</P>
<P>
"The Skin Polar Probe should change all that, by giving general
practitioners the ability to diagnose suspected melanomas on the
spot, enabling swift treatment if they are malignant and avoiding
needless surgery if they are not," he said.
</P>
<P>
The company had already developed a "doctor in a box", a
computerized device for detecting cervical cancer, which was due
to undergo trials around the world in the next few months.
</P>
<P>
The device is the first of its kind in the world and would be
mass produced late this year or early next year, he said in an
interview with Xinhua. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0185 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Largest Bank Leans Toward Large, Efficient Enterprises </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- China's largest bank will direct
more of its loans to large, well-performing, state-owned
enterprises to aid the country's economic restructuring effort.
</P>
<P>
The Industrial and Commercial Bank of China (ICBC) will, on the
basis of market situation and state industrial policies, use its
own rating of clients to guide loan extensions and will consider
enterprises rated at A or above as its basic clients, according to
bank president Liu Tinghuan.
</P>
<P>
Priority will be given to large- and medium-size state-owned
enterprises with marketable products, good economic efficiency and
sound credibility; to large joint-stock companies and
overseas-funded firms in which the state participates; and to
medium- and small-size companies with triple-A ratings, the
president said.
</P>
<P>
He said that 80 percent of this year's new loans will be
extended to companies rated A or above, with the number of
companies with ratings of AA or better hitting no less than 40
percent of the loan portfolio.
</P>
<P>
To that end, ICBC will implement a special loan program among
some selected super-large companies and will continue to sign
bank-enterprise lending agreements with the country's 512 key
industrial firms and 300 key commercial businesses, according to
Liu.
</P>
<P>
The bank will, in principle, not increase its lending to
companies rated BB or lower and will instead step up its effort to
recover loans, the president said.
</P>
<P>
China's central bank, the People's Bank of China, has decided
to phase out the credit quota system among state-owned commercial
banks and introduce asset-to-liability management of bank credits
starting this year, a move that gives banks greater autonomy in
making lending decisions.
</P>
<P>
ICBC's yuan-denominated loans this year will be 205 billion
yuan more than last year. Of that amount, 155 billion yuan will be
for working capital loans and 50 billion yuan for investment in
fixed-assets, according to the bank's work plan this year.
</P>
<P>
Statistics show that ICBC had more than 2.15 trillion yuan in
outstanding deposits and over 1.9 trillion yuan in unpaid loans by
the end of last year.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
