<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0186 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Water Level Surges in Lower Yangtze River Probably Due to El Nino </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WUHAN, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Higher-than-normal water levels on
the lower reaches of the Yangtze River during the dry winter
season is being attributed to the "El Nino" phenomenon.
</P>
<P>
Between November and February, water levels on the middle and
lower Yangtze River have been higher than normal because of higher
rainfall totals, said Wang Jun, senior engineer in the weather
forecast department of the Ministry of Water Resources.
</P>
<P>
Rain mainly fell in the areas of Dongting Lake, Boyang Lake in
central China's Hubei and Hunan provinces and Hangzhou, a city in
east China's Zhejiang Province, Wang said. Nanchang Railway
Station in Hubei Province has recorded 369 millimeters of rainfall
since the beginning of this year.
</P>
<P>
The water level of many river sections below Hankou in Hubei
Province rose 2-to-3 meters compared with average heights.
</P>
<P>
Wang said that El Nino, a weather condition affecting
atmospheric and ocean currents, had a wide-ranging impact in
1997. Research by Chinese meteorologists suggests that the dry
season following an El Nino year usually results in
heavier-than-normal rainfall along the middle and lower reaches of
the Yangtze River.
</P>
<P>
The Hankou Hydrologic Station's statistics show that the
January water level on this section of the Yangtze River has
exceeded 17 meters nine times, and that six out of those nine
times followed an El Nino year.
</P>
<P>
According to Wang, China is intensifying research on a possible
connection between El Nino and the hydrological situation of the
lower Yangtze River. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
