<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippines Discusses Ways to End Conflicts in South </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The newly-created Quick Reaction
Team met on Thursday to discuss matters concerning possible
violations of a joint cease-fire agreement between the Philippine
government and the rebel Moro Islamic Liberation Front (MILF).
</P>
<P>
The 18-member team is an independent body formed on March 3 by
the government and the MILF to speed up resolution of armed
conflicts between the two sides or between the MILF and former
guerrillas belonging to the Moro National Liberation Front (MNLF).
</P>
<P>
The MILF and the MNLF have had several clashes lately in the
southern provinces of Maguindanao and North Cotabato, in which
about a dozen combatants were killed, scores of others injured and
residents displaced in affected villages.
</P>
<P>
Eliseo Mercado, chairman of an independent fact-finding
committee of the government and MILF, was unanimously chosen to
head the team.
</P>
<P>
Earlier, Police Director Chief Franco Calida of the Autonomous
Region in Muslim Mindanao said the team had to be formed following
complaints from peace negotiators that the existing fact-finding
group led by Mercado has been "very passive" in resolving the
conflicts.
</P>
<P>
Calida, who is also vice chairman for the government side of
the Committee on the Cessation of Hostilities, said the
newly-organized team is assured of a more responsive and swift
action with the help of officials and troops from both warring
camps.
</P>
<P>
The team is composed of six representatives each from the
government, the MILF and the fact-finding committee.
</P>
<P>
The MILF, a breakaway faction from the MNLF and now the biggest
Muslim rebel group in the country, refuses to be part of the peace
agreement signed between the government and the MNLF in 1996 and
wants its own peace accord with Manila.  
</P>
</TEXT>
