<HEADLINE> Senior Religious Figures Praise Freedom in Religious Belief </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Senior religious figures are
unanimous that the religious policy of the Communist Party of
China (CPC) has created a fine environment for religious affairs.
</P>
<P>
These personities, who are also members of the Ninth National
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC), are attending the ongoing First Session of the
CPPCC Ninth National Committee.
</P>
<P>
Zhao Puchu, chairman of the Buddhist Association of China, said
the all-round, correct implementation of the Party's policy of
freedom in religious belief, booming economy, improved living
standard of the people, social stability and national unity have
all contributed greatly to a fine environment for the development
of religions.
</P>
<P>
He noted that the people of religious circles should in turn
adapt themselves to socialist society and go all out to support the
government to enhance its management of religious affairs so as
to serve China's stability and development.
</P>
<P>
Jin Luxian, vice-chairman of the Chinese Catholic Bishops
College, said that over the past five years, the legitimate rights
and interests of religious circles and normal religious activities
have been well protected. Moreover, he added, the government has
scored tremendous successes in China's economic growth, and this is
favorable to the development of religions in the country.
</P>
<P>
Wan Yaobin, vice-chairman of the Islamic Association of China,
said there are approximately 20 million moslems in China, who are
satisfied with the country's religious policy.
</P>
<P>
Han Wenzao, chairman of the China Christian Council, said that
religion should carry on the tradition of patriotism and
contribute to the country's social progress and development.
</P>
<P>
Min Zhiting, vice-chairman of the China Daoist Association,
said that along with the registration of religious sites to the
government, the legitimate rights and interests of the religious
circles can be protected better still.  
</P>
</TEXT>
