<HEADLINE> Kabbah Cuts Cabinet Members by Half </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LAGOS, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Returned President Ahmed Tejan
Kabbah has reduced the number of cabinet ministers from 30 to 15
to show his determination for an efficient government, the Daily
Times reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
President Kabbah, who ended his more than nine months of
self-exile in neighboring Guinea Tuesday, has also pledged to run
a broad-based government his time around.
</P>
<P>
To do this effectively, he promised to set up a policy
advisory committee to evaluate and advise him on all policy
matters of governance and monitor the performance of public
offices, parastatals and public corporations.
</P>
<P>
The president called on his people to cooperate with him fully
in order to achieve the set goals of government for the
betterment of the people.
</P>
<P>
The past poor performance of the government functionaries,
such as bureaucracy, and faulty policies are part of the factors
that triggered off the coup in the tiny west African country last
May, forcing Kabbah and his government to flee to Guinea.
</P>
<P>
He also promised to create and sustain an atmosphere for the
press to operate without fear or favor.
</P>
<P>
The size of the national army would be decided in the near
future, he added.
</P>
<P>
Kabbah regained power in Freetown after the west African peace
keeping force ECOMOG dislodged the military junta in mid
February.
</P>
<P>
With many soldiers loyal to the junta and its allied rebel
group having surrendered, ECOMOG Force Commander Maj.-Gen.
Timothy Shelpidi said the Nigerian-led force is still on the look
out for the ousted junta leader Johnny Paul Koroma. 
</P>
</TEXT>
