<HEADLINE> Science Enhances Enthusiasm of Hubei Cotton Farmers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The introduction of
worm-resistant seeds and the proliferation of cultivation
technology has greatly enhanced the enthusiasm of cotton farmers
and heralded a good 1998 cotton harvest in north China's Hebei
Province.
</P>
<P>
Hebei, one of China's major cotton producers, has witnessed a
significant decrease in cotton growing areas in recent years due
to the rising cost of fertilizers and pesticides, and the failure
to control rampant worm infestations.
</P>
<P>
The province planted cotton on a mere 377,100 ha in 1997, a
substantial decrease on the historic high of well over 600,000
hectares.
</P>
<P>
The provincial government initiated a program to reverse the
situation by introducing new breeds of cotton seeds which offer
greater resistance to worms and higher per unit output. In
addition, the program can effectively reduce production costs by
between 750-1200 yuan per hectare.
</P>
<P>
A recent survey conducted by the provincial statistical bureau
revealed that this year's area planted to cotton will approach
424,000 hectares. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0193 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> North China Province Invests Heavily on Key Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TAIYUAN, March 12 (Xinhua) -- North China's Shanxi Province,
the country's largest coal base, has injected 10.4 billion yuan
(1.25 billion US dollars) into 23 key projects in the past year.
</P>
<P>
Local officials said that construction of these projects has
been going on smoothly. They include a multi-billion
water-diversion project, a railway line, power plants and
expressways.
</P>
<P>
The Wanjiazhai water-diversion project, called "life project"
for Shanxi, is designed to channel water from the upper reaches of
the Yellow River to coal-rich Shanxi, which often suffers from a
severe shortage of water, through a system of tunnels, aqueduct
pipelines and reservoirs.
</P>
<P>
The whole project will cost 20 billion yuan (about 2.41 billion
US dollars), of which the World Bank will provide 400 million US
dollars in the form of loans.
</P>
<P>
Scheduled for completion in 2001, the project will begin
generating electricity at the end of this year following the
completion of a main dam.
</P>
<P>
Another key project under construction is the Yangcheng Pithead
Power Plant, the world's biggest with a total investment of 13.2
billion yuan.
</P>
<P>
The plant, with six 350,000-kilowatt generating units, will
have an installed capacity of 2.1 million kw. With power produced
there transmitted to energy-thirsty Jiangsu Province in east China
via a 755-km 500-kilovolt line, the plant will be able to provide
more than 10 billion kwh of electricity a year.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, Zhangze Power Plant is now under expansion with
installation of two 300,000-kw generating units for "transporting
electricity" to east China's Shandong Province.
</P>
<P>
To facilitate the coal transportation out of Shanxi, the 252-km
railway line between Houma in Shanxi and Yueshan in Henan Province
was put into trial operation in 1997. And Jincheng-Yangcheng
Expressway was also completed last year for the same purpose.
</P>
<P>
Another 94-km-long expressway linking Yuanping City and
Taiyuan, the provincial capital, is being built with a total
investment of 2.6 billion yuan. It will be completed in October
this year. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
