<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 08:28 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> 3 Israeli Soldiers Responsible for Killing </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JERUSALEM, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The three Israeli soldiers who
killed three Palestinian workers and sparked widespread rioting in
the territories were released Thursday under the order of Army's
Central Commander Uzi Dayan.
</P>
<P>
The release came despite Dayan's public statement that the
initial investigation showed that the Palestinian driver, killed
together with two other Palestinian workers Tuesday evening, was
not intending to launch a terror attack but only trying to cut
into the line at the Tarkumiya roadblock near Hebron.
</P>
<P>
Outraged Palestinians staged widespread clashes with Israeli
soldiers in the West Bank following the killing. Dozens of
protesters were injured Wednesday in clashes with Israeli soldiers
in several places.
</P>
<P>
This was the worst violence in months between the Israelis and
Palestinians, signaling the simmering tensions due to the
prolonged deadlock in the peace process.
</P>
<P>
By releasing the three soldiers, Israeli Army apparently
defended the soldiers' action in opening fire at the van which
was said to have tried to run over the roadblock and injured an
Israeli soldier. The Army's orders give soldiers who suspected
terror attacks the right to open fire, though they are required to
fire warning shots first.
</P>
<P>
Israeli Army promised to continue the investigation and to
inform the Palestinian National Authority (PNA) of all details.
</P>
<P>
In another step to calm the situation, Israeli Defense
Minister Yitzhak Mordechai telephoned PNA's deputy head Mahmoud
Abbas (Abu Mazen) Wednesday night to express sorrow over the
killing. Mordechai updated Abbas his visit late Wednesday to the
Tarkumiya roadblock and called on the PNA to help calm the
tensions.
</P>
<P>
Earlier Tuesday night, Israeli Prime Minister Benjamin
Netanyahu telephoned PNA President Yasser Arafat to offer
condolences to the families of the victims.
</P>
<P>
Speaking late Wednesday while meeting visiting Albanian Prime
Minister Fatos Nano, Netanyahu again called for restoring calm
and warned the PNA against exploiting the incident for political
gains. Commenting on the call on him to pay a condolence visit to
the victim families, Netanyahu only said the security
establishment was checking the possibility. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
