<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0197 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Military Wind Tunnel Benefits Civilian Projects </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese military scientists at a
wind tunnel test base have begun providing more service for the
country's civilian projects.
</P>
<P>
The base is attached to the Commission of Science, Technology
and Industry for National Defense. It formerly was used solely for
China's development of satellites, guided missiles, aircraft and
other national defence projects.
</P>
<P>
However, in support of the country's economic development, the
base is now being used for special wind tunnel tests for such
things as the design of new locomotives. As a result of the
locomotive tests, the front part of the cab was redesigned to
reduce wind resistance. The research played a decisive role in
increasing train speed in the country last year.
</P>
<P>
The base also ran wind tunnel tests for a medium-size truck
developed by central China's Hubei Province. After altering the
design, the air-power resistance coefficient and oil consumption
volume of the truck decreased.
</P>
<P>
The base also has performed wind tunnel tests for such civilian
projects as Asia's highest television tower in Shanghai, an
extension project for Capital International Airport in Beijing and
the Haicang Bridge connecting Haicang with Xiamen Island.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
