<HEADLINE> Shanghai Earmarks 70 Billion Yuan for Environmental Protection </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Shanghai's ambitious plan to
clean up its environment by 2000 has opened a broad arena for
foreign investors, according to the city's Economic Commission.
</P>
<P>
An Economic Commission official said Shanghai from 1996 to
2000 will invest 70 billion yuan in environmental protection,
which include tree planting, wastewater and garbage treatment,
drinking water supply, gas projects as well as the cleaning up of
the Suzhou River.
</P>
<P>
The investment earmarked for environmental protection is the
biggest among all the Chinese cities.
</P>
<P>
Experts at the ongoing "China-Europe Symposium on Environmental
Technology" predict that foreign investors can compete for about
10 billion yuan worth of deals.
</P>
<P>
Currently, the world's major companies related to
environmental protection have stationed themselves in Shanghai, in
the wake of China's preferential policies in environmental
protection. 
</P>
