<HEADLINE> Malaria Epidemic Contained in Southern Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Regional health offices have
contained a malaria epidemic in a southern Philippine island, the
Philippine News Agency reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Mustala Hairon, regional secretary of the
Department of Health in the Autonomous Region in Muslim Mindanao,
as saying that his office had delivered sufficient anti-malaria
services and undertaken other health measures in Laminusa Island,
Sulu province.
</P>
<P>
"With all the help that is pouring into Laminusa and all the
efforts given, the epidemic is contained...It is now under
control," the health official declared.
</P>
<P>
Earlier reports said that 138 people in Laminusa had died from
the malaria epidemic since the disease broke out in February.
</P>
<P>
Hairon said as an added control measure, 301 children in
Laminusa were immunized for measles. Children from neighboring
islands were also recommended for immunization.
</P>
<P>
Hairon, together with the autonomous region Governor Nur
Misuari and other local officials assessed the over-all health
situation in the affected island on March 5.
</P>
<P>
Misuari expressed sympathy with the relatives of those who died
as he distributed relief goods and recommended the setting up of a
potable water system, Hairon said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the report said, health officials in nearby
Tawi-Tawi city have put up a "red alert" around the island to
avert any possible occurrence of the dreaded disease. 
</P>
</TEXT>
