<HEADLINE> Survey: Chinese College Students Concerned About Politics </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
JINAN, March 12 (Xinhua) -- A Work Committee on Higher Learning
of east China's Shandong Province announced that most Chinese
college students concern themselves with state affairs.
</P>
<P>
The committee drew the conclusion from results of a survey of
1,000 university students.
</P>
<P>
The survey reveals that more than 90 percent of the respondents
said they paid a great deal of attention to these events: Hong
Kong's return to the motherland, the 15th National Congress of the
Communist Party of China, the battle against corruption, and
Sino-U.S. relations.
</P>
<P>
A majority of the respondents said that what they most want to
say is: "May the motherland be prosperous" and the "21st century
belongs to China.".
</P>
<P>
Ninety-three percent of those surveyed agreed that the central
government had done a good job in deepening reform, expanding
opening-up and speeding up economic development, as well as in the
development of foreign relations and promotion of the
reunification of the motherland.
</P>
<P>
Another 70 percent of the respondents said that the central
government extended effective efforts in developing science and
education and controlling inflation and stablizing prices.
</P>
<P>
According to the survey, 97 percent of the respondents said the
political situation in the country is quite stable or
comparatively stable.
</P>
<P>
Some 31 percent of those surveyed said China had sustained
rapid and healthy economic development in 1997, while 53 percent
said there are still many problems in addition to the rapid
development. 
</P>
</TEXT>
