<HEADLINE> New Offshore Oil Field Found in Angola </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LUANDA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Angola National Petroleum
Corporation said a new deep-water oil field was discovered by Elf
Exploration Angola, an affiliate of the Elf Petroleum Corporation
of France, which is tapping oil in the Angolan waters.
</P>
<P>
A release issued by the Angola National Petroleum Corporation
said that Elf Exploration Angola discovered an oil field with
large reserves and high-quality oil in Rosa-1 Well 1,405 meters
under sea level, over 200 km northwest of the capital Luanda.
</P>
<P>
During the trial production, the well produces 12,000 barrels
daily. It is revealed that Elf will carry out follow-up
exploration to confirm its actual reserves.
</P>
<P>
The new oil field is the third one found in the No. 17 waters
by Elf Corporation. The other two have reportedly 1,400 million
barrels' oil reserve altogether.
</P>
<P>
Elf Corporation Angola has been operating in the southern
African country for many years. Its discoveries have nearly
doubled Angola's oil reserve and made the country the second
largest oil-producer in the sub-Sahara Africa, next only to
Nigeria.
</P>
<P>
At present, oil has become the main economic pillar in Angola,
with its daily output increased from 600,000 barrels two years
ago to the current 750,000 barrels.
</P>
<P>
It is estimated that Angola's oil production will reach one
million barrels in the beginning of next century. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0206 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Securities Market Witnesses Sound Development (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- China's securities market remains
basically stable and continues to exhibit good prospects for
further growth, according to Zhou Zhengqing, chairman of the China
Securities Regulatory Committee (CSRC).
</P>
<P>
Today's People's Daily quoted Zhou, who serves as deputy
secretary-general of the State Council, as saying that "the
development of China's stock markets remains generally stable,
despite recent fluctuations." Even though the market appears
somewhat bearish when considering previous periods of overheating,
the trend is basically normal when compared to the sluggish market
witnessed in previous years.
</P>
<P>
Stock indices at the end of 1997 showed growth of 30 percent on
a year-on-year basis.
</P>
<P>
Zhou, a deputy to the Ninth National People's Congress, said
his confidence in China's stock markets is based on four factors:
</P>
<P>
Firstly, the national economy will continue to maintain good
growth momentum, with the government pledging to 1998 measures to
ensure an eight percent growth rate for this year.
</P>
<P>
Secondly, deepening the reform of state-owned enterprises
(SOEs) and implementing the reemployment project will greatly
improve the production and efficiency of related enterprises.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, total savings deposits of Chinese citizens stood at a
record 4,600 billion yuan (554.21 billion US dollars) at the end
of 1997. Savings will further promote the desire to invest in
securities, and will in turn create favorable conditions for
expanding sources for financing.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0207 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Securities Market Witnesses Sound Development (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Finally, the program to enhance investor awareness of stock
risks launched at the end of 1996, and the market order
rectification campaign introduced last year have helped to
effectively curb excessive speculation and maintain market order.
</P>
<P>
"The aforementioned factors have been conducive to improving
the efficiency of listed companies and ensuring steady development
of the stock market," said Zhou, who serves concurrently as
director of the State Council's China Securities Commission.
</P>
<P>
Zhou responsed to a question concerning whether listing medium-
and large-sized SOEs will affect investor confidences by pointing
out that "such worries are unnecessary."
</P>
<P>
He noted that China's stock market is in the preliminary stage
of development, and stressed that nurturing market demand will
require a long process since the conditions for large-scale market
expansion are currently inadequate. However, this in no way rules
out market expansion, a prerequisite for development.
</P>
<P>
Each of the world's five largest stock exchanges enjoys market
capitalization in excess of 2,000 billion US dollars, compared to
slightly over 200 billion US dollars for China's exchanges.
</P>
<P>
Stock market capitalization in developed countries usually
accounts for some 80 percent of the GDP, while the figure for
China stands at only 24 percent.
</P>
<P>
"Meeting the needs of economic reform and development requires
that we enlarge the stock market in line with market demand, with
related actions carried out in an appropriate manner and at the
proper time," said Zhou.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0208 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Securities Market Witnesses Sound Development (3) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
However, the process of listing large SOEs requires full
consideration of the capacity and endurance of the market, and
stress will be placed on strict examinations of the quality of
listed companies, according to Zhou.
</P>
<P>
He sternly rebuked the belief that "market development is more
important than market standardization," and called the belief
"totally incorrect."
</P>
<P>
Zhou pointed out that the stock market in the United States
gradually embarked on a road of stable development after
strengthening market regulation in the wake of market slumps in
1929.
</P>
<P>
The steady growth of China's stock markets will require the
firm implementation of the principles stressing legislation,
supervision, self-discipline, and standardization.
</P>
<P>
"The blind pursuit of market expansion while neglecting
standardization will encourage excessive speculation and hinder
healthy market development," according to Zhou.
</P>
<P>
He disclosed that China will focus future work on the following
five major aspects:
</P>
<P>
Firstly, deepening reform of the securities supervision system
with a goal towards establishing unified and highly-efficient
securities supervision mechanisms. As part of the effort,
functions related to supervising securities firms will be
transferred from the People's Bank of China, the nation's central
bank, to the CSRC, and central and local government supervising
powers over securities will be centralized.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0209 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Securities Market Witnesses Sound Development (4) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Secondly, tightening supervision and further rectifying and
standardizing market order.
</P>
<P>
Thirdly, exerting every possible effort to improve the quality
of listed companies, including strengthening examination and
approval procedures, optimizing structures and strengthening
regulation.
</P>
<P>
Fourthly, accelerating market legislation efforts,
including formulation of the "Securities Law."
</P>
<P>
Finally, actively experimenting with the establishment of a
securities investment fund.
</P>
<P>
Zhou announced that the first round of securities investment
funds will be issued to the public in the near future.
</P>
<P>
He pointed out 101 listed companies were issuing B shares to
overseas investors by the end of February, with the total amount
of capital raised from related issues reaching 4.5 billion US
dollars. Zhou also pointed the that the B share market is expected
to witness further development.
</P>
<P>
In addition, 42 inland Chinese companies had raised a total of
9.7 billion US dollars on overseas stock markets by the end of
last month, including 40 companies listing H shares in Hong Kong.
</P>
<P>
Recent years have also witnessed the rapid growth of red chip
stocks issued by companies registered in Hong Kong with inland
backing. For example China Telecom (HK), a major red chip company,
raised 4.2 billion US dollars and became the fourth largest listed
firm on the Hong Kong Market.
</P>
<P>
Last June, the State Council issued a circular designed to
standardize the activities of inland investors holding red chip
stocks and curb the rush for related listings.
</P>
<P>
"The CSRC will continue to encourage the standardized
development of red chip companies in accordance with the
circular", said Zhou. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0210 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
