<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0211 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Philippine Non-Bank Financial Bodies Outnumber Banks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Non-bank financial institutions
have outnumbered banks as they account for 58.6 percent of the
total operating network in the country, the Central Bank of the
Philippines said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In its 1997 third quarter report to President Fidel Ramos, the
central bank noted that during the quarter, the number of
financial institutions totaled 16,316 as of the end of September
1997.
</P>
<P>
Of this number, the non-bank institutions, comprising lending
investors and pawnshops, totaled 9,569 units.
</P>
<P>
During the period, banks grew from 6,569 in March 1997 to 6,747
in September 1997, compared with only 6,045 on September 19, 1996,
the report said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank said the increase in the number of banks
improved the population-to-banks ratio from 11,442 at the end of
1996 to 10,925 as of June 1997.
</P>
<P>
More efficient financial intermediation carried out by banks
and non-banks contributed to the improvement in the ratio of
domestic liquidity which rose to 39.7 percent as of the third
quarter of 1997 from 38.2 percent in the last quarter of 1996, it
said.
</P>
<P>
The central bank also expressed optimism that the assets of
commercial banks remained adequate to cover risk assets, saying
the risk asset ratio of these banks at 16.5 percent as of the
third quarter was higher than the 10 percent statutory
requirement.
</P>
<P>
Likewise, the central bank proposed to the Monetary Board to
strengthen banking regulations as concerns of a financial crisis
like that in Thailand could prevail in the Philippine market.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0212 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> NZ Stocks Finishes Higher </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Wellington, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The New Zealand sharemarket
continued to gain on Thursday, led by Telecom shares.
</P>
<P>
The NZSE40 Index ended 20 points higher at 2269 with a turnover
of over 78 million dollars (45 million U.S. dollars).
</P>
<P>
Among the main leaders, Air New Zealand remained unchanged at
200 cents. Fletcher Energy dropped 7 cents to 610 cents.
</P>
<P>
Other main leaders all finished firmer. Brierley Investment and
Carter Holt Harvey was up 1 cent each to 110 cents and 258 cents
respectively. Fletcher Forest gained 3 cents to 127 cents. Lion
Nathan picked up 2 cents to 432 cents. Telecom jumped 20 cents to
830 cents and accounted for 40 percent of the market turnover.
</P>
<P>
Overall, there were 52 rises and 44 falls.  
</P>
</TEXT>
