<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> ASEAN Members Enhance Cooperation in Cement Industry </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Representatives from six ASEAN
members met here Thursday to seek ways of promoting cooperation in
the cement field.
</P>
<P>
At a three-day symposium, the representatives reached an
agreement that gives priority to member countries to purchase
cement from fellow members that have excess production capacity.
</P>
<P>
A regional surplus of 35 million tons of cement is forecast
this year as the recession will cut demand by about 10 percent
from last year's level of 112 million tons, according to the
participants.
</P>
<P>
The symposium was organized by the ASEAN Federation of Cement
Manufacturers which groups Thailand, Indonesia, Malaysia, the
Philippines, Singapore and Vietnam.
</P>
<P>
Federation President Tawee Butsunton said total production
capacity of the six countries this year would be about 163 million
tons while demand is projected at 100 million tons.
</P>
<P>
"Evidently, total production capacity in 1998 will exceed
demand and therefore cement manufacturers in Thailand, Indonesia,
Malaysia and the Philippines are looking for export markets," he
said.
</P>
<P>
This year Thailand will need to offload 8 million to 10 million
tons of cement in export markets while Indonesia is expected to
export 4.5 million tons and the Philippines 5.2 million tons, said
Tawee, who is also executive vice-president of Thailand's Siam
Cement plc.
</P>
<P>
Federation members that need to import cement and clinker are
Vietnam, Singapore and Malaysia.
</P>
<P>
Thailand's cement consumption last year, hit by the economic
downturn, dropped by 4 percent from the previous year to 36
million tons. There were no clinker or cement imports due to the
domestic oversupply.
</P>
<P>
The country exported 1.2 million tons of cement and 4.3 million
tons of clinker last year.
</P>
<P>
Tawee said that due to the slump in the construction industry,
the country's cement demand is expected to be 26.6 million tons,
26 percent lower than in 1997. Production capacity has been
forecast at 50 million tons.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
