<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0215 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Zimbabwe's Army Retrenchment Program Continues </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Zimbabwe National Army (ZNA)
is still reducing its size in an internal army exercise
complementing the wider retrenchment program that has already
seen the army reduced from 51,000 to 35,000 soldiers.
</P>
<P>
The Herald daily reported Thursday that the reduction is meant
to cut the army's annual budget while the retrenchment exercise
seeks to streamline general government expenditure in line with
economic demands.
</P>
<P>
Job Whabira, Zimbabwean Secretary for Defense, told the paper
Wednesday that the down-sizing was dictated by needs that arose
in the army particularly during peace time. But the army still
had to recruit soldiers to replace those who retired or died.
</P>
<P>
"Forty thousand soldiers is the army establishment that we
could maintain if we had the money. But because of economic
constraints we had to make our own internal arrangements to
down-size the army and create some savings," the secretary said,
adding that "The savings are very nominal but good enough."
</P>
<P>
The army streamlined its forces to focus more on training and
upgrading of equipment, he noted.
</P>
<P>
Most of the equipment including vehicles were inherited from
the Rhodesian army and was "dilapidated," said Whabira, who
confirmed the purchase of new equipment but would not disclose
it.
</P>
<P>
"Wait, we will display the equipment on Defense Forces Day,"
he said.
</P>
<P>
The Secretary for Defense dismissed as untrue reports that the
army was facing serious food shortages at some barracks which had
forced the ZNA to send soldiers home occasionally. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
