<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0800 GMT, March 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- Visiting Russian Prime Minister Viktor
Chernomyrdin said Wednesday that U.S. President Bill Clinton
and Russian President Boris Yeltsin may hold a summit by the
middle of this year.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that this meeting will take place and... this
should set forth the trend of our bilateral relationship,"
Chernomyrdin said at a joint news conference with U.S. Vice
President Al Gore at the White House.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that this summit will occur this year, not later but
in the middle of the year," said Chernomyrdin. But the exact
date and venue have not been fixed. (US-Russia-Chernomyrdin)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BEIJING -- China is concerned with the bloodshed in Kosovo,
Qian Qichen said here Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Qian made the remark in response to a question at a press
conference hosted by the ongoing session of the Ninth National
People's Congress, the Chinese legislature, here Thursday
morning. It is an internal matter of Yugoslavia, he added.
(China-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
ROME -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto Dini Wednesday urged
ethnic Albanians in Yugoslavia's province of Kosovo to end
violence and enter into dialogue with Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Dini said that the Kosovo Albanians and Belgrade, the two sides
involved in the conflict, must immediately stop violence, in which
about 80 people have been killed.
</P>
<P>
The Albanians in Kosovo "must choose the way of dialogue" to
attain the degree of autonomy, he said. (Italy-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
TIRANA -- The European Union (EU) and Macedonia agreed
Wednesday that the Kosovo issue must be settled politically
through negotiations between Belgrade and ethnic Albanians.
</P>
<P>
EU special envoy Tony Lloyd, who paid a brief visit to Skoplje
Wednesday, and Macedonian Foreign Minister Blagoj Handziski also
agreed that a solution to the Kosovo issue should be found without
altering the borders of the Federal Republic of Yugoslavia.
(Macedonia-EU-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BELGRADE -- The Yugoslavian government has rejected
international pressure over its handling of the Kosovo conflict,
describing it as "interference" in its internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
A government statement issued Wednesday said tough action
against terrorism was the legitimate right and duty of a sovereign
state.
</P>
<P>
The government was responding to the emergency meeting on
Monday of the Contact Group on Former Yugoslavia which proposed
sanctions against Belgrade over the conflict between Serbian
police and ethnic Albanians over the past two
weeks.(Yugoslavia-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
STOCKHOLM -- Boosted by a strong economy and low unemployment,
Denmark's center-left ruling coalition won the parliamentary
election Wednesday, with one seat more than the opposition
center-right bloc, official figures show.
</P>
<P>
With 99.5 percent of the votes counted, the ruling coalition of
social democrats, radicals and their political allies were
credited with a slim majority of 90 seats in the 179-seat
parliament. (Denmark-Election) 
</P>
