<HEADLINE> Malaysia to Help Indonesia in Firefighting </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KUALA LUMPUR, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Malaysia said Thursday that
it is ready to send firefighters to Indonesia to help put out the
forest fires in Kalimantan before the situation worsens and last
year's haze problem recurs.
</P>
<P>
Under a Memorandum of Understanding on Natural Disaster Aid
between the two countries, Malaysia is required to send its
firefighters to Indonesia at anytime at the request of Indonesia,
Information Minister Mohamed Rahmat said.
</P>
<P>
Mohamed, who is also chairman of the National Disaster and
Relief Management Committee, said: "It appears that the small area
which caught fire in Indonesia has spread and we want to take
measures early and cooperate in putting out the fire so that last
year's problems will not recur."
</P>
<P>
Last year, Malaysia was seriously affected by the haze caused
by forest fires in neighboring Indonesia.
</P>
<P>
Malaysia would propose to Indonesia that the first meeting of
the Malaysia-Indonesia Joint Committee be held in Jakarta, Mohamed
said, adding that the date for the meeting would only be decided
after Indonesian President Soeharto, who had been re-elected for a
seventh term, forms his new cabinet.
</P>
</TEXT>
