<HEADLINE> Japan to Fund Reforestation Project in Philippines </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Japan will fund 31 million pesos
(775,000 U.S. dollars) for a five-year reforestation project on a
2,176-hectare area in the Philippines' Clark Special Economic
Zone.
</P>
<P>
The Overseas Economic Cooperation Fund of Japan has approved
the funding, the Philippine News Agency Thursday quoted Romeo
David, president of the Clark Development Corporation, as saying.
</P>
<P>
David said the reforestation project is a joint effort of his
corporation and the Department of Environment and Natural
Resources to combat the possibility of inadequate water supply in
the future in the 4,400-hectare main Clark area.
</P>
<P>
The two parties recently signed a memorandum of understanding
to undertake long-term integrated environmental solutions, among
which is the establishment of a water shed and a reforestation
area in the Clark sub-zone.
</P>
<P>
The Clark watershed project was designed to rehabilitate the
areas' capacity for hydrological balance by planting some 2.5
million hardwood and fruit-bearing trees with the involvement of
local residents.
</P>
<P>
The watershed project in its full blown stage will help in
preventing soil erosion and excessive flooding and revitalizing
the holding capacity of underground water, David explained.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
