<HEADLINE> WB to Invest in Zimbabwe's Private Sector </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HARARE, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The International Finance
Corporation (IFC), the private sector arm of the World Bank, will
invest about 800 million Zimbabwean Dollars (47 million U.S.
Dollars) in eight private sector projects in Zimbabwe this year.
</P>
<P>
The Business weekly reported Thursday that most of the
projects are in the agro-processing and manufacturing sectors.
</P>
<P>
The organization is also working on investments in the
financial and health sectors, said Philip Condon, IFC deputy
regional representative for southern Africa, in an interview with
the Business Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
This year's figure brings IFC's total investment portfolio for
the past 15 years to about 2.4 billion Zimbabwean Dollars (141
million U.S. Dollars). Investment has been made in the
manufacturing, horticulture and pharmaceutical sectors, among
others, he said.
</P>
<P>
Condon said IFC's financial commitment to Zimbabwe represented
about 11 percent of the total sub-Saharan investment.
</P>
<P>
IFC offered financial assistance through loan disbursements
and equity investments in some cases. The assistance was given
only to private sector projects that were financially viable and
export-oriented.
</P>
<P>
Condon was optimistic that in the next fiscal year more
resources would be allocated to Zimbabwe.
</P>
<P>
However, he added, "The current situation makes it difficult
for us to plan ahead because we are not sure of what the future
holds." 
</P>
</TEXT>
