<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0226 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Evidence Found at Site of Nanjing Massacre </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NANJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- An antitank grenade, a bayonet, a
military knife and 300 rounds of ammunition believed used by
Japanese troops during the Nanjing Massacre were unearthed in
mid-February at a building site near the Zhongshan Wharf of
Nanjing City in east China's Jiangsu Province.
</P>
<P>
At the same time, helmets, bronze collar-badges, enamel bowls
and some other daily goods used by Chinese soldiers more than 60
years ago have also been found.
</P>
<P>
Experts here believe that the newly discovered articles
coincide with historical records of the Nanjing Massacre.
</P>
<P>
Starting from Dec. 13, 1937, the Japanese invaders began a
six-week massacre of 300,000 civilians and disarmed Chinese
soldiers.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that during the massacre Japanese troops killed
more than 9,000 Chinese citizens at the Zhongshan Wharf along the
Yangtze River with machine guns and threw the dead bodies into the
river on Dec. 16 and 18 of 1937.
</P>
<P>
Photos of massacre scenes at the wharf taken by a photographer
for the Japanese troops also document the slaughter.
</P>
<P>
Liu Yongxing, 85 years old and a survivor of the Nanjing
Massacre, said that 60 years ago his younger brother was killed by
Japanese soldiers and that he had a narrow escape by jumping into
the river. He said the newly discovered Japanese bayonet and
ammunition are strong evidence of the Nanjing Massacre.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0227 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
