<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Vietnam Predicts Slower Export Growth in First Quarter </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
HANOI, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Vietnam's export growth in the
first quarter is projected at 14 percent, well below last year's
20 percent growth during the same period, the ministry of trade
was quoted as saying Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The average monthly exports in the first quarter amounted to
745 million U.S. dollars, well short of the state target of 910
million dollars to gross a targeted 11 billion dollars exports for
the whole year of 1998, reported "Vietnam News" by quoting trade
officials as saying.
</P>
<P>
The ministry attributed the export slump mainly to fierce price
competition among main export commodities including rice, rubber,
textiles, garments, footwear and marine products.
</P>
<P>
The ministry predicted sharp drop in rubber and coffee exports
during the first quarter, with rubber exports reaching 36,000
tons, a 24 percent year-on-year drop, and coffee exports reaching
110,000 tons, a 37.3 percent drop over the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil and cashew nuts have also posted drops in export
value against 1997 figure. Although the volume of pumped oil
increased by 18.6 percent in the first two months, export value
fell by 80 million dollars against the same period last year.
</P>
<P>
Crude oil prices dropped by 50 dollars per ton while cashew nut
prices fell by 60 to 70 dollars per ton.
</P>
<P>
The officials said that the regional financial crisis has
affected Vietnam's exports. Its exports to regional countries
account for 25 to 30 percent of its total export value. 
</P>
</TEXT>
