<HEADLINE> NPC Deputies Hail Progress in Law-making, Supervision </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Deputies to the First Session of
the Ninth National People's Congress (NPC), now well under way
here, said China has scored remarkable progress in legislation,
law-enforcement and supervision, but there still exist some
problems.
</P>
<P>
Amudun Niyaz, a deputy from the Xinjiang Uygur Autonomous
Region, said that building of a socialist country ruled by law is
a major strategy set by the 15th National Congress of the
Communist Party of China, and that long-term, arduous efforts are
required to achieve the goal.
</P>
<P>
However, he acknowledged that the pressing problems for the
time being remain the failure to abide by the law, and put an end
to laxity law-enforcement and weak supervision.
</P>
<P>
To speed up the pace for legislation, more new laws should be
enacted and some exiting laws have to be revised so as to further
improve the legal system and a mechanism should be established to
standardize supervision procedures and strengthen supervision
effectiveness, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, deputy Dai Mingzi said that the Eighth NPC enacted
the largest number of laws during the past five years as compared
with any previous period. The NPC has also scored the greatest
progress in its self-development during this five-year period.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, over the past five years, the role of the supreme
organ of state power have been brought into still better play, and
the public have become increasingly aware of the irreplaceable
role of such functions, he said.
</P>
<P>
NPC deputy Wang Tong proposed that the pace for the making of
laws concerning reform and economic development should be
accelerated, but underlined the laws' publicization and
implementation, which are more important.  
</P>
</TEXT>
