<HEADLINE> World Bank Helps Philippines Strengthen Safety Nets </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The World Bank is helping the
Philippines strengthen its social safety nets to mitigate the
adverse effects of the present currency crisis, particularly on
employment, the Philippine News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
"Strengthening the social safety nets would need a priority
now. We have social assessment to determine the immediate needs,"
the report quoted Khalilzadeh Shirazi, World Bank regional manager
for strategy and partnerships of East Asia and the Pacific, as
saying.
</P>
<P>
Shirazi said the Philippines may be less affected by the Asian
crisis but the magnitude of the crisis and the sharp drop in
growth rates of many countries made it necessary to have these
measures.
</P>
<P>
"It (the Philippines) is doing very well in coping with the
crisis. What will eventually happen depends on the regional
environment so everything is not within control of the
Philippines," he said.
</P>
<P>
The World Bank is currently working with the Philippines,
Thailand and Indonesia for this undertaking to help them cope with
the social impact of the crisis, he said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Vinay Bhargava, World Bank country director for the
Philippines, said the bank is readying its 90-million-U.S.-dollar
assistance aimed at increasing incomes of the poor and providing
basic services.
</P>
<P>
This is part of a 1-billion-dollar special loan package the
bank committed for the Philippines last month, he said.
</P>
<P>
He said it is necessary to help troubled economies due to the
worsening impact of the crisis on employment, inflation and
budget.
</P>
<P>
"It was agreed that 1998 (employment) trend in the Philippines
may be the worst. Expect some rise in the unemployment in the near
future because the growth rate will slow down by about half," he
added.
</P>
<P>
Philippine Socioeconomic Planning Secretary Cielito Habito said
that as of last month, the Philippine Department of Labor and
Employment had received 431 notices of layoffs affecting more than
19,000 workers.
</P>
<P>
The actual number may more than double considering unregistered
cases. The jobs of thousands of Filipino workers in countries like
Malaysia and South Korea are "likewise imperiled," he said.
</P>
<P>
Habito added that the crisis has also severely affected
services, education, housing programs and social welfare services.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
