<HEADLINE> Guangzhou Develops Rural Economy </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The rural economy in south
China's Guangdong Province, including the grain, aquatic products
and township enterprise sectors, developed steadily in 1997.
</P>
<P>
Statistics for 1997 show that Guangzhou's rural economy
recorded income of 108 billion yuan, up 2.1-fold on the previous
year. The total agricultural output rose by six percent to 15.5
billion yuan, with the average annual income of farmers growing by
nine percent to 5,630 yuan.
</P>
<P>
The city government's efforts to develop advanced agriculture
and large water conservancy projects continued to enrich local
consumer choices in terms of vegetables and rice.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou has nine agricultural experimental zones, including
three zones opened in 1996. The city has also introduced advanced
foreign agricultural equipment.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou has allocated over 2.6 billion yuan for the
construction of water conservancy facilities over three years,
with the figure surpassing the accumulated total for the previous
40 year period.
</P>
<P>
An additional 70,000 hectares were placed under irrigation
during 1997, with related efforts significantly increasing
agricultural harvests. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
