<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0236 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Rare Bird Found in Jiangxi Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- A rare bird only known through
photographs has been spotted in Wuyuan County in east China's
Jiangxi Province.
</P>
<P>
The "garrulax galbanus," slightly larger than the babbler,
lives only in the evergreen broad-leaf forests in Lianxi and
Meilin villages in Wuyuan County. There used to its records in
southwest China's Yunnan Province and neighboring Burma.
</P>
<P>
Experts with the National Environmental Protection Agency said
that the garrulax galbanus is one of the rare birds with the
narrowest distribution in the world.
</P>
<P>
"Its specimen was unavailable in the past so that there is
still no systematic knowledge of the bird's habits and
characteristics," said an expert.
</P>
<P>
The birds discovered this time were in four groups with the
total number estimated at 30. The investigating group that spotted
the garrulax galbanus recorded the birds' chirping, which
reportedly is unique and beautiful.
</P>
<P>
The group discovered the birds during an investigation in the
Wuyuan County Nature Reserve. It is now conducting further studies
to gain a better knowledge of the number, distribution and habits
of the bird in the reserve.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
