<HEADLINE> Farmers' Income Increases in China's Populous Province </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHENGDU, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Farmers' per-capita income in
southwest China's Sichuan Province reached a record 1,595
yuan in real terms in 1997, up 9.3 percent on 1996.
</P>
<P>
A recent sample survey shows that 23.4 percent of the rural
households in the province received 2,240 yuan per capita, the
national standard for a relatively comfortable life.
</P>
<P>
The farmers earned 1,081 yuan from industry, 276 yuan from
agriculture, and 223 yuan from the service sector.
</P>
<P>
Economists attribute the increase mainly to the strict control
over prices, with the price index of farmers' living expenses
below 6 percent while that of the means of production less than
one percent.
</P>
<P>
In addition, the province intensified its efforts to help poor
farmers in northern and western Sichuan, and has considerably
narrowed the income gap. 
</P>
</TEXT>
