<HEADLINE> Semiconductor Capital Spending to Drop Worldwide </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LOS ANGELES, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Semiconductor capital
spending will drop by 12-14 percent worldwide in 1998 compared
with that of last year, according to a report from an American
investment analyst company.
</P>
<P>
The drop is attributed to steeper-than-expected cuts in Japan,
Morgan Stanley &AMP; Co. said in a newly revised forecast before its
Semiconductor Equipment Conference in California.
</P>
<P>
The company had previously predicted a 7 to 10 percent decline
in spending on semiconductor production systems.
</P>
<P>
Reduced capital spending budgets by Japanese chip makers was
blamed for the downgraded outlook. The report said that the
spending in Japan will decline by 14 percent from that of last
year, based on yen value.
</P>
<P>
The company also believed that Motorola will cut its capital
investment in semiconductor from its originally estimated 2.5
billion U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Other North American-based chip makers will likely trim this
year's capital spending plans, the report added.
</P>
<P>
"Nonetheless, we expect North American capital spending to
still be up 10 percent, although this could slip to a mid-single
digit increase," the report said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
