<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Bangladesh to Publish Updated Code of Laws </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
DHAKA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Bangladesh will soon have an
updated code of laws to meet the needs of courts, lawyers and
others concerned, the national news agency BSS reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
A bill to this effect would be introduced to the current
session of the Jatiya Sangsad (parliament) for the passage of the
Bangladesh Code, the news agency quoted sources at the Ministry of
Law, Justice and Parliamentary Affairs as saying Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
A draft bill in this regard has been prepared to be submitted
to the next cabinet meeting for approval.
</P>
<P>
The Bangladesh Code is designed to present in handy volumes the
amended, adapted and authentic versions of all enacted laws in
force in the country, to ascertain the current status of the
existing laws which have undergone extensive changes and to keep
track of the flow of new laws being enacted.
</P>
<P>
The task of preparing the Bangladesh Code was initiated soon
after the country gained independence in 1971 and a cell was
formed in 1972.
</P>
<P>
The cell examined a total of 373 laws inherited from the past
dating from 1836 to 1947. Of the laws, 93 were repealed, 17
declared non-Bangladesh and the remaining 263 proposed for
amendments.
</P>
<P>
A program was undertaken to publish the Bangladesh Code in 12
volumes in the early years of independence, but only one volume
was awaiting publication, leaving the country without a complete
code of laws for over two decades.
</P>
<P>
The present government revived the program and a three-member
committee has been formed to make recommendations in this regard.
</P>
<P>
The committee has submitted its recommendations to the
government after examining the country's laws in the period from
1948 to 1957 in the first phase, and in the second phase, it will
examine the laws from 1957 to 1971, the news agency said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0249 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Houses to be Ready for Quake Victims By September </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHIJIAZHUANG, March 12 (Xinhua) -- All the homeless quake
victims in Zhangjiakou Prefecture in northern Hebei Province
should be able to move into new houses by the end of September,
local officials told Xinhua recently.
</P>
<P>
By then, the 44,000 collapsed houses should be rebuilt and
nearly 70,000 damaged houses repaired, they said.
</P>
<P>
On Jan. 10, Zhangbei and Shangyi counties in the prefecture
were devastated by an earthquake measuring 6.2 on the Richter
scale, which left 47 dead and more than 1,000 seriously injured.
</P>
<P>
Local people have been braving sub-zero temperatures to survive
and rebuild their homes with financial and physical assistance
from the government, the army, and people from other parts of the
country and the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
Nobody has died or been injured from the cold weather in the
area which is on the brink of the Mongolian Plateau.
</P>
<P>
Currently, local governments of all levels have worked out
preferential policies in building houses and supplying materials.
Local architects involved in designing the new houses for the
victims said that they would bring earthquake safety and frigid
temperatures into consideration. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
