<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0252 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China's Poverty Alleviation Goal Attainable: Official </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- A senior Chinese official in
charge of poverty alleviation today expressed his confidence that
China can accomplish its goal of basically eliminating poverty by
the end of this century.
</P>
<P>
Yang Yongzhe, deputy chief of the State council's leading group
for eradicating poverty, said his confidence is backed up by
concerted efforts of the central and local governments in recent
years and the increased state funding for this end.
</P>
<P>
China helped lift seven million needy people out of poverty in
1996 and another eight million in 1997. It has also earmarked an
additional 3 billion yuan (361 million US dollars) in loans and
1.5 billion yuan from (181 million US dollars) from the central
budget to support the poverty relieving endeavor since 1996.
</P>
<P>
In his government report to the ongoing First Session of the
Ninth NPC, Premier Li Peng announced that his country will help
another 10 million needy rural people to have adequate food and
clothing this year.
</P>
<P>
"If we can eliminate poverty for the remaining 20 million
people in next two years before the end of this century, the
projected objective for China's poverty alleviation will be
accomplished," said Yang, also a deputy to the NPC session.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, the task is becoming increasingly tougher as
the majority of existing poor people are inhabited in most remote,
outlying mountainous areas, with arid land and little access to
the outside world due to backward transport conditions.
</P>
<P>
He went on to say that the central government encourages
relatively affluent provinces and cities to choose one or two
backward and less-developed areas as their cooperative partners to
lead these areas out of poverty.
</P>
<P>
"This has proved to be one of the most effective ways to help
the needy in the impoverished regions," Yang said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
