<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0253 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Stones With Ancient Paintings Discovered </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
XI'AN, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese archeologists have
discovered more than 60 stones with colored paintings dating back
to the Han Dynasty (206 B.C. to 220 A.D.) in 13 tombs found in
Shenmu County of northwest China's Shaanxi Province.
</P>
<P>
Archeologists said this is the first time since the beginning
of this century that so many sandstones with colored paintings of
the Han Dynasty period have been unearthed in the province.
</P>
<P>
The stones were placed at the gates of the tombs and used as
symbols of gate-keeping.
</P>
<P>
The paintings on the stones include portraits of the Spring God
and Autumn God as well as tales of Jing Ke's attempt to kill Qin
Shihuang, the first emperor of the Qin Dynasty (221 to 207 B.C),
and other stories.
</P>
<P>
The painting of the Spring God is 1.03 meters high and 0.27
meters wide. The god has a human face and a bird's body, with a
three-feather hat. He is wearing a red coat and feather-skirt,
holding a red sun in his left hand and a square in his right
hand. A green dragon is under his feet and another dragon is
behind him.
</P>
<P>
The pictures were painted in pink, red, white, brown, green and
purple. Even the hair, beard and strings of ancient musical
instruments were painted clearly.
</P>
<P>
Experts here believe that the discovery of the stone paintings
is of great importance to research into the ancient arts, fairy
tales, music, dance and dress in China. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
