<HEADLINE> 650 Million People Expected to Travel in 2000 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Total international tourist
arrivals of about 650 million are forecast for the year 2000 with
global tourism receipts keeping on rising year by year, the
Philippine News Agency reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The report quoted Philippine Tourism Secretary Mina Gabor, who
cited figures released by the World Tourism Organization, as
saying the total revenue from tourism will reach more than 500
billion U.S. dollars yearly by the end of the century.
</P>
<P>
Gabor said tourism has become a major industry in most
countries of the world and "third in importance after oil and
motor vehicles" in international trade.
</P>
<P>
Tourism receipts are greater than the world's exports of
selected products such as electronics, clothing, textiles and raw
materials, Gabor said.
</P>
<P>
The most successful tourist-receiving regions by far are East
Asia and the Pacific which have achieved successes in the past
four decades, she added.
</P>
<P>
She said the World Tourism Organization forecasts have revealed
that leisure tourism would grow faster than other travel
activities in East Asia and the Pacific and South Asia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
