<HEADLINE> Pakistan's Exports Up by 16.7 Percent in February </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ISLAMABAD, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Pakistan's exports increased by
16.7 percent to 705 million U.S. dollars in February from 604
million dollars in January.
</P>
<P>
According to provisional figures released Wednesday by the
Federal Bureau of Statistics, Pakistan's exports during July, 1997
to February, 1998 totaled 5.651 billion dollars as compared to
5.344 billion dollars during the corresponding period of last
year, showing an increase of 5.7 percent.
</P>
<P>
Imports of the country during the month of February amounted to
792 million dollars as against 789 million dollars in January,
indicating an increase of 0.4 percent.
</P>
<P>
During July, 1997 to February, 1998, imports totaled 7.053
billion dollars as against 7.665 billion dollars in the
corresponding period of last year, showing a decrease of 7.98
percent.
</P>
<P>
The import and export figures during July, 1997 to February,
1998 showed that trade deficit stood at 1.402 billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Pakistan's main items of exports in February were cotton
fabrics, cotton yarn, rice, synthetic textile fabrics, garments,
sports goods and leather products, while imported items included
petroleum products, palm oil, wheat, power generating machine,
tea, iron and steel. 
</P>
</TEXT>
