<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Beijing Refueling Automobiles With Liquefied Petroleum Gas </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The first filling station using
liquefied petroleum gas has gone into operation in China's capital.
</P>
<P>
The station, located in Beijing's Chaoyang District, can
provide fuel for 200 automobiles with a 50-liter gas bottle daily.
</P>
<P>
Tests on 10 retrofitted automobiles shows that, by using
liquefied petroleum gas, the engine produces less noise, emissions
are reduced and all the functions of the automobiles remain the
same as when they use other kinds of fuel. However, the charge for
the fuel is 30 percent less.
</P>
<P>
Beijing now has more than 1.2 million motor vehicles using
gasoline and diesel oil, one of the city's major sources of air
pollution.
</P>
<P>
Experts said that to retrofit a vehicle with liquefied
petroleum gas, it is necessary to change the vehicle's engine
system and to test engine functions and emissions. Only those
passing related tests are allowed to run on the streets.
</P>
<P>
According to Beijing's Municipal Environmental Bureau, the city
will first retrofit some taxis and buses to expand the use of
liquefied petroleum gas.
</P>
<P>
Shanghai and Xiamen in east China are conducting similar tests
to replace gasoline and diesel fuel with liquefied petroleum gas.
</P>
<P>
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
