<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Sino-U.S. Scientists Cooperate on New Therapy for Cancer </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SHANGHAI, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese and American scientists
have decided to join efforts in using "white arsenic," a
traditional Chinese poison that provokes maturity and death of
differentiated cancer cells.
</P>
<P>
A Sino-U.S. cancer differentiation therapy research center was
joinly established in Shanghai Wednesday by Ruijin Hospital
attached to Shanghai Second Medical University, the Shanghai
Institute of Hematology, Reliance Group Holdings, Inc. and Samuel
Waxman Cancer Research Fund from the United States.
</P>
<P>
This is believed to be the world's first research center on
differentiation therapy.
</P>
<P>
Wang Zhenyi, honorary president of the Shanghai Institute of
Hematology and an academician of the Chinese Academy of
Engineering, said the new method is to differentiate cancer cells
and provoke their early maturity and death with arsenic trioxide,
a material used in many murder cases in ancient China.
</P>
<P>
He said no serious side-effects are caused by this therapy
while the commonly used chemo-therapy kills cancer cells together
with healthy cells and hinders normal blood formation.
</P>
<P>
The new cancer therapy will be based on China's achievements in
the clinical use of arsenic trioxide to treat acute promyelocytic
leukemia.
</P>
<P>
Chen Zhu, a hematology expert and academician of the Chinese
Academy of Sciences, believes the establishment of the research
center will encourage the application of differentiation therapy
in the treatment of liver and stomach cancers and other types of
leukemia.
</P>
<P>
According to an agreement reached among the four parties, the
U.S. Reliance company is to offer 600,000 U.S. dollars in five
years for the center's research program.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0267 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Forest Belt in Reservoir Area of China's Three Gorges Project </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
CHONGQING, March 10 (Xinhua) -- China will spend 6.6 billion
yuan on a large forest belt in the reservoir area of the Three
Gorges project.
</P>
<P>
The new forest belt will have an area exceeding 2 million
hectares and will cover 145 counties in the provinces of Hubei and
Sichuan and Chongqing Municipality.
</P>
<P>
The Three Gorges project, which is now under construction at
Sandouping of Yichang City, Hubei Province, on the middle reaches
of the Yangtze River, is the world's biggest water-control
project.
</P>
<P>
Construction of the project started in 1993 and will require
the relocation of 1.2 million residents. The entire project will
take 17 years. When the project is completed a gigantic dam will
be erected and a reservoir with a length of 600 kilometers will be
formed upstream.
</P>
<P>
The Chinese government has attached great importance to the
environment in the reservoir area and has financed the planting of
a forest-protection belt along the upper reaches of the Yangtze
River.
</P>
<P>
The newly planned forest project is expected to be able to
increase the forest cover of the reservoir area from the present
27 percent to 46 percent upon completion. The new forest project
will also play an important role in curbing soil erosion in the
reservoir area, improving the quality of the water in the Yangtze
and guaranteeing safe operation of the hydropower generators at
the Three Gorges Dam.
</P>
<P>
The new forest project, which has already been implemented in
Chongqing, will be finished in 2010, just one year after the
completion of the Three Gorges Dam in 2009. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0268 </DOCNO>
