leading publishing house in Britain, to those enterprises,
organizations, and individuals who have made significant
achievements in developing world aerospace and aviation technology
and management.
</P>
<P>
"One hundred and seventy entries for this year's awards, the
fifth of its kind, came from more countries than ever before,
reflecting the global nature of both the industry and its awards
program. Those which have won are truly the best of the best,"
said Allan Winn, editor-in-chief of Flight International.
</P>
<P>
In early 1997, AMECO finished repainting three Boeing-747-100s
from Northwest Airlines of the United States. Afterwards, the
corporation repainted aircraft for New Zealand, Vietnam and
Australia.
</P>
<P>
The real breakthrough came in August when AMECO completed a
D-check and strut modification for a B747-200 freighter for
Lufthansa of Germany. For AMECO, the job represents a first
venture into the European aircraft heavy maintenance market, as
the D-check is the highest level for aircraft maintenance and this
time the check fell on a B747 airliner, one of the most advanced
aircraft in the world.
</P>
<P>
Actually, the first success had already brought further
contracts. At the end of last year, Lufthansa sent another
B747-200 freighter for a C-check.
</P>
<P>
Air China and the German air carrier jointly set up Aircraft
Maintenance and Engineering Corp., Beijing, in May of 1989, making
it the largest joint venture in the history of China's civil
aviation. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
