<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0271 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Kenya's Economic Growth at 2.9 Percent in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NAIROBI, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Kenya's economic growth was
registered at 2.9 percent last year, down from the 4.6 percent in
1996, according to the latest issue of the monthly economic
review issued by the Central Bank of Kenya.
</P>
<P>
The bank said last year's growth figure for gross domestic
product (GDP) was the lowest since 1993 when economic growth
recorded 0.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
The central bank predicted that the GDP growth is expected to
rebound to about 4.6 percent in the second half of 1998.
</P>
<P>
"The increase in growth in 1998 is expected to stem from the
continued sustenance of the favorable prices of the principal
agricultural exports," the bank report noted.
</P>
<P>
The bank attributed the slow-down in economic growth last year
to the significant decline in agriculture, manufacturing, trade
and tourism.
</P>
<P>
A general loss of investors' confidence in 1997 also
contributed to the depressed level of investment in almost all
sectors of the economy, it added.
</P>
<P>
The bank pointed out that the drought suffered in the first
half of last year and heavy rains caused by the El Nino
phenomenon late in 1997 in the predominantly agricultural areas
also adversely affected economic growth. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
