<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Launch Fourth Weather Satellite (1) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- China plans to launch a
replacement Fengyun 1 synchronous solar orbit meteorological
satellite next October, an official with the National
Meteorological Satellite Center (NMSC) said today.
</P>
<P>
All countries and regions in the world will have free access to
the new weather satellite's data, the official said.
</P>
<P>
The satellite will be the fourth weather satellite launched by
China.
</P>
<P>
China launched its first and second weather satellites in 1988
and 1990 respectively. However, the two satellites, both of the
Fengyun 1 series, have stopped functioning.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, the country launched a Fengyun 2 weather satellite,
which was formally put into use in January this year and is
reportedly operating well.
</P>
<P>
Experts explain that the Fengyun 1 series weather satellites
are all synchronous solar orbit satellites, while the Fengyun 2
series satellites are in synchronous orbit with the earth.
</P>
<P>
"China holds that weather satellites should not be commercial;
they should serve the world free of charge, because the change of
weather respects no national border," the NMSC official said.
</P>
<P>
He said most countries in the Asia-Pacific Region can get
access to data sent back from the Fengyun 2 weather satellite,
which is in a geostationary orbit over 105 degrees east longitude.
</P>
<P>
According to the official, the service life span of the current
Fengyun 2 weather satellite is three years. Before 2000, another
Fengyun 2 series satellite will be launched to sustain
meteorological data.
</P>
<P>
At present, a few countries and regions -- including the
United States, Russia, the European Union and China -- are able
to develop and launch weather satellites.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0273 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> China to Launch Fourth Weather Satellite (2) </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
Experts say that weather satellites provide information to help
forecast such disasters as typhoons and rainstorms, to monitor
forest fires, and to estimate crop harvests.
</P>
<P>
An appraisal given by a group of scientists from the Chinese
Academy of Sciences last month spoke highly of the core
device of the Fengyun 2 weather satellite -- the multi-channel
scanning radiometer developed by the Shanghai Institute of
Technical Physics.
</P>
<P>
With high resolution, precision and reliability, the device
was a major breakthrough by China in its remote sensing
technology, the scientists said.
</P>
<P>
According to the scientists, both infrared and visible light
pictures sent back by the Fengyun 2 are of the same quality as
that made by other weather satellites.
</P>
<P>
As to the Fengyun 2 series weather satellite China plans to
launch before the year 2000, director Le Xiuhai of the Shanghai
Institute of Technical Physics said his institute has the
confidence to provide even better radiometers, so that China
and other countries can get better meteorological services.
 
</P>
</TEXT>
