<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0274 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Experts: "East Asian Miracle" Not Over </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The East Asian financial crisis
will affect the region's economic growth in the next few years,
but the "East Asian Miracle" is not over because the economic
fundamentals for steady growth have not been undermined by the
crisis, experts said Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Speaking at a press conference here at the end of an Asian
Development Forum (ADF) plenary session, Joseph Stiglitz, senior
vice president of the World Bank, said there have been remarkable
increases in per capita income and literacy and reduction in
poverty in East Asia in the past three decades.
</P>
<P>
"These are all the changes that are not going to be undermined
by the current turmoil," he said.
</P>
<P>
The region's growth is likely to slow down, but the overall
reasons for growth may be long-lasting, he said.
</P>
<P>
Stiglitz cited enormous increases in human capital, high
savings rates and marcroeconomic stability in East Asia as the
sound fundamentals for the long-term economic growth.
</P>
<P>
"The fundamentals should serve East Asia well into the coming
years as soon as the crisis gets over," he said.
</P>
<P>
In an earlier speech, Stiglitz blamed the poor management of
the financial sector, the huge short-term debts owed by the
private sector and high lendings to property sectors for the
outbreak of the Asian crisis last July.
</P>
<P>
He urged East Asian governments to maintain the strength of
their economies and political and economic stability to bolster
investors' confidence, which he said is important for the region
to end the crisis.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Peter Sullivan, vice president of the Asian
Development Bank (ADB), said in a report circulated at the meeting
that the East Asian miracle is not over and the long-term economic
outlook for the region is positive.
</P>
<P>
He said economic fundamentals that contributed to extraordinary
growth during the last 30 years are still in place and they
include a solid workforce, good macroeconomy and openness to
global markets.
</P>
<P>
"Looking forward next 30 years, we are projecting that East
Asia and South Asia will continue to grow, though the growth rate
of East Asian countries is unlikely to reach annually 7 percent as
it was," he said.
</P>
<P>
Referring to the cause of the current crisis, Sullivan said one
strain is insufficient development of the financial sector,
regulation and supervision.
</P>
<P>
"With massive investment from abroad, Asian countries have not
been matched to such sophisticated investment," he said.
</P>
<P>
He said another strain is the downturn of trade compounded by a
downturn of global demand, which made Asian countries less
competitive.
</P>
<P>
The week-long conference is jointly organized by the ADB and
the World Bank to discuss lessons of the Asian crisis and Asia's
future development strategies. The meeting will end on Thursday
evening. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0275 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Roundup:India's PM Candidate Fails to Prove Support to </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
NEW DELHI, March 12 (Xinhua) -- With the Tamil Nadu allies
failing to forward their letters of support for a Bharatiya Janata
Party (BJP) led government till late Wednesday evening, BJP prime
ministerial candidate Atal Behari Vajpayee could not keep his
promise to present his documentary proof of support to President
K. R. Narayanan on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
In his letter to Vajpayee on Tuesday, the president asked him
whether his party, which has emerged the largest party in the just
concluded general elections, was "able and willing" to form a
"stable government".
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee called on the president Tuesday evening and claimed to
be able to form a stable government. Then the president asked him
to present a documentary proof of his support and Vajpayee
promised to do so on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Vajpayee and other BJP leaders were stumped by the seemingly
inexplicable delay of support from Tamil Nadu and were forced to
postpone an appointment with the president from Wednesday to
Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The delay on the part of the Tamil Nadu allies has triggered
speculation in political circles here that Ms Jayalalitha, leader
of the allies in the State, was out to drive a hard bargain in
respect of her one-point demand: dismissal of the Dravida Munnetra
Kazhagam (DMK) government in the State.
</P>
<P>
All-India Anna Dravida Munnetra Kazhagam (AIADMK) supremo
Jayalalitha Wednesday thrust a spanner in the works of the BJP by
demanding the scalp of the Karunanidhi government in lieu of her
support to Vajpayee's bid to form the next government at the
Center.
</P>
<P>
She has also prevailed upon her allies in the State not to give
support to Vajpayee till the time her demand to dismiss the State
government is conceded.
</P>
<P>
In addition to this demand, Jayalalitha is learnt to be
insisting on the inclusion of a couple of her nominees in the
Union Cabinet, about whom the BJP has grave reservations. On its
part, the BJP has so far refused to give a commitment to sack the
Karunanidhi government.
</P>
<P>
In his meeting with the president Tuesday evening, Vajpayee had
claimed the support of 252 out of 543 MPs in the Lower House of
Parliament. Jayalalitha commands the allegiance of 27 MPs.
</P>
<P>
President Narayanan, who has the reputation of being a man who
goes by the "rule-book", is unlikely to initiate any further
action on the formation of the new government till he is fully
satisfied on the basis of documentary proof that the coalition
Government to be formed by Vajpayee would be a stable one.
</P>
<P>
Apart from the documentary proof of support from the allies,
the president is likely to expect a written reply from Vajpayee to
his letter sent on Tuesday in which the president had specifically
asked Vajpayee whether "he would be able and willing to form a
stable government which could secure the confidence of the House."
 
</P>
</TEXT>
