<HEADLINE> Yugoslav Envoy Announces Level of Autonomy for Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ZAGREB, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Yugoslav ambassador to Croatia,
Veljko Knezevic, said Kosovo would be given a certain level of
autonomy, but not "as it had under the previous constitution."
</P>
<P>
Under the 1974 constitution of the former Yugoslavia, Kosovo
had the status of a federal unit, as well as the status of a
former Yugoslav republic.
</P>
<P>
Serbia cancelled Kosovo's autonomy in 1989 because the Albanian
separatists constituted the illegal "Kosovo Republic" and the
"Kosovo Liberation Army," which targeted the Yugoslav government.
</P>
<P>
Speaking to reporters here Wednesday, Knezevic said that at a
meeting in Belgrade on Tuesday, the Yugoslav government rejected
attempts to internationalize the Kosovo issue, because that would
mean meddling in the country's internal affairs.
</P>
<P>
Knezevic reiterated the stance of the Yugoslav government that
the actions of Serbian police in Kosovo had been directed
exclusively at ethnic Albanian terrorists.
</P>
<P>
Knezevic said there is no reason for the Kosovo crisis to
affect relations between Croatia and Serbia. 
</P>
</TEXT>
