<HEADLINE> Danish Ruling Center-Left Wins Parliamentary Election </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
STOCKHOLM, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Boosted by a strong economy
and low unemployment, Denmark's center-left ruling coalition won
the parliamentary election Wednesday, with one seat more than the
opposition center-right bloc, official figures show.
</P>
<P>
With 99.5 percent of the votes counted, the ruling coalition of
social democrats, radicals and their political allies were
credited with a slim majority of 90 seats in the 179-seat
parliament.
</P>
<P>
The opposition bloc, consisting mostly of conservatives and
liberal parties, was a single seat behind at 89.
</P>
<P>
Political observers said the ruling coalition "would continue
in power," but will face a tough time given the narrow victory.
