<HEADLINE> Ukraine's Foreign Debts Increase </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
KIEV, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Ukraine's foreign debt increased
sharply this year to 9.559 billion U.S. dollars, and looks set to
keep rising, reported Ukrainian Interfax news agency.
</P>
<P>
Foreign debt totalled eight billion dollars in 1996, but the
figure climbed to 8.65 billion in 1997.
</P>
<P>
The Ukrainian Finance Ministry put Ukraine's debts to Russia at
over two billion dollars, to Turkmenistan at 0.563 billion and the
Commonwealth of Independent States (CIS) at 2.564 billion.
</P>
<P>
Ukraine also owed the World Bank 1.216 billion dollars in
arrears, the International Monetary Fund (IMF) 2.386 billion and
the European Union 0.352 billion.
</P>
<P>
Ukrainian debt to the United States, Germany and Japan
respectively stood at 0.476 billion, 0.473 billion and 0.188
billion dollars.
</P>
<P>
Since its breakaway from former Soviet Union six years ago, the
Ukraine economy has declined and government spending has been
tightly controlled. Experts predict its foreign debt would
continue to increase over the next couple of years. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
