<HEADLINE> Thailand Works Out Plan for Industrial Adjustment </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The National Industrial
Development Committee of Thailand has finalized a structural
adjustment plan for industrial sectors, the Nation newspaper
reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Enhancing competitiveness of Thai products on the global market
is the foremost objective of the five-year action plan, according
to Somphob Amatayakul, head of the sub-committee tasked with
producing structural adjustment action plans.
</P>
<P>
Measures under the plan include improving technology,
increasing skilled labor, developing small and medium-sized
industries as important bases for large industrial developments,
decentralizing labor-intensive industries to rural areas and
environmental protection management for all of the sectors,
Somphob said.
</P>
<P>
The committee has been granted 1.2 billion U.S. dollars to
carry out the action plan in 13 sectors of food, textile,
automobile and parts, electrical and electronics, ceramics and
glass, rubber, footwear and leather, drugs and chemicals, gems and
jewellery, wood and furniture, plastics, petrochemicals and steel.
</P>
<P>
Thailand received a loan package from the World Bank and the
Asian Development Bank for the structural adjustment plan after
experiencing difficulties resulting from the shrinking industrial
sector.
</P>
<P>
The plan will be submitted for cabinet approval next week.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
