<HEADLINE> Sri Lanka Swear In First Jaffna Mayor Since 1984 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
COLOMBO, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Sarojini Yogeswaram, a member of
the Tamil United Liberation Front (TULF) was sworn in on Wednesday
as the first mayor of former Tamil rebel northern strong-hold
Jaffna since 1984.
</P>
<P>
According to the Island newspaper Thursday, Sarojini, whose
husband represented Jaffna city in the country's parliament from
1977 to 1983, took her oaths before the city's acting magistrate.
</P>
<P>
Eight other TULF members and a member of the Eelam People's
Revolutionary Liberation Front (EPRLF) were then sworn in by the
new Jaffna mayor, the paper said.
</P>
<P>
Sarojini's husband Vettival Yogeswaram was killed along with
TULF leader Appathurai Amirathalingham in Colombo in 1990 in an
attack blamed on Tamil rebels.
</P>
<P>
She has been a TULF member for several years but has not held
any office until now.
</P>
<P>
Local government elections in Jaffna city were held for the
first time in more than a decade in January this year, marking the
first step to restore a civilian administration in Jaffna city.
</P>
<P>
Jaffna Peninsula in northern Sri Lanka was captured by
government troops from the Tamil rebels in May, 1996 and has since
been under military control.
</P>
<P>
The Tamil rebels have been fighting for a separate state for
minority Tamils in Sri Lanka's north and east in a war which began
in 1983. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
