<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Qian Qichen on Sino-British Relations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Vice-Premier and Foreign Minister
Qian Qichen said here today that with the resettlement of the Hong
Kong issue and scheduled exchange of visits by senior government
leaders, Sino-British relations will witness greater development
in 1998.
</P>
<P>
Qian made these remarks at a press conference in response to a
question by a reporter from the Hong Kong Special Administrative
Region (SAR).
</P>
<P>
"Hong Kong used to be a problem between China and Britain left
over by history. The two countries once fought war over Hong Kong,
and also had conflicts and disputes over the Hong Kong issue,"
noted Qian.
</P>
<P>
However, he said, this 150-year-plus history has already become
by-gones with Hong Kong's return to its motherland, which was
recognized by the British government.
</P>
<P>
"With the resolution of this question left over from the past,
the relations between the two major powers of China and Britain
will surely enjoy greater growth in all areas," he said.
</P>
<P>
He further noted that British Foreign Secretary Robin Cook has
already paid a visit to China, and British Prime Minister Tony
Blair is also going to visit China later this year.
</P>
<P>
Moreover, he added, the Chinese premier will attend the second
Asia-Europe Meeting (ASEM) scheduled to be held in London in
April, and also visit Britain.
</P>
<P>
"So I believe this year will witness greater development in
Sino-British relations," Qian said. 
</P>
