<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chinese Foreign Minister on Taiwan Issue </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
March 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Foreign Minister Qian Qichen said
that conditions are ripe to hold cross-Straits political
negotiations under the principle of "one China".
</P>
<P>
Qian made the remark at a press conference hosted by the
ongoing session of the Ninth National People's Congress here
today.
</P>
<P>
He said that negotiations should be held in accordance with the
principle of "one China". In this way can Taiwan compatriots'
desire to seek peace and security be satisfied, he said.
</P>
<P>
Qian said that a step-by-step approach can be adopted before
further talks are held. And the first step is to end hostilities
across the Taiwan Straits, he said.
</P>
<P>
It is reasonable to hold procedural talks to discuss the name,
form and ways of negotiations, he said, adding that all kinds of
matters can be discussed.
</P>
<P>
According to previous experiences, there were political
obstacles when business talks were held, he said
</P>
<P>
Qian said he welcomes the expansion of cross-Straits exchanges,
including exchanges between the Association for Relations
Across the Taiwan Straits and Straits Exchange Foundation.
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan issue used to be a very clear one but it has become
complicated now, he said, adding that he does not understand why
Taiwan is afraid of talking about "one China".
</P>
<P>
The Taiwan authorities used to adhere to "one China" but now
they have backed down from that position, he said.
</P>
<P>
It is totally unnecessary to be afraid of talking about "one
China," he said. Both sides should recognize that there is one
China in the world before the reunification, that Taiwan is part
of China, and that China's territory and sovereignty cannot be
separated, he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0296 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
