<HEADLINE> Taiwan's Activities in Southeast Asian Financial Crisis Criticized </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Chinese Vice-Premier and Foreign
Minister Qian Qichen said here today that Taiwan's activities
during the Southeast Asian financial crisis will produce no good
results.
</P>
<P>
Addressing a press conference given today hosted by the First
Session of the Ninth National People's Congress, he noted that the
financial crisis started from Southeast Asia last July and later spread to
many countries.
</P>
<P>
Last October, he recalled, Taiwan announced all of sudden the
devaluation of the New Taiwan Dollar by 10 percent, thus leading
to another round of devaluation. Actually, Taiwan added fuel to
the flame of the southeast Asian financial crisis, Qian said.
</P>
<P>
It should be noted that senior Taiwan officials repeatly
mentioned that the Chinese RMB would soon be devaluated. After
that, Taiwan officials traveled to many countries in the region on
many occasions in an attempt to benefit from these countries'
difficult situation and seek their political ulterior motives, he
said.
</P>
<P>
"So I think the activities of Taiwan harbor evil intentions and
i don't think they will produce any good results," Qian said.  
</P>
</TEXT>
