<HEADLINE> Pinochet Takes Oath as Lifetime Senator </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
SANTIAGO, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Former Chief Commander of Chile,
General Augusto Pinochet, took an oath of office as the country's
lifetime senator on Wednesday, forming a new national congress
with another 149 lawmakers.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet's decision to become a legislator triggered protests
around the country. About 6,000 protesters gathered before the
congress located in the Pacific city Valparaiso.
</P>
<P>
Police have arrested about 170 demonstrators in the capital
Santiago.
</P>
<P>
The 82-year-old Pinochet stepped down as the army chief on
Tuesday and transferred power to three-star General Ricardo
Izurieta at a ceremony attended by President Eduardo Frei.
</P>
<P>
Pinochet headed the coup d'etat on September 11, 1973, which
ousted President Salvador Allende. He then held the Chilean
presidency from 1974 to 1990 when he restored a civil government .
</P>
<P>
The Chilean National Congress consists of 120 elected
representatives, 38 elected senators, nine appointed senators and
a lifetime senator.
</P>
<P>
Christian-Democrat Senator Andres Zaldivar Larrain was elected
as the new president of the upper house and Mario Rios from
National Renovation as the vice president.
</P>
<P>
Another Christian-Democrat Gutenberg Martinez was re-elected
president of the lower house. 
</P>
</TEXT>
