<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0302 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> More Trees to Be Planted This Spring </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- South China is greener this
spring after large areas were planted with seedlings, reported
today's China Daily.
</P>
<P>
Eight provinces and autonomous regions in south China have
completed soil preparation on more than one million
hectares. Trees have been planted on 734,000 hectares, up 84
percent from the same period of last year, said the State
Forestry Bureau, transformed from the former Ministry of Forestry
in the government's institutional restructure.
</P>
<P>
Shaanxi, Shanxi and Zhejiang provinces and the Tibet Autonomous
Region took action last autumn and winter to urge strengthened
afforestation work.
</P>
<P>
To employ more science and technology in tree planting, Hubei
Province raised seedlings of advanced species on more than 4,000
hectares. They are expected to occupy the market, which used to
be filled with fake and inferior seeds.
</P>
<P>
This year's national spring afforestation has started, although
more places in northern China such as Beijing will begin tree
planting in April.
</P>
<P>
In the past two decades, each year witnessed a growth of 5.3
million hectares of trees. Statistics indicate that 90 percent of
the trees are well preserved. It is reported that 2.4 billion
trees were planted each year.
</P>
<P>
China is home to 33.3 million hectares of human-planted trees,
by far the most in the world. There are 137 million hectares of
forested land at present, compared with 115 million hectares at
the beginning of the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
With a forest coverage rate of 13.9 percent, China is striving
to reach a goal of 15.5 percent by the end of 2000.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
