<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0305 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Mussolini's Fiat Auctioned in Geneva </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 11 (Xinhua) -- The 1944 Fiat sport car, in which
the Italian fascist dictator Benito Mussolini and his lover
Claretta Petacci tried to escape from Italy, was sold Wednesday
for 156,000 Swiss Francs (about 105,000 U.S. dollars) at Brooks
vintage car auction in Geneva.
</P>
<P>
As auctioneers put it, the black, two-door, seven-meter-long
plush Fiat 2800 was "unique." Besides representing "a page in
Italian history," it was one of only three Fiat 2800s in the world
built by Tourism of Milan.
</P>
<P>
The two others, which have been lost without a trace, belonged
to Italy's exiled King Humbert II and the Spanish Royal House
respectively, they said.
</P>
<P>
In April, 1945, Mussolini and Claretta were caught in the car
when they tried to flee Italy. The Fiat, regarded as a symbol of
fascism, was dumped in Lake Como. However, it was eventually
hauled out and smuggled to Switzerland.
</P>
<P>
After many years and several owners, it became the property of
a wealthy Swiss family in 1950 and was completely restored in 1980.
</P>
<P>
The names of the Swiss family and the buyer were not revealed
at the auction.
</P>
<P>
The auctioneers said the Fiat, with a red-leather interior and
weighing 2,300 kilos, can travel at a maximum speed of 140
kilometers per hour. And the car has traveled less than 1,000
kilometers, they added.
</P>
<P>
Other vintage cars for auction included a 1938 Chrysler
Imperial C-19, a 1938 Bugatti, a 1919 Ford Tudor sedan, a 1933
Rolls Royce Phantom and a 1912 Bispano-Suiza. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
