JAKARTA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Japanese Prime Minister Ryutaro
Hashimoto is scheduled to arrive here Saturday evening for a
two-day working visit, an official of the Japanese embassy in
Jakarta told Xinhua Thursday.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto is believed to bridge a dispute between the
International Monetary Fund (IMF) and President Soeharto over the
latter's plan to peg the rupiah (national currency) at a fixed
rate to the U.S. dollar under a currency board system (CBS).
</P>
<P>
"The two leaders are expected to focus their discussion on the
current economic crisis in the region, especially in Indonesia,
and on what Japan can do to help our country," the local English
newspaper "the Jakarta Post" also quoted a senior official here,
who spoke on condition of anonymity, as saying.
</P>
<P>
Hashimoto's office announced earlier in Tokyo that the Prime
Minister would hold bilateral talks with President Soeharto on
Sunday and would leave Jakarta after the meeting.
</P>
<P>
He will be the first foreign leader to meet with Soeharto after
the president's reelection on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
Japan is Indonesia's largest trading partner and creditor and
has pledged 5 billion U.S. dollars to support the 43 billion U.S.
dollars IMF rescue package for Jakarta.
</P>
<P>
Last Saturday, the IMF delayed its promised 3 billion U.S.
dollars to Indonesia because of the so-called lack of reforms in
the country. Meanwhile, the World Bank and the Asian Development
Bank (ADB) also delayed their loans to Indonesia.  
</P>
</TEXT>
