<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Thailand Expects to Attract More Tourists From U.S. </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BANGKOK, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Tourism Authority of Thailand
(TAT) is looking forward to more visitors from the United States
when tourists from Southeast Asia declined drastically, a leading
English newspaper reported Thursday.
</P>
<P>
In 1997, about 311,000 Americans visited Thailand, making up
less than 5 percent of the total arrivals. But in January this
year, U.S. visitors to Thailand increased by 4.23 percent to
35,582 compared to the same month a year earlier.
</P>
<P>
In view of more potential in the U.S. market, the TAT is
switching gear to suit the market demand, the Bangkok Post quoted
a TAT senior official as saying.
</P>
<P>
The TAT will offer promotional inland air fares, including four
stops for less than 200 U.S. dollars.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, the authority is making conscious efforts to keep
tourists in Thailand rather than to share them with other
countries of the Association of Southeast Asian Nations.
</P>
<P>
To those who want to stay in Thailand, the TAT will give
discount coupons, promoting walking tours and working with Thai
Airways for special fares around the country, said the official,
who is in charge of North American east coast market.
</P>
<P>
"With the depreciation of the baht and last year's inflation
rate of only 8 percent, Thailand still represents the most
remarkable value for the leisure and business travelers," he
added. 
</P>
</TEXT>
