<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Manila Raises Minimum Bank Capitalization </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
MANILA, March 12 (Xinhua) -- The Philippine Central Bank has
approved a new round of increase in the minimum capitalization
requirement for banks ranging from 22 percent to a high of 75
percent, a leading newspaper reported on Thursday.
</P>
<P>
The central bank also approved accelerating the 2 percent
general loan loss reserve provisioning with full implementation by
October 1, 1999, the Manila Bulletin reported.
</P>
<P>
Central bank governor Gabriel Singson said in a statement
released late Wednesday night that the increase in the
capitalization depends on the classification of the bank.
</P>
<P>
For the expanded commercial banks, the minimum capital base has
been jacked up by 57 percent to 5.5 billion pesos (137.5 million
U.S. dollars) from the existing requirement of 3.5 billion pesos
(87.5 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
On the other hand, the ordinary commercial banks'
capitalization was almost doubled to 3 billion pesos (75 million
dollars) from the current requirement of 1.625 billion pesos
(40.625 million dollars).
</P>
<P>
The deadline for compliance with the new capitalization
requirements has been set for December 31, 2000, Singson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
