<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Italy Urges Kosovo Albanians to End Violence </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
ROME, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Italian Foreign Minister Lamberto
Dini Wednesday urged ethnic Albanians in Yugoslavia's province of
Kosovo to end violence and enter into dialogue with Belgrade.
</P>
<P>
Dini said that the Kosovo Albanians and Belgrade, the two sides
involved in the conflict, must immediately stop violence, in which
about 80 people have been killed.
</P>
<P>
The Albanians in Kosovo "must choose the way of dialogue" to
attain the degree of autonomy, he said.
</P>
<P>
Italy greatly regrets what happened in the past weeks in
Kosovo, Dini said.
</P>
<P>
Italy and other countries are making efforts to bring the two
sides to the negotiating table, he added.
</P>
<P>
On the outcome of the London meeting of the six-nation Contact
Group for the former Yugoslavia Monday, Dini said that the
fundamental request advanced by the group was to convince Belgrade
to talks.
</P>
<P>
"I think we are moving in the hoped-for direction, " he said.
</P>
<P>
Italian Prime Minister Romano Prodi told parliament Wednesday
that the Italian ambassador to Yugoslavia has been instructed to
talk Belgrade and the Kosovo Albanians into dialogue.
</P>
<P>
The ambassador is in contact with the Albanians in the province
to work for "a clear signal of the will to seek out a way to
negotiations with Belgrade," Prodi said.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Italian Foreign Undersecretary Piero Fassino said
Monday that an explosion of the crisis in Kosovo could have
serious consequences on the political balance in the Balkans.
</P>
<P>
Fassino said the Contact Group, comprising the United States,
Britain, France, Italy, Germany and Russia, will meet again on
March 25 to discuss the situation in Kosovo. 
</P>
</TEXT>
