<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Chernomyrdin Says Yeltsin, Clinton May Meet at Mid-year </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Visiting Russian Prime
Minister Viktor Chernomyrdin said on Wednesday that U.S. President
Bill Clinton and Russian President Boris Yeltsin may hold a summit
by the middle of this year.
</P>
<P>
"I am convinced that this meeting will take place and... this
should set forth the trend of our bilateral relationship,"
Chernomyrdin said at a joint news conference with U.S. Vice
President Al Gore at the White House.
</P>
<P>
"We hope that this summit will occur this year, not later but
in the middle of the year," said Chernomyrdin. But the exact
date and venue have not been fixed.
</P>
<P>
Part of the purpose of the Russian prime minister's visit was
to work on setting an agenda for a meeting between Clinton and
Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
Chernomyrdin met Clinton at the White House Wednesday
afternoon. One of the issues they focused is next Russian-U.S.
summit.
</P>
<P>
"This is quite clear that we've been developing the necessary
materials to introduce in the agenda of the presidential summit,"
Chernomyrdin said. "We are preparing strategic issues to them,
which basically will be carried out in the 21st century."
</P>
<P>
"To do that, we need to address some questions," said the
Russian prime minister through an interpreter, indicating that
Russia's Duma, the parliament, needs to ratify the START II treaty
before the summit. 
</P>
</TEXT>
