<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Highlights of Major Beijing-based Newspapers </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
BEIJING, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Highlights of today's major
Beijing-based Newspapers:
</P>
<P>
 "People's Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- The Presidium of the First Session of the Ninth National
Committee of the Chinese People's Political Consultative
Conference (CPPCC), China's top advisory body, held its third
meeting yesterday.
</P>
<P>
The meeting approved an electoral method for the current CPPCC
session, as well as a candidates' list and a list of scrutineers
and scrutineers-general.
</P>
<P>
-- President Jiang Zemin lauded Chongqing for its good
beginning since its municipality was approved a year ago at the
NPC, the top legislature, as China's four municipality after
Beijing, Shanghai and Xinjiang.
</P>
<P>
In a panel discussion with deputies from Chongqing to the
current NPC session, which opened last Thursady, Jiang noted that
Chongqing has achieved smooth transition in administrative
divisions and the new structure as a municipality has embarked on
the track of normal operation.
</P>
<P>
-- A reception was held at the Great Hall of the People
yesterday evening for ethnic minority deputies to the Ninth
People's Congress (NPC) and the members of the Ninth National
Committee of the CPPCC, both in session here since last week.
</P>
<P>
Chinese leaders Jiang Zemin, Li Peng, Qiao Shi, Li Ruihuan, Hu
Jintao, Wei Jianxing and Li Lanqing were present at the reception.
</P>
<P>
"Xinhua Daily Telegraph"
</P>
<P>
-- Chinese Premier Li Peng yesterday urged Inner Mongolia
Autonomous Region to turn its rich natural resources into economic
strength and narrow its economic disparity with coastal areas by
accelerating the pace of economic development.
</P>
<P>
"Inner Mongolia is rich in coal and other mineral resources,
and it has good conditions for developing agriculture and
livestock breeding," he said in a group discussion attended by
Inner Mongolia deputies to the NPC.
</P>
<P>
-- Premier Li Peng said that China's policy of reform and
opening-up will remain unchanged despite some negative impact
brought to it by the southeast Asian financial crisis.
</P>
<P>
During a panel discussion with deputies to the Ninth NPC from
eastern Fujian Province, Li noted that the southeast Asian
financial crisis has affected many countries and may bring some
negative impact on China's economic growth, but the country's
policy of reform and opening-up will remain unchanged.
</P>
<P>
-- The Association for Relations Across the Taiwan Strait
(ARATS) will further expand exchanges programs with its Taiwan
counterpart by inviting Taiwan delegations to the mainland.
</P>
<P>
 "China Daily"
</P>
<P>
-- A group of top Chinese managers are ruling out privatization
as a remedy for the state-owned enterprises troubled by poor
business performance.
</P>
<P>
Privatization has been proposed by many Western economists who
believe it will provide inventives to bosses, subsequently
reducing corruption by senior management.
</P>
<P>
-- China has agreed that the certificate of ID card issued by
the Macao-Portuguese government to Macao residents will remain
effective until October 19, 2001.
</P>
<P>
-- Both the United States and China should be more flexible
when discussing China's entry into the World Trade Organization,
says China's foreign trade minister.
</P>
<P>
Bilateral trade talks have entered a critical phase and should
be brought to an end as soon as possible, Wu Yi told US deputy
Trade Representative Richard Fisher in Beijing yesterday. 
</P>
</TEXT>
