<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0347 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Xinhua World News Summary at 0100 GMT, March 12 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
TIRANA -- British Foreign Office Minister of State Tony Lloyd
made a flash visit to Albania Wednesday on Kosovo business.
</P>
<P>
Lloyd briefed Albanian Foreign Minister Paskal Milo on Monday's
emergency meeting in London of the Contact Group on former
Yugoslavia.
</P>
<P>
In a joint statement after the London meeting, the Contact
Group, comprising the United States, Russia, Britain, France,
Germany and Italy, asked the United Nations Security Council for
an arms embargo against Yugoslavia, and called for a peaceful
solution to the troubles through dialogue. (Albania-Britain-Kosovo)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
WASHINGTON -- U.S. President Bill Clinton has exempted Vietnam
from a Cold War law that restricts trade because of limit
emigration, the White House said on Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
"The president based his decision on Vietnam's track record of
progress on emigration over the past 15 years and its accelerated
efforts in recent months," the White House said in a statement.
</P>
<P>
U.S. officials said on Tuesday that Clinton signed a waiver to
the so-called Jackson-Vanik amendment, which prevents the
U.S. government from giving trade and investment funding to
nations that do not allow their citizens to emigrate or travel
abroad freely.
</P>
<P>
Clinton's decision will make Vietnam eligible for financial
backing from the U.S. Export-Import Bank and the Overseas Private
Investment Corp, but does not grant it the Most Favored Nation
trade status. (US-Vietnam-Trade Waiver)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
BAGHDAD -- A mass funeral was held here Wednesday for 40
children who have died for lack of medicine and foodstuffs due to
the U.N. sanctions imposed on Iraq for its invasion of Kuwait in
1990.
</P>
<P>
Saltan al-Shawy, chairman of the Iraqi child support society,
was quoted by the Iraqi news agency as saying that the embargo has
led to the death of 1.3 million Iraqi children.
</P>
<P>
He held the U.S. administration responsible for the death of
the children on account of its determination to maintain the
unjustified sanctions on the Iraqi people.
</P>
<P>
Al-Shawy described the continuing embargo as a collective
annihilation crime against the children and people of Iraq.
(Iraq-Funeral)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
MOSCOW -- Russia is ready to build a nuclear power plant in
Bushehr, Iran, despite Ukraine's refusal to supply turbine, the
Russian Ministry for Atomic Energy said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
According to the Interfax news agency, Minister for Atomic
Energy Yevgeny Adamov had talks with visiting Vice President of
the Iranian Organization for Nuclear Energy Asadullah Saburi and
they agreed that Ukraine's refusal to participate in the project
"will not exert any serious influence on the construction of the
first unit in Bushehr."
</P>
<P>
Adamov's spokesman Georgy Kaurov cited Adamov as saying that if
Ukraine does not supply the turbine, similar equipment will be
provided by Russian enterprises.
</P>
<P>
A contract worth 800 million U.S. dollars for building the
first unit of the Bushehr nuclear power plant was signed by Russia
and Iran on January 8, 1995. (Russia-Iran-Nuclear)
</P>
<P>
- - - -
</P>
<P>
LONDON -- The British government Wednesday defended a European
Union decision not to sponsor a resolution at the United Nations
critical of China's human rights record.
</P>
<P>
Prime Minister Tony Blair said in parliament that he did not
think a United Nations resolution was "the right way to proceed,"
but his government would keep raising the issue.
</P>
<P>
It is the first time in nine years that Britain, the current EU
president, has not signed the resolution.
</P>
<P>
The 15-member EU has decided recently not to table a resolution
at the U.N.'s Commission on Human Rights meeting in Geneva this
year, saying dialogue is better than confrontation with China
concerning the human rights issue. (EU Decision-China) 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
