<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China City Building More Homes for Elderly </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 12 (Xinhua) -- There has been a
growing number of homes for the elderly in Guangzhou,
capital of south China's Guangdong Province.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou has over 700,000 people above the age of 60, or
nearly 20 percent of the city's population. More of the elderly
are choosing to live in homes for the elderly, where they can
receive proper care and make friends with other old people.
</P>
<P>
A city government official says that the government manages
seven homes for the lederly, with 2,000 beds, and these facilities
cannot meet the needs.
</P>
<P>
Some homes for the elderly are being built at a lower cost and
with more flexible management to provide better service. Homes for
the elderly have been built on 87 percent of Guangzhou's streets.
</P>
<P>
They are available at a reasonable cost and are even free to
those who are unable to pay for the accommodation.
</P>
<P>
Some individuals and enterprises are also building these
facilities, and Guangzhou has eleven privately-run homes for the
elderly.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
