<BODY>
<HEADLINE> South China City Giving Priority to Impoverished Unemployed </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
GUANGZHOU, March 12 (Xinhua) -- Over 500 unemployed workers
living in poverty in the city of Guangzhou, capital of south China's
Guangdong Province, have found jobs thanks to the help of the city
government.
</P>
<P>
The city government has established a service system for the
impoverished jobless, which will find a job for them within 10
days after an application is filled out.
</P>
<P>
The special service system operates for the following
people: males above 45 and females above 40 who are unemployed for
12 consecutive months; both husband and wife who lose their jobs,
or one is unemployed and the other is laid off for six consecutive
months.
</P>
<P>
Guangzhou's unemployment rate was 2.61 percent last year,
meaning 650,000 people out of work.
</P>
<P>
Because of economic changes, state-owned enterprises are
no longer able to provide sufficient jobs and the city government
has been encouraging the unemployed to look for work with
non-state-owned enterprises. The Labor Bureau says it will
guarantee all their social security.  
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
