<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Hold Talks With Annan </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 11 (Xinhua) -- U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan has held talks with President Bill Clinton and his foreign
policy team members, discussing a range of issues including Iraq,
the White House said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
The two sides also discussed U.S. arrears of payment to the
United Nations and the Middle East peace process.
</P>
<P>
"The president reiterated the administration's firm support for
U.N. dues, our arrears," a senior administration official told a
briefing after Clinton's talks with Annan.
</P>
<P>
He said President Clinton had reiterated his commitment to work
with Congress and the leadership of Congress "so that we can get
those appropriations made this year."
</P>
<P>
According to Article 19 of the U.N. Charter, any U.N. member
state which is in two years consecutive arrears may lose voting
rights in the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The U.S. debt to the United Nations at the end of 1997 was 1.3
billion dollars for regular dues and peacekeeping expenses. It is
rising to 1.7 billion dollars in 1998. If the United States does
not come up with the money it should pay to the United Nations by
the end of this calendar year, it will be two years in arrears in
total, above the threshold level that Article 19 sets. And
washington would lose its voting right in the General Assembly.
</P>
<P>
The senior official said Clinton had promised to Annan that he
would exert "his maximum efforts to get Congress to appropriate
those funds."
</P>
<P>
The issue of Iraq was the main topic that Annan discussed first
with Clinton, then with National Security Adviser Sandy Berger,
the senior administration official said.
</P>
<P>
The president and the secretary-general agreed on the need for
vigilance now in monitoring Iraqi compliance with the arrangement
that were made in the memorandum of understanding that the
secretary-general signed with Iraq Deputy Prime Minister Tariq
Aziz in Baghdad.
</P>
<P>
"There was agreement... that one week of successful inspections
and one week of Iraqi compliance is far from adding up to the kind
of sustained, long-term Iraqi compliance with the Security Council
resolutions and the memorandum of understanding," the senior
official said.
</P>
<P>
At a photo session before talks with Annan, Clinton said the
United States would consult with U.N. Security Council members
before resorting to force against Iraq if it failed to comply with
its agreement, reached with Annan, on weapons inspections.
</P>
<P>
But he insisted that the United States need not any approval
from the United Nations for any kind of attack on Iraq.
</P>
<P>
"We believe that the resolution gives us the authority to take
whatever actions are necessary but of course we would consult,"
Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
On the issue of the Middle East, Clinton and Annan discussed
briefly the need for movement forward in the Arab-Israeli peace
process, the senior official said.
</P>
<P>
"The president and Secretary of State (Madeleine) Albright, who
was also in the meeting, underscored our view that we cannot
continue without some movement forward on the peace process and
that the burden is on the leadership of the Israeli and
Palestinian authority to take the hard decisions necessary to move
this process forward," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0363 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canadians Make Record Visa Purchases in 1997 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Canadian consumers made a record
64.8 billion dollars (46 billion U.S. dollars) in purchases on
their Visa cards in 1997, Visa Canada said Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
That accounted for 12.2 percent of all purchases made by
Canadian consumers during the year, and was 12 percent higher than
the purchases on Canadian Visa cards in 1996.
</P>
<P>
Canada's most populous province Ontario accounted for 43
percent of the 1997 total, charging just over 27 billion dollars
on Visa cards, followed by British Columbia and Quebec with 11.7
billion and 9.9 billion dollars respectively.
</P>
<P>
Visa Canada President Derek Fry attributed this strong
performance to the strength of the Canadian economy, which grew
3.8 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
The successful expansion of Visa into non-traditional market
segments such as grocery, health care and government payments was
also a major factor. 
</P>
</TEXT>
