<HEADLINE> UK Gov't Urged to Ban Smoking in Public </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 11 (Xinhua) -- A scientific group Wednesday urged
the British government to ban smoking in public after finding that
passive smoking causes lung cancer and heart disease.
</P>
<P>
The Scientific Committee on Tobacco and Health said in a report
that long-term exposure to other people's smoke can cause lung
cancer and heart disease.
</P>
<P>
The report, published to coincide with National No Smoking Day,
is the first major study by a government committee on tobacco and
health for 10 years.
</P>
<P>
In the report, health experts called on ministers to curb
smoking in thousands of public places.
</P>
<P>
The report said there was "an importance and urgency with the
smoking problem that needs to be recognized by both the government
and the public."
</P>
<P>
Government Chief Medical Officer Kenneth Calman indicated that
curbs on public smoking may appear in a forthcoming White Paper.
</P>
<P>
"The message is absolutely clear. Passive smoking is bad for
your health.... From my own point of view, I think the case is very
strong," he told BBC Radio. 
</P>
</TEXT>
