<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> New Study Finds Hardcore Drug Users More Numerous </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 11 (Xinhua) -- New ways of counting show the
number of hardcore drug users in Chicago and surrounding Cook
County in Illionis is much higher than previous estimates, said
federal researchers.
</P>
<P>
The study, released Wednesday by Barry McCaffrey, director of
the White House Office of National Drug Control Policy, raises the
possibility that the conventional estimate of 13 million regular
drug users in the country at large is far too low.
</P>
<P>
The Cook County study estimates there are about 330,000
habitual users of cocaine, crack cocaine and heroin in the
urbanized county. Previous studies estimated the number of
residents using drugs other than marijuana at 117,000.
</P>
<P>
Calling the Chicago-area findings "unsettling," McCaffrey said
it raises questions about whether the national estimate of 13
million hardcore drug users should be larger. "I would lean in the
direction of saying yes," he said.
</P>
<P>
Hardcore use is defined as the use of heroin, powder cocaine or
crack cocaine on eight or more days during at least one of the
preceding eight months, the drug policy office said.
</P>
<P>
"Hardcore drug users maintain the illegal drug market,"
McCaffrey said, "and they provide a spring from which new
epidemics of drug use flow."
</P>
<P>
The Chicago-area research will be followed up, if Congress
approves, by surveys in other areas of the country, McCaffrey
said, emphasizing the need for accurate estimates of drug users.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0371 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Cook Not Optimistic About His Middle East Trip </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 11 (Xinhua) -- British Foreign Secretary Robin
Cook said Wednesday that he did not hope his Middle East trip next
week would achieve easy progress on the stalled peace process
there.
</P>
<P>
Cook, whose country now holds the current European Union (EU)
presidency, told a news conference, "I am by no means complacent
about the problem. I do not hold out any facile hopes of easy
progress."
</P>
<P>
"But I believe that if the international community does apply
intensive diplomatic pressure, then we will be able to get the
peace process moving again," he said.
</P>
<P>
The foreign secretary will visit Egypt, Jordan, the Palestinian
self-ruled territories, Israel, Syria and Lebanon from 15-18
March.
</P>
<P>
He will meet political leaders in each country, launching a new
EU drive to restart the Middle East peace process, which has been
stalled for almost a year.
</P>
<P>
Cook reiterated that the search for a way to reinvigorate the
Middle East peace process was one of the key foreign policy
priorities for the UK's EU presidency, which ends in June.
</P>
<P>
He said that during his visit, he would make it clear to
Israeli Prime Minister Netanyahu that he had to stick to the Oslo
peace framework which laid out the path to a final settlement.
</P>
<P>
"I'll go to Israel with the clear message that the Oslo accords
were signed by both parties.... Netanyahu has an international
legal obligation to make the agreements work."
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Cook said that he would also tell the Palestinians
that they had to take action to stop guerrilla attacks.
</P>
<P>
But he refused to point out what the EU would do if Israel and
the Palestinian authorities did not return to the negotiating
table.
</P>
<P>
"I don't want to spell out whether anything might be done if
there is no progress. I go in a sense of partnership, hoping to
achieve progress," he said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
