<HEADLINE> Britain Pledges to Press Ahead With EU-Cyprus Talks </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 11 (Xinhua) -- The British government, the
current European Union (EU) president, promised Wednesday that the
membership talks of Cyprus with the EU should proceed as planned.
</P>
<P>
Britain, which is to hold a one-day conference on EU
enlargement in London Thursday, made the statement amid reports
that the French government openly voiced doubts whether the
membership talks with Cyprus should go ahead as the two
communities in Cyprus failed to form a joint delegation for the
London conference.
</P>
<P>
A Downing Street spokesman said Wednesday, "The accession
process embraces Cyprus and the countries of eastern Europe. That
is what was agreed and that is what we will be pursuing."
</P>
<P>
The spokesman made it clear that the 15-nation bloc must press
ahead with the Cyprus membership talks even if the Turkish
Cypriots refuse to take part. The unrecognized Turkish state in
the north of the island could not have a veto over the issue, he
said.
</P>
<P>
British Prime Minister Tony Blair was expected to tell
Thursday's meeting that the door to eventual EU membership was not
closed, the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
Blair would also tell the potential members over dinner at 10
Downing Street Wednesday night that the process of joining the EU
would not be easy and would demand sacrifices, he added.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, Blair was also expected to urge Cyprus to ease
tension in the eastern Mediterranean by scrapping a controversial
deal to arm itself with Russian ground-to-air missiles.
</P>
<P>
The British government has earlier appealed to Cyprus to give
up its planned purchase and deployment of the S-300 missile
systems in southern Cyprus as the Turkish government threatened to
destroy the missiles if they are deployed. 
</P>
</TEXT>
