<HEADLINE> Two Men Charged With Murders in Northern Ireland </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 11 (Xinhua) -- A British court charged two men
Wednesday with the killing of a Protestant and a Catholic in a pub
in Northern Ireland last week.
</P>
<P>
But a detective told the magistrate in the town of Newry,
County Down in Northern Ireland, that the two accused men, Ryan
Robley, 28 and David Keys, 26, had denied killing Philip Allen, a
Protestant, and Damien Trainor, a Roman Catholic.
</P>
<P>
The victims, lifelong friends despite the sectarian divisions,
were killed on March 3 by gunmen who stormed into a Roman
Catholic-owned pub in the village of Poyntzpass and opened fire
before fleeing away.
</P>
<P>
The killings were part of a shooting spree by rival pro-British
Protestant and pro-Irish Catholic guerrilla groups that has
claimed a total of 15 lives since late December.
</P>
<P>
Meanwhile, two more men were charged with the murders of Allen
and Trainor, and they will appear in court at Banbridge, County
Down Thursday, police said. 
</P>
