<HEADLINE> Canada's Capacity Utilization Increases </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Canadian firms slightly increased
their rate of capacity use in the fourth quarter of 1997, closer
to the peak reached in 1988, said reports Wednesday.
</P>
<P>
Capacity utilization hit 85.6 percent in the quarter, up 0.3
percent and only 1.2 percent points below the 10-year record of
86.8 percent, according to the latest Statistics Canada figures.
</P>
<P>
Inflationary pressures develop when the economy approaches
capacity. However, there were few signs of rising prices.
</P>
<P>
"Despite these high rates, industry prices have remained
relatively stable for the past two years and labor costs have also
changed little over that period," the statistics agency was quoted
as saying.
</P>
<P>
The country's inflation was 1.1 percent in January. It is
forecast that Canada would have an inflation of 1 to 2 percent for
all of 1998, the reports said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
