<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0378 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Hong Kong Has Passed Test of Fire in Financial </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
PARIS, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Tung Chee Hwa, the chief executive
of the Hong Kong Special Administrative Region of China, said here
Wednesday that Hong Kong has "passed the test of fire" through the
financial crisis which devastated many Asian nations last year.
</P>
<P>
"Those with free markets, strong regulation, rule of law and
stringent fiscal discipline, such as Hong Kong and Singapore, have
passed the test of fire," said Tung in a speech addressed to the
French National Employers' Association CNPF.
</P>
<P>
He said that Hong Kong has a "low, consistent and simple tax
structure, an open and accountable government, and a clean and
corruption free civil service."
</P>
<P>
"Most importantly, we believe strongly in upholding the rule of
law," he said.
</P>
<P>
He also said that being an externally oriented economy, Hong
Kong needs certainty in exchange rates and will not abandon its
14-year-old currency board system which provides full U.S. dollar
backing for the Hong Kong dollar.
</P>
<P>
"In the recent round of attacks on the Hong Kong dollar, the
currency board system has proven to be most effective," he said.
</P>
<P>
Tung again stressed that Hong Kong does not need to devalue the
Hong Kong dollar, as it is not in the interests of Hong Kong to do
so. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0379 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Canada's Economy to Top G-7 in 1998 </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
OTTAWA, March 11 (Xinhua) -- Canada is set to outperform the
rest of the Group of Seven countries in economic growth this year,
according to the latest report by the Conference Board of Canada.
</P>
<P>
The pace of growth in Canada is expected to slow to 3.2 percent
this year after a 3.8-percent advance in 1997, the Ottawa-based
economic thinktank predicted.
</P>
<P>
The slowdown will happen because of a maturing business cycle,
Asian market weakness and higher interest rates, said Peter Lok,
the board's senior research associate.
</P>
<P>
The G-7 nations will collectively post gains in their gross
domestic product (GDP) of 2.1 percent in 1998, down sharply from
the 2.7 percent growth in 1997.
</P>
<P>
In 1999, Canada's GDP will slow further to 2.8 percent, but
that would still rank it second among the G-7 economies after
Italy's 2.9 percent.
</P>
<P>
"This depreciation will result from slower growth in the U.S.
economy and the impact of higher interest rates domestically," Lok
said.
</P>
<P>
The outlook for the G-7 as a whole in 1999 is for GDP growth to
moderate to 1.9 percent, the board said. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> XIE19980312.0380 </DOCNO>
<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Britain Urges Immediate Dialogue on Kosovo </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
LONDON, March 11 (Xinhua) -- The British government Wednesday
urged the Yugoslav government and ethnic Albanians in Kosovo to
start a political dialogue on resolving their disputes as soon as
possible.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that Kosovo ethnic Albanian leader Ibrahim
Rugova had earlier called for independence for the troubled
province, while Belgrade ruled out any reconciliation talks until
the demand of total independence was dropped.
</P>
<P>
Responding to the latest development of the Kosovo crisis, a
British Foreign Office source was quoted by Reuters as saying that
it was "vital that both sides should urgently begin dialogue
without preconditions."
</P>
<P>
The Foreign Office source noted that the six-nation Contact
Group, namely the United States, Russia, Britain, France,
Germany and Italy, was willing to act as intermediary if the
current stand-off is unable to ease off.
</P>
<P>
Under the joint statement issued after the one-day Contact
Group meeting held in London Monday, all the Contact Group members
made it clear that they do not support the ethnic Albanians'
demand for an independent Kosovo but urge the Belgrade government
to grant the province autonomy.
</P>
<P>
It was reported that some 80 people have been killed in recent
bloody clashes between Serbian police and the Kosovo Liberation
Army in Kosovo, where 90 percent of its population are ethnic
Albanians. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
