<DATE_TIME> 1998-03-12 </DATE_TIME>
<BODY>
<HEADLINE> Clinton Refuses to Comment on Testimony Negotiations </HEADLINE>
<TEXT>
<P>
WASHINGTON, March 11 (Xinhua) -- U.S. President Bill Clinton
Wednesday refused to comment on reports that his lawyers are
negotiating with independent counsel Kenneth Starr to provide
presidential testimony in the Monica Lewinsky investigation.
</P>
<P>
At a joint photo opportunity with U.N. Secretary-General Kofi
Annan, Clinton refused to take reporters' questions about any such
testimony.
</P>
<P>
"I am not going to talk about that today," Clinton said.
</P>
<P>
Annan was at the White House to brief Clinton on his recent
agreement with Iraqi President Saddam Hussein to let U.N.
inspectors search for weapons of mass destruction in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
The president told reporters, "I have got to do the work that
the people in this country hired me to do."
</P>
<P>
Earlier Wednesday, Jim Kennedy, spokesman for the White House
counsel's office, said no one at the White House will have any
comment on reported negotiations between Clinton's personal
lawyers and Starr's office.
</P>
<P>
Starr heads a grand jury investigation into allegations against
Clinton, including whether he had an affair with Lewinsky and then
urged her to lie about it under oath when providing an affidavit
in a separate suit.
</P>
<P>
Although there have been reports about the negotiations between
the two sides, Kennedy said, "We have made no announcement
regarding this issue.... We're just not having any comment."
</P>
<P>
Media reports said the president is willing to answer questions
about the Lewinsky matter, but only after the former White House
intern has testified before the grand jury.
</P>
<P>
However, negotiations between Starr's office and lawyers for
Lewinsky have broken down, and her appearance before the grand
jury has not yet been scheduled. 
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
</DOC>
